d":"/manual-6","page_id":"/manual","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual#carbon-is-made-of-modules","content":"The easiest way to picture Carbon: it's split into Modules — one for each part of your\nbusiness. Selling lives in Sales. Buying lives in Purchasing. Making things lives in\nProduction. And so on."},"483":{"id":"/manual-7","page_id":"/manual","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual#carbon-is-made-of-modules","content":"When you log in, you land on the home screen. Every tile here is a Module — click one to\nstart working in it."},"484":{"id":"/manual-8","page_id":"/manual","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual#carbon-is-made-of-modules","content":"Here's what each Module is for:"},"485":{"id":"/manual-9","page_id":"/manual","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual#carbon-is-made-of-modules","content":"type: info"},"486":{"id":"/manual-10","page_id":"/manual","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual#carbon-is-made-of-modules","content":"Don't memorize this. You'll learn each Module as you need it. The rest of this manual\nwalks through them one at a time, in the order you'd actually use them."},"487":{"id":"/manual-11","page_id":"/manual","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual#we-learn-with-a-real-company","content":"Every screenshot in this manual comes from Acme Inc., a real demo company that makes\nprecision metal parts for aerospace and defense customers. So what you see here is exactly\nwhat you'll see in the app."},"488":{"id":"/manual-12","page_id":"/manual","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual#find-your-topic","content":"type: info"},"489":{"id":"/manual-13","page_id":"/manual","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual#find-your-topic","content":"Looking for developer docs (the API, self-hosting)? Use the Developer Docs toggle at\nthe top of the sidebar."},"490":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","type":"page","content":"Carbon in 15 minutes","tags":[],"url":"/manual/walkthrough"},"491":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-0","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough","content":"Follow one real order from quote to cash — and see how Carbon's modules connect."},"492":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-1","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/walkthrough#step-1--quote-the-customer--sales-module","content":"Step 1 — Quote the customer · Sales module"},"493":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-2","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/walkthrough#step-2--take-the-order--sales-module","content":"Step 2 — Take the order · Sales module"},"494":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-3","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/walkthrough#step-3--how-its-made--items-module","content":"Step 3 — How it's made · Items module"},"495":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-4","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/walkthrough#step-4--make-it--production-module","content":"Step 4 — Make it · Production module"},"496":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-5","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/walkthrough#step-5--buy-the-steel--purchasing-module","content":"Step 5 — Buy the steel · Purchasing module"},"497":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-6","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/walkthrough#step-6--check-it-and-ship-it--quality--inventory","content":"Step 6 — Check it and ship it · Quality + Inventory"},"498":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-7","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/walkthrough#step-7--get-paid--accounting-module","content":"Step 7 — Get paid · Accounting module"},"499":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-8","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/walkthrough#thats-the-whole-loop","content":"That's the whole loop"},"500":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-9","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/walkthrough#go-deeper","content":"Go deeper"},"501":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-10","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough","content":"The fastest way to \"get\" Carbon is to follow one order through it. We'll track a single real\npart — a Counterweight Hook that Acme makes for Radiant Aerospace — from the first\nprice request to a paid invoice. You'll touch most of the Modules along the way."},"502":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-11","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough","content":"type: info"},"503":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-12","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough","content":"The part: the Counterweight Hook (part number CWH-A36-15) is a steel hook cut from\n1-inch plate. Radiant orders 500 at a time. You don't need to do anything here — just read."},"504":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-13","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough","content":"Here's the whole journey. Each step happens in a different Module, and Carbon links them all\ntogether automatically:"},"505":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-14","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough#step-1--quote-the-customer--sales-module","content":"Radiant asks \"what do 500 hooks cost?\" You answer with a quote. Open the Sales module,\ngo to Quotes, and you'll see every quote — here's Q000061 for Radiant, already marked\nOrdered (they said yes)."},"506":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-15","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough#step-1--quote-the-customer--sales-module","content":"You add a line for the part and quantity; Carbon adds up the material and shop time so you\ncan set a price. When the customer says yes, one click turns the quote into a sales order."},"507":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-16","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough#step-2--take-the-order--sales-module","content":"The sales order is the customer's commitment. In Sales → Orders you can see SO000069\nfor Radiant Aerospace — Completed, $36,820."},"508":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-17","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough#step-2--take-the-order--sales-module","content":"Open the order and you see the line: CWH-A36-15, 500 each at $73.14. Notice it's set to\nMake to Order — so Carbon knows it has to be built, and it already created a job for it."},"509":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-18","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough#step-3--how-its-made--items-module","content":"Every part you make has a Method — a recipe with two halves: the Bill of Material (what\nit's made of) and the routing (the steps to make it). Open the part in the Items module\nto see it."},"510":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-19","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough#step-3--how-its-made--items-module","content":"Each hook needs 40 lb of steel, so 500 hooks need 20,000 lb. Carbon already knows that —\nwatch what it does next."},"511":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-20","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough#step-4--make-it--production-module","content":"Because the order is Make to Order, Carbon creates a job (J000097) for 500 pieces. The\nProduction module is mission control for the shop — here you can see active jobs and how busy\neach work center is."},"512":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-21","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough#step-4--make-it--production-module","content":"On the shop floor, operators open the Shop Floor app, tap onto each step, and record how\nmany good pieces they finished. That's how the job gets marked done — and how its real cost\nadds up."},"513":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-22","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough#step-5--buy-the-steel--purchasing-module","content":"Acme is short on 1-inch plate, so Carbon flags it and you raise a purchase order to your\nsteel supplier, Ryerson (PO000057). The Purchasing module tracks all of this."},"514":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-23","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough#step-5--buy-the-steel--purchasing-module","content":"Because A36 plate is batch-tracked, Carbon records exactly which steel went into this batch\nof hooks — the start of full traceability."},"515":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-24","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough#step-6--check-it-and-ship-it--quality--inventory","content":"The job's last step is Inspection — a quality gate. Once the parts pass, you create a\nshipment and send the 500 hooks. Carbon marks the order line Shipped."},"516":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-25","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough#step-7--get-paid--accounting-module","content":"Finally you bill the order. The sales invoice (AR000025) pulls its lines from what\nshipped — no re-typing — and once Radiant pays, it's marked Paid."},"517":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-26","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough#thats-the-whole-loop","content":"One part, one connected chain — each record a click away from the next:"},"518":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-27","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough#thats-the-whole-loop","content":"type: info"},"519":{"id":"/manual/walkthrough-28","page_id":"/manual/walkthrough","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/walkthrough#thats-the-whole-loop","content":"That's the whole idea of Carbon: enter something once, and it follows the work across every\nModule. Now dive into any step below."},"520":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","type":"page","content":"Advanced purchasing","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing"},"521":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-0","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","content":"Outside processing, RFQs, drop-ship and the supplier portal."},"522":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-1","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"523":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-2","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#outside-processing","content":"Outside processing"},"524":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-3","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#set-up-and-run-an-outside-operation","content":"Set up and run an outside operation"},"525":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-4","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#supplier-quotes-rfqs","content":"Supplier quotes (RFQs)"},"526":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-5","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#send-an-rfq-and-compare-the-replies","content":"Send an RFQ and compare the replies"},"527":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-6","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#drop-ship","content":"Drop-ship"},"528":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-7","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#set-up-a-drop-ship","content":"Set up a drop-ship"},"529":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-8","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#the-supplier-portal","content":"The supplier portal"},"530":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-9","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#purchasing-planning","content":"Purchasing planning"},"531":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-10","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#turn-suggestions-into-purchase-orders","content":"Turn suggestions into purchase orders"},"532":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-11","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"533":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-12","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","content":"Purchasing basics covered the everyday loop: raise a PO,\nsend it, receive the goods. This page covers the trickier buying jobs:"},"534":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-13","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","content":"Send a part out for a coating (outside processing)."},"535":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-14","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","content":"Shop several suppliers for the best price (RFQs)."},"536":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-15","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","content":"Ship straight to your customer (drop-ship)."},"537":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-16","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","content":"Let Carbon tell you what to buy (planning)."},"538":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-17","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Everything here lives in the Purchasing module. Open it from the home screen, then use the\nsub-nav for Purchase Orders, Supplier Quotes, and Planning."},"539":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-18","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Pick the tool you need today:"},"540":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-19","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#outside-processing","content":"Some steps aren't done in-house. A part comes off your mill in great shape, but still needs\nanodizing or painting. You send it to a specialist, they do the work, and they ship it\nback. That round trip is outside processing."},"541":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-20","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#outside-processing","content":"In Carbon, it's just an operation in a part's routing — like\nFlame Cut or Inspection. The only difference: its type is Outside, not Inside."},"542":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-21","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#outside-processing","content":"Inside — runs at your own work center and costs you shop time."},"543":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-22","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#outside-processing","content":"Outside — runs at a supplier and costs you what the supplier charges."},"544":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-23","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#outside-processing","content":"Acme sends parts to two outside suppliers, both set as Subcontractors and Service Providers:"},"545":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-24","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#outside-processing","content":"Here an aluminum bracket is milled in-house, anodized at Allen's Anodizing, then inspected.\nOperation 20 has no work center and no labor minutes — it points at a supplier and carries a price."},"546":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-25","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#set-up-and-run-an-outside-operation","content":"Add the operation and set its type to Outside. Open the part's Manufacturing tab, add\nthe operation where the service belongs, and choose Outside as the type."},"547":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-26","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#set-up-and-run-an-outside-operation","content":"Point it at a supplier and a price. Pick the supplier — Allen's Anodizing — and enter\nwhat they charge. That price rolls up into the part's cost, just like in-house labor."},"548":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-27","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#set-up-and-run-an-outside-operation","content":"Release the job. The outside operation appears in the job's operation list with status\nTodo, in sequence between the inside steps."},"549":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-28","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#set-up-and-run-an-outside-operation","content":"Raise a PO for the service. When production reaches the outside step, create a\npurchase order to the supplier. Carbon links it back to\nthe job, so it knows which parts left the building and why."},"550":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-29","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#set-up-and-run-an-outside-operation","content":"Ship out, then receive back. Send the parts to the supplier. When they return finished,\nrecord a receipt against the PO. That marks the outside\noperation complete and the job moves to the next step."},"551":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-30","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#set-up-and-run-an-outside-operation","content":"type: warn"},"552":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-31","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#set-up-and-run-an-outside-operation","content":"Outside parts are still your inventory. While parts are at the anodizer, they're\nwork-in-progress that's temporarily off-site. Don't close the job until you've received them\nback, or your job costs and on-hand counts will be wrong."},"553":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-32","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#supplier-quotes-rfqs","content":"Before you buy something expensive, you usually want more than one price. A Request for Quote\n(RFQ) does that: describe what you want, send it to several suppliers, collect their\nsupplier quotes, compare, then convert the winner to a PO — no re-typing."},"554":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-33","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#supplier-quotes-rfqs","content":"A supplier quote is the buying-side mirror of a sales quote. Carbon\nmakes one per supplier you ask."},"555":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-34","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#supplier-quotes-rfqs","content":"Example: Acme needs a big lot of 1″ A36 steel plate. The RFQ goes to four suppliers at once —\nRyerson, Olympic Steel, Reliance Steel, and MetalMart."},"556":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-35","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#send-an-rfq-and-compare-the-replies","content":"Create the RFQ and add what you want priced. In the Purchasing module, create a new RFQ\nand add a line per item — here, one line for A36 Steel Plate 1″ (A36-STEEL-PLT-1\".96x240)."},"557":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-36","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#send-an-rfq-and-compare-the-replies","content":"Choose the suppliers and send. Add the four suppliers as recipients. Carbon makes a supplier\nquote for each and sends it — by email or through the supplier portal."},"558":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-37","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#send-an-rfq-and-compare-the-replies","content":"Collect the replies. Prices land back on each supplier quote. The list shows which are still\noutstanding."},"559":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-38","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#send-an-rfq-and-compare-the-replies","content":"Compare side by side. Open the comparison view. Carbon lines the suppliers up so the\ncheapest price and best lead time jump out. The lowest number isn't always the right one — a\nslightly higher price that arrives sooner can win when a job is waiting."},"560":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-39","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#send-an-rfq-and-compare-the-replies","content":"Convert the winner to a PO. Pick the quote and convert it to a\npurchase order in one click. Supplier, item, price, and\nquantity carry over, and the PO stays linked to the quote. That's exactly how Acme's\nPO000057 to Ryerson came to be: A36 plate at $0.25/LB."},"561":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-40","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#send-an-rfq-and-compare-the-replies","content":"type: tip"},"562":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-41","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#send-an-rfq-and-compare-the-replies","content":"Keep the prices for next time. A supplier quote can feed a supplier's price list for\nthat item, so next time Carbon already knows the price — no RFQ needed unless you want to re-shop it."},"563":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-42","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#drop-ship","content":"Normally goods you buy come to you — you receive them, then ship from your own dock.\nSometimes the supplier should ship straight to your customer instead. That's a\ndrop-shipment: you still buy it and still bill your customer, but the goods never touch your\nbuilding."},"564":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-43","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#drop-ship","content":"In Carbon it's a flag that links a sales order and a purchase order. Acme's hero order\nSO000069 is normal — its dropShipment flag is false (Acme makes those hooks itself). A\ndrop-ship order sets that flag to true."},"565":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-44","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#set-up-a-drop-ship","content":"Mark the sales order line as drop-ship. On the sales order,\nturn on drop-shipment for the line. Carbon now knows the part won't come from your inventory."},"566":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-45","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#set-up-a-drop-ship","content":"Generate the linked PO. Carbon creates a PO to your supplier with the ship-to set to\nyour customer's address, not your warehouse. Confirm supplier, price, and quantity."},"567":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-46","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#set-up-a-drop-ship","content":"Send the PO; the supplier ships your customer. Nothing arrives at your shop, so there's no\nreceipt and no inventory movement on your side."},"568":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-47","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#set-up-a-drop-ship","content":"Invoice the customer as usual. You still bill from the sales order and pay from the PO. Your\nmargin is the difference — Carbon tracks both sides."},"569":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-48","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#set-up-a-drop-ship","content":"type: warn"},"570":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-49","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#set-up-a-drop-ship","content":"Drop-ship skips your inventory on purpose. The part never appears in your\non-hand stock — by design. If you want the goods\nfirst (to inspect or kit), buy it normally and ship it yourself."},"571":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-50","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#the-supplier-portal","content":"How do suppliers actually reply to an RFQ or confirm a PO? Carbon gives each supplier a\nportal — a secure web link where they respond online, with no Carbon login of their own."},"572":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-51","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#the-supplier-portal","content":"Whatever the supplier types lands straight on the matching record in your Carbon — no copy-paste,\nno typos. Each link is private, so a supplier only sees the documents you sent them."},"573":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-52","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#the-supplier-portal","content":"type: tip"},"574":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-53","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#the-supplier-portal","content":"No account, no friction. The portal makes it easy for small shops — like an anodizer or\npainter — to reply fast. The faster they respond, the faster your RFQ comparison fills in."},"575":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-54","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#purchasing-planning","content":"How do you know what to buy in the first place? Purchasing planning watches your demand\nand your stock, works out where you'll run short, and hands you a list of buy suggestions\nyou can turn into POs."},"576":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-55","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#purchasing-planning","content":"Demand comes from two places:"},"577":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-56","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#purchasing-planning","content":"Jobs. When you release a job, its\nmethod lists the materials it needs. Not enough on hand = a shortage."},"578":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-57","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#purchasing-planning","content":"Reorder points. For stocked items (see Replenishment),\nCarbon flags anything that dips below its minimum."},"579":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-58","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#purchasing-planning","content":"This is how Acme's hero PO was born. Job J000097 needed 40 LB of A36 plate per piece —\n20,000 LB for the batch of 500 — and Acme was short. Carbon flagged it, and that suggestion\nbecame PO000057 to Ryerson."},"580":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-59","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#turn-suggestions-into-purchase-orders","content":"Open the planning view. In the Purchasing module, open Planning. Carbon lists every\nitem about to run short, the quantity it suggests, and what's driving the need."},"581":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-60","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#turn-suggestions-into-purchase-orders","content":"Review and adjust. Bump a quantity to hit a price break, change the supplier, or skip a line.\nCarbon's number is a starting point, not a command."},"582":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-61","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#turn-suggestions-into-purchase-orders","content":"Generate the POs. Select the lines and let Carbon create the POs. It groups them by supplier,\nso one click can make several tidy orders — all the Ryerson items on one PO."},"583":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-62","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#turn-suggestions-into-purchase-orders","content":"Approve and send. New POs land in Draft or Needs Approval (like PO000057 did).\nFrom there it's the normal purchasing basics loop."},"584":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-63","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#turn-suggestions-into-purchase-orders","content":"type: info"},"585":{"id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing-64","page_id":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/advanced-purchasing#turn-suggestions-into-purchase-orders","content":"Planning closes the loop. A job creates demand, planning surfaces the shortage, a PO fills\nit, the receipt restocks the shelf, and the job pulls what it needs. Run planning regularly and\nshortages stop sneaking up on you."},"586":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","type":"page","content":"Purchasing basics","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics"},"587":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-0","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","content":"Purchase orders, receiving and supplier quotes."},"588":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-1","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"589":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-2","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#whats-on-a-purchase-order","content":"What's on a purchase order"},"590":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-3","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#create-the-purchase-order","content":"Create the purchase order"},"591":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-4","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#start-a-new-order","content":"Start a new order"},"592":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-5","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#pick-the-supplier","content":"Pick the supplier"},"593":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-6","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#set-dates-and-delivery","content":"Set dates and delivery"},"594":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-7","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#add-the-line","content":"Add the line"},"595":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-8","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#approve-it-and-send-it","content":"Approve it and send it"},"596":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-9","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#submit-for-approval","content":"Submit for approval"},"597":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-10","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#approve","content":"Approve"},"598":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-11","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#send-it","content":"Send it"},"599":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-12","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#receive-the-goods","content":"Receive the goods"},"600":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-13","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#start-a-receipt-from-the-po","content":"Start a receipt from the PO"},"601":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-14","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#confirm-what-arrived","content":"Confirm what arrived"},"602":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-15","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#enter-the-batch-lot-number","content":"Enter the batch (lot) number"},"603":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-16","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#post-the-receipt","content":"Post the receipt"},"604":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-17","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#what-happens-next","content":"What happens next"},"605":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-18","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"606":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-19","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","content":"When a job needs material you don't have, you buy it with a\npurchase order (PO) — a document that tells a\nsupplier what you want, how much, the price, and when. This page\nshows how to raise a PO, send it, and receive the goods onto your shelf."},"607":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-20","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","content":"We'll follow a real Acme example: PO000057 to Ryerson for the A36 Steel Plate that\nfeeds job J000097."},"608":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-21","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Purchasing is its own module. Open it from the left rail to see open POs, the amount on\norder, and the sub-nav for Purchase Orders, Suppliers, and supplier quotes."},"609":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-22","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"type: info"},"610":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-23","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this fits. A job (or low stock) creates a need →\nyou raise a PO here → you receive the goods,\nwhich adds them to inventory → the job uses them → the supplier bills you. It's the buy-side\nmirror of the sell-side flow in Carbon in 15 minutes."},"611":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-24","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#whats-on-a-purchase-order","content":"A PO has two parts, shown as tabs on the record:"},"612":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-25","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#whats-on-a-purchase-order","content":"Header (Details tab) — the supplier, dates, deliver-to location, currency, and payment\nterms. One supplier per PO."},"613":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-26","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#whats-on-a-purchase-order","content":"Lines (Lines tab) — one row per thing you're buying: an\nitem, a quantity, a unit price, and a required date."},"614":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-27","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#whats-on-a-purchase-order","content":"type: tip"},"615":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-28","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#whats-on-a-purchase-order","content":"Get a price first. Not sure what something costs? Send a supplier quote (RFQ): you\nask one or more suppliers for a price, then turn the best reply into a PO without re-typing.\nCarbon also remembers a supplier's last price and pre-fills it — Acme's A36 plate runs\n$0.25/LB at Ryerson."},"616":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-29","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#start-a-new-order","content":"In the Purchasing module, open Purchase Orders and click New Purchase Order.\nCarbon assigns the next number (Acme's was PO000057) and opens it in Draft — nothing is\ncommitted yet, so you can edit or delete freely."},"617":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-30","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#pick-the-supplier","content":"Choose the supplier. Acme picks Ryerson. Carbon then fills in that supplier's\ncurrency (USD), payment terms (Net 30), and contact and address for you."},"618":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-31","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#pick-the-supplier","content":"type: warn"},"619":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-32","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#pick-the-supplier","content":"No supplier record yet? Create it first — see Suppliers. A PO\nmust point at a real supplier."},"620":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-33","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#set-dates-and-delivery","content":"On the Details tab, confirm the order date (2026-06-12) and pick the deliver-to\nlocation. Acme ships to Headquarters. Leave Net 30 or override it for this order."},"621":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-34","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#add-the-line","content":"On the Lines tab, click Add Line and set the type to Part. Search for the item —\nAcme picks A36 Steel Plate 1\" (A36-STEEL-PLT-1\".96x240). Then enter the three numbers:"},"622":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-35","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#add-the-line","content":"Quantity — 54,001 LB"},"623":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-36","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#add-the-line","content":"Unit price — $0.25 (Carbon pre-fills the last known price)"},"624":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-37","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#add-the-line","content":"Required date — 2026-06-21"},"625":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-38","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#add-the-line","content":"Carbon multiplies them into the extended price: 54,001 × $0.25 = $13,500.25."},"626":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-39","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#add-the-line","content":"Purchase Order · PO000057 — Lines. One line: 54,001 LB of A36 steel plate at $0.25/LB."},"627":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-40","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#add-the-line","content":"type: tip"},"628":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-41","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#add-the-line","content":"Shortcut: buy from a job. Acme didn't type this line by hand. When job J000097 was\nplanned, Carbon saw it needed 20,000 lb of A36 plate it didn't have and surfaced a\nshortage — from there you generate the PO with item, quantity, and supplier already\nfilled in. See Jobs and\nAdvanced purchasing."},"629":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-42","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#approve-it-and-send-it","content":"A draft commits you to nothing. Two steps make it a real order."},"630":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-43","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#submit-for-approval","content":"When the order is ready, submit it for approval. Carbon moves it from Draft to\nNeeds Approval — large buys can need a manager's sign-off so nobody accidentally commits\nthe company. Who approves what is set in Users & permissions."},"631":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-44","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#submit-for-approval","content":"A PO walks through these statuses:"},"632":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-45","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#approve","content":"An approver opens the order, checks the lines and total, and approves it. If something's\nwrong, they reject it back to Draft."},"633":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-46","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#send-it","content":"Once approved, click Send. Carbon builds a PO document (PDF) and emails it to Ryerson's\ncontact. The order moves to To Receive. You can also download the PDF yourself."},"634":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-47","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#send-it","content":"type: warn"},"635":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-48","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#send-it","content":"Sending is not receiving. Sending tells the supplier what you want — it does not add\nanything to inventory. Material lands on your shelf only when you receive it."},"636":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-49","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#receive-the-goods","content":"This is the step that actually changes your stock. When the truck arrives, create a\nreceipt against the PO. Receiving:"},"637":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-50","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#receive-the-goods","content":"Adds the material to inventory at the deliver-to location."},"638":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-51","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#receive-the-goods","content":"Records how much arrived per line, so Carbon knows what's still outstanding."},"639":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-52","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#receive-the-goods","content":"Records the lot for batch-tracked items, for full\ntraceability."},"640":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-53","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#receive-the-goods","content":"A36 Steel Plate is batch-tracked, so the receipt asks for a lot number — that's how Acme can\nlater trace a hook back to the exact heat of steel it came from."},"641":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-54","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#start-a-receipt-from-the-po","content":"Open PO000057 and click Receive (or start from Inventory → Receipts and pick the PO).\nCarbon pre-loads the open lines with the outstanding quantity — here the full 54,001 LB."},"642":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-55","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#confirm-what-arrived","content":"Enter the received quantity per line. If they shipped everything, accept the suggested\namount; if part, enter the smaller number and Carbon keeps the rest open. Pick the shelf /\nbin — Acme's A36 plate goes to R02-B01-01 at Headquarters."},"643":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-56","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#enter-the-batch-lot-number","content":"Type the supplier's lot number from the mill certificate. This lot is now linked to the\nmaterial, so Carbon records which lot the job consumes."},"644":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-57","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#enter-the-batch-lot-number","content":"Receipt · A36 Steel Plate against PO000057. Receiving 54,001 LB into bin R02-B01-01, with the supplier's batch recorded."},"645":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-58","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#enter-the-batch-lot-number","content":"type: info"},"646":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-59","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#enter-the-batch-lot-number","content":"The lot shown (HEAT-A36-0612) is illustrative — enter whatever batch ID the mill\ncertificate gives. Items that aren't batch- or serial-tracked skip this step."},"647":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-60","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#post-the-receipt","content":"Click Post. Carbon then:"},"648":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-61","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#post-the-receipt","content":"Increases on-hand stock at Headquarters by the received quantity."},"649":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-62","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#post-the-receipt","content":"Stamps the PO line as received and moves the order toward To Invoice."},"650":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-63","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#post-the-receipt","content":"Posts the inventory value to your books at the purchase cost."},"651":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-64","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#post-the-receipt","content":"The steel is now real, on the shelf, and ready for job J000097."},"652":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-65","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#what-happens-next","content":"The job consumes the plate, carrying the lot number into the finished hooks."},"653":{"id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics-66","page_id":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/purchasing-basics#what-happens-next","content":"The supplier sends a bill, which you match to the PO and receipt as an\naccounts-payable invoice. Matching PO ↔ receipt ↔ bill is how\nyou catch an overcharge before you pay."},"654":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","type":"page","content":"Suppliers","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/suppliers"},"655":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-0","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers","content":"Set up the vendors you buy materials and services from."},"656":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-1","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"657":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-2","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#what-a-supplier-record-holds","content":"What a supplier record holds"},"658":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-3","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#acmes-suppliers","content":"Acme's suppliers"},"659":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-4","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#create-a-supplier","content":"Create a supplier"},"660":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-5","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#open-the-form","content":"Open the form"},"661":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-6","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#fill-in-the-core-details","content":"Fill in the core details"},"662":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-7","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#add-a-contact","content":"Add a contact"},"663":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-8","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#add-a-location","content":"Add a location"},"664":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-9","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#set-payment-terms","content":"Set payment terms"},"665":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-10","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#link-supplier-part-numbers","content":"Link supplier part numbers"},"666":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-11","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#the-finished-supplier","content":"The finished supplier"},"667":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-12","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"668":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-13","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers","content":"A supplier (or vendor) is any company you buy from — a steel mill, a parts\ndistributor, an anodizer. Add one before you can order from it. This page shows how, using\nAcme's real vendors."},"669":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-14","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Suppliers live in the Purchasing module. Open Purchasing, then click Suppliers\nin the sub-nav across the top."},"670":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-15","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Set a supplier up once and the rest of buying gets easier. Every purchase\norder already knows who to email, where to ship from, how\nyou pay, and the price to expect."},"671":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-16","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#what-a-supplier-record-holds","content":"You don't have to fill it all in at once — a name is enough to start. Add the rest as\nyou go."},"672":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-17","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#what-a-supplier-record-holds","content":"Carbon gives every supplier a short ID like SUP000013. The friendly name shows\neverywhere; the ID keeps it stable even if you rename the company."},"673":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-18","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#acmes-suppliers","content":"A real shop keeps a mix of vendors. The Type column groups them so you can filter the\nlist later."},"674":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-19","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#acmes-suppliers","content":"Two small fields shape how a supplier behaves:"},"675":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-20","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#acmes-suppliers","content":"Type groups and filters the list. It doesn't affect pricing. Define your own types in\nSettings — Acme uses five."},"676":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-21","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#acmes-suppliers","content":"Status controls whether you can buy now. Active shows everywhere; Inactive is\nhidden from new orders but kept for history — that's how you retire a vendor without\ndeleting records."},"677":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-22","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#create-a-supplier","content":"Let's add Ryerson, Acme's steel mill."},"678":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-23","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#open-the-form","content":"In Purchasing → Suppliers, click New. Carbon opens a short form. The only required\nfield is the Name."},"679":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-24","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#fill-in-the-core-details","content":"Enter the Name, pick a Type, and confirm the Currency (Carbon defaults to your\nbase currency — USD for Acme). Then click Save."},"680":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-25","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#fill-in-the-core-details","content":"Carbon assigns the next ID (SUP000013) and opens the full record. The other tabs now unlock."},"681":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-26","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#add-a-contact","content":"Open the Contacts tab and click New. Add a name, email, and phone for the person you\ndeal with — usually a sales rep."},"682":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-27","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#add-a-contact","content":"Mark one as the purchasing contact. That's who Carbon emails when you send a purchase\norder, so pick the person who takes orders. You can add as many contacts as you like."},"683":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-28","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#add-a-location","content":"Open the Locations tab and click New to enter the ship-from or remit-to address. If\na vendor ships from several plants, add one location per site."},"684":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-29","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#add-a-location","content":"type: tip"},"685":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-30","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#add-a-location","content":"Most vendors have a single location, so Carbon fills it in automatically on every purchase\norder. You only choose when there's more than one."},"686":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-31","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#set-payment-terms","content":"Open the Payment tab and pick a default term. Net 30 means the invoice is due 30 days\nafter it's issued. Setting a default here means every new order starts with the right terms."},"687":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-32","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#set-payment-terms","content":"Acme buys from Ryerson on Net 30 — the same terms that carry onto purchase order\nPO000057."},"688":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-33","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#link-supplier-part-numbers","content":"Your vendor rarely uses your part number. A supplier part links the two — it stores the\nvendor's part number and price for one of your items. The right\nnumber prints on the order and the price fills in automatically."},"689":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-34","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#link-supplier-part-numbers","content":"Add them two ways:"},"690":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-35","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#link-supplier-part-numbers","content":"From the supplier → the Supplier Parts tab — good for loading a vendor's catalog."},"691":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-36","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#link-supplier-part-numbers","content":"From the item → the item's Suppliers tab — good for \"who can sell me this?\""},"692":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-37","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#link-supplier-part-numbers","content":"With this in place, picking Ryerson on a purchase order line for A36 plate auto-fills the\n$0.25/LB price Acme negotiated."},"693":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-38","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#the-finished-supplier","content":"Here's Ryerson once it's fully set up — the record the rest of buying leans on."},"694":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-39","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#the-finished-supplier","content":"Now raising a purchase order is mostly point-and-click: pick Ryerson, pick the material, and\nCarbon already knows the contact, address, terms, and price."},"695":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-40","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#the-finished-supplier","content":"type: warn"},"696":{"id":"/manual/buying/suppliers-41","page_id":"/manual/buying/suppliers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/buying/suppliers#the-finished-supplier","content":"Don't create a duplicate (a separate \"Ryerson Inc.\" next to \"Ryerson\"). Duplicates split\nyour spending across two records and make reports wrong. Search the list first and reuse\nthe vendor if it exists."},"697":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","type":"page","content":"Migrating your data","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data"},"698":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-0","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","content":"Bring your items, customers and suppliers into Carbon."},"699":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-1","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"700":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-2","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#import-in-this-order","content":"Import in this order"},"701":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-3","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#1--units--locations","content":"1 — Units & locations"},"702":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-4","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#2--items","content":"2 — Items"},"703":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-5","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#3--customers--suppliers","content":"3 — Customers & suppliers"},"704":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-6","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#4--opening-inventory","content":"4 — Opening inventory"},"705":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-7","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#5--boms--methods","content":"5 — BOMs & methods"},"706":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-8","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#6--open-orders","content":"6 — Open orders"},"707":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-9","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#how-every-importer-works","content":"How every importer works"},"708":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-10","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"709":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-11","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","content":"Moving from spreadsheets or another system? You don't retype everything by hand. You import\nit with Carbon's built-in CSV importers. The one rule: import the things other records\ndepend on first."},"710":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-12","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","content":"We'll use Acme Inc.'s real data as the example throughout."},"711":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-13","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Each importer lives in the module that owns the data — Items, Sales, Purchasing,\nInventory. You open that module, click Import, and upload a CSV. Imported parts land in\nthe Items module, on the Parts list."},"712":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-14","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#import-in-this-order","content":"Carbon records are linked. A part needs a unit of measure. Opening stock needs the part\nand a location. A sales order needs a customer and an item. So you load the bottom\nlayer first and build up."},"713":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-15","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#import-in-this-order","content":"type: tip"},"714":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-16","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#import-in-this-order","content":"You don't have to migrate history. Most shops bring in master data (items, customers,\nsuppliers) plus a snapshot of opening inventory and any open orders — and leave closed\njobs and paid invoices in the old system. A clean start beats a perfect copy."},"715":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-17","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#1--units--locations","content":"A unit of measure (UoM) is how you count an item: EA for each, LB for pounds. A\nlocation is a site that holds stock. Carbon ships with the common UoMs, so usually you're\njust confirming they exist."},"716":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-18","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#1--units--locations","content":"Acme keeps it small — EA for parts, LB for raw materials — and runs two sites,\nHeadquarters and Texas."},"717":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-19","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#1--units--locations","content":"type: warn"},"718":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-20","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#1--units--locations","content":"Pick your UoM and location codes now and never rename them. Every imported row points at\nthese codes by exact text — change EA to ea later and you orphan thousands of references."},"719":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-21","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#2--items","content":"Items are the heart of Carbon — a part you make, a material\nyou buy, a tool. This is the biggest import. Each CSV row becomes one item."},"720":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-22","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#2--items","content":"Two decisions matter on every row: its itemType (part, material, tool?) and its\nreplenishmentSystem — do you Make it or Buy it?"},"721":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-23","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#2--items","content":"type: tip"},"722":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-24","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#2--items","content":"Keep readableId values consistent. Acme uses [abbrev]-[material]-[rev] for parts\n(CWH-A36-15) and a longer pattern for materials (A36-STEEL-PLT-1\".96x240). A predictable\nscheme makes parts findable and the BOM import in Step 5 far easier."},"723":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-25","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#3--customers--suppliers","content":"With items in place, add who you sell to and buy from. Customers come before any quote or\norder; suppliers before any purchase order. Same workflow, two files."},"724":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-26","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#3--customers--suppliers","content":"type: info"},"725":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-27","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#3--customers--suppliers","content":"Customer/supplier types and payment terms are short lookup lists. If your CSV uses\none Carbon doesn't have yet, create it once under Settings first. More in\nCustomers and Suppliers."},"726":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-28","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#4--opening-inventory","content":"Now record what's on your shelves today. Each row says: this item, this quantity, at this\nlocation (and which shelf, if you track bins)."},"727":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-29","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#4--opening-inventory","content":"Each row becomes an inventory adjustment that sets the item's on-hand quantity."},"728":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-30","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#4--opening-inventory","content":"type: warn"},"729":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-31","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#4--opening-inventory","content":"Import opening inventory once, ideally on go-live day. If you import balances and keep\ntransacting in the old system, the two drift apart fast. Freeze, count, import, run forward."},"730":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-32","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#5--boms--methods","content":"A method is how a made item is built: its bill of materials\n(what it's made of) plus its routing (the operations that make it). Methods only work once\nthe parent and all child items already exist — which is why they come after Step 2."},"731":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-33","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#5--boms--methods","content":"The Counterweight Hook's method is short: one material, three operations."},"732":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-34","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#5--boms--methods","content":"You import methods with two files, loaded in order:"},"733":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-35","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#5--boms--methods","content":"BOM lines — one row per material, linking a parent readableId to a child\nreadableId with a quantity. For the hook: parent CWH-A36-15, child\nA36-STEEL-PLT-1\".96x240, qty 40 LB."},"734":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-36","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#5--boms--methods","content":"Routing operations — one row per operation, with its sequence, process (Flame Cut,\nSandblasting, Inspection) and the work center it runs at, plus a time per piece."},"735":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-37","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#5--boms--methods","content":"Carbon stitches the two into the parent's method. From then on, any\njob for that part copies the recipe automatically."},"736":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-38","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#5--boms--methods","content":"type: tip"},"737":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-39","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#5--boms--methods","content":"Multi-level assemblies import the same way — just make sure every sub-assembly exists as\nan item first, and import the deepest level's BOM before its parents."},"738":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-40","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#6--open-orders","content":"Last, bring in work still in flight: open quotes, sales orders awaiting fulfillment,\nand purchase orders awaiting receipt. By now everything they point at already exists."},"739":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-41","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#6--open-orders","content":"These mirror Acme's real follow-on Counterweight Hook orders (SO000070 and SO000071, right\nafter the hero order SO000069). Once in, Carbon plans jobs and purchasing against them."},"740":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-42","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#how-every-importer-works","content":"Every importer follows the same five steps, so once you've done one, you've done them all."},"741":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-43","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#how-every-importer-works","content":"Open the importer. Go to the module that owns the data — Items, Sales, Purchasing,\nInventory — and click Import. Download Carbon's template CSV and pour your data into\nits columns."},"742":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-44","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#how-every-importer-works","content":"Upload the file. Drop in your .csv. Carbon previews the first rows so you can confirm\nit parsed correctly."},"743":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-45","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#how-every-importer-works","content":"Map columns. Point each of your columns at a Carbon field — your \"Part No.\" to\nreadableId, \"UoM\" to unitOfMeasureCode, \"Make/Buy\" to replenishmentSystem. If your\nheaders match the template, mapping auto-fills."},"744":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-46","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#how-every-importer-works","content":"Validate. Carbon checks every row before changing anything — flagging blanks, a missing\nUoM code, or a duplicate readableId. Fix flagged rows and re-upload."},"745":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-47","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#how-every-importer-works","content":"Import. When the preview is clean, confirm. Carbon creates the records and shows a\nsummary. Spot-check a few, then move to the next file."},"746":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-48","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#how-every-importer-works","content":"type: warn"},"747":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-49","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#how-every-importer-works","content":"Always run a small test batch first — five or ten rows — before importing thousands. A\ntiny run surfaces a wrong mapping or bad UoM code in seconds, not after you've created 5,000\nmis-mapped parts."},"748":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-50","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#how-every-importer-works","content":"type: tip"},"749":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data-51","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/migrating-data#how-every-importer-works","content":"Big or repeatable migration? Carbon is API-first — anything\nyou can type in, you can script. For a large move or a recurring sync, scripting against the\nAPI beats hand-mapping CSVs. You can even have an AI assistant drive it through Carbon's\nbuilt-in MCP server. See\nUsing the API."},"750":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","type":"page","content":"Setting up your company","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company"},"751":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-0","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","content":"Company profile, locations, units of measure and number sequences."},"752":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-1","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"753":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-2","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#1-company-profile","content":"1. Company profile"},"754":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-3","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#2-locations","content":"2. Locations"},"755":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-4","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#shelves-and-bins-live-inside-a-location","content":"Shelves and bins live inside a location"},"756":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-5","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#3-units-of-measure","content":"3. Units of measure"},"757":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-6","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#4-number-sequences","content":"4. Number sequences"},"758":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-7","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#5-payment-terms","content":"5. Payment terms"},"759":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-8","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#the-order-to-do-them-in","content":"The order to do them in"},"760":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-9","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"761":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-10","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","content":"Tell Carbon a few facts about your business — who you are, where you keep stock, how you\nmeasure things, how documents are numbered, and when you get paid. Set these up once, up\nfront. We'll use the real settings behind Acme Inc., the example company in this manual."},"762":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-11","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Everything here lives in the Settings module. Open it from the gear icon at the\nbottom-left of the navigation rail."},"763":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-12","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Settings is split into sections: Company, Locations, Units of Measure,\nSequences, Payment Terms, and more. You'll set up five of them below."},"764":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-13","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"type: tip"},"765":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-14","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"You need an administrator account to change these settings.\nYou can edit most of them later — except your base currency. Pick that one carefully."},"766":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-15","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#1-company-profile","content":"Your company profile is your business's ID card. Carbon stamps it onto every document you\nsend — quotes, order confirmations, purchase orders and invoices."},"767":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-16","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#1-company-profile","content":"Open Settings → Company."},"768":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-17","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#1-company-profile","content":"Enter your name and address. Acme is \"Acme Inc.\" at 2400 Anvil Way, Springfield, OH."},"769":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-18","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#1-company-profile","content":"Upload your logo (PNG or SVG). It shows on PDFs and in the top-left of the app."},"770":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-19","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#1-company-profile","content":"Set your base currency. Acme uses USD. This is the currency your books are kept in."},"771":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-20","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#1-company-profile","content":"Click Save."},"772":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-21","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#1-company-profile","content":"type: warn"},"773":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-22","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#1-company-profile","content":"Don't change your base currency after you start transacting — it isn't a supported flow.\nIf you picked wrong, start a fresh company instead."},"774":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-23","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#2-locations","content":"A location is a physical site where you make things, hold\nstock, or ship from. Carbon tracks inventory and work centers per location. Acme runs two."},"775":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-24","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#2-locations","content":"Headquarters is Acme's home base. It runs the Counterweight Hook thread you'll follow\nin this manual (SO000069,\nJ000097, PO000057)."},"776":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-25","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#2-locations","content":"Texas is a second site with its own burn table and laser table."},"777":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-26","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#shelves-and-bins-live-inside-a-location","content":"Inside a location you can say exactly where stock sits, using storage units (racks,\nrows, levels, bins). Acme's A36 steel plate for the Hook job lives in bin R02-B01-01. You\ndon't need these on day one — one catch-all bin per location is enough to start."},"778":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-27","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#shelves-and-bins-live-inside-a-location","content":"type: tip"},"779":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-28","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#shelves-and-bins-live-inside-a-location","content":"Add a location for every site that holds inventory or ships product. One building? One\nlocation is fine. Just don't lump two separate warehouses together, or your on-hand counts\nwon't match reality. More in Locations & stock."},"780":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-29","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#3-units-of-measure","content":"A unit of measure (UoM) is how you count a thing — each, pounds, gallons, feet. Every\nitem has one. The Counterweight Hook is counted in EA (Each);\nthe steel plate it's cut from is measured in LB (Pound). Acme runs 16 in total."},"781":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-30","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#3-units-of-measure","content":"To add your own, open Settings → Units of Measure and give it a short code (the\nabbreviation that shows on documents) and a name."},"782":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-31","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#3-units-of-measure","content":"type: warn"},"783":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-32","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#3-units-of-measure","content":"Set an item's unit before you transact with it — it feeds pricing, inventory and\npurchasing. Buying in one unit and stocking in another (buy steel by the pound, receive it as\nplates) uses separate purchase and inventory units, not a change to the base unit."},"784":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-33","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#4-number-sequences","content":"Every document gets a short, readable ID — Q000061, SO000069, J000097, PO000057,\nAR000025. You don't type these; Carbon builds each one from a number sequence: a prefix\nplus a running counter."},"785":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-34","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#4-number-sequences","content":"Each sequence has three parts you can tune:"},"786":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-35","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#4-number-sequences","content":"Prefix — the letters in front. AR is accounts receivable (money owed to you), AP\nis accounts payable (money you owe)."},"787":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-36","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#4-number-sequences","content":"Padding — how many digits, zero-filled. Acme pads to six, so SO000069, not SO69."},"788":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-37","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#4-number-sequences","content":"Next number — the counter, which ticks up by one each time a document is created."},"789":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-38","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#4-number-sequences","content":"Acme's hero order flows through these sequences: quote Q000061 becomes sales order\nSO000069, spawns job J000097, triggers purchase order PO000057, and finishes\nwith invoice AR000025."},"790":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-39","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#4-number-sequences","content":"type: tip"},"791":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-40","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#4-number-sequences","content":"Set prefixes and padding before you create your first document. The counter only goes up\n— don't reset it backwards, or you risk duplicate IDs."},"792":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-41","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#5-payment-terms","content":"Payment terms say when an invoice is due — and sometimes offer a discount for paying\nearly. Attach a default to each customer and supplier. Carbon copies it onto their orders and\ninvoices and works out the due date. Acme keeps seven."},"793":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-42","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#5-payment-terms","content":"Net 30 is Acme's default and the term on the hero thread — on Radiant Aerospace's order\nSO000069, the Ryerson purchase order PO000057, and the invoice AR000025."},"794":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-43","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#5-payment-terms","content":"type: info"},"795":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-44","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#5-payment-terms","content":"Set one term as the company default, optionally override it on a specific customer or\nsupplier, and Carbon fills it in automatically on every new order and invoice. You can still\nchange it on one document when a deal calls for it."},"796":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-45","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#the-order-to-do-them-in","content":"Each layer builds on the one before it:"},"797":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-46","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#the-order-to-do-them-in","content":"type: warn"},"798":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company-47","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/setup-company#the-order-to-do-them-in","content":"Do this before you import. Migrating data\nattaches parts, customers and suppliers to the company, locations and units you defined here.\nFoundation first, then data."},"799":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","type":"page","content":"Users & permissions","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions"},"800":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-0","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","content":"Invite your team, assign employee types and control who can do what."},"801":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-1","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"802":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-2","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#two-simple-ideas","content":"Two simple ideas"},"803":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-3","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#invite-your-team","content":"Invite your team"},"804":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-4","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#choose-an-employee-type","content":"Choose an employee type"},"805":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-5","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#set-module-permissions","content":"Set module permissions"},"806":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-6","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#roles-side-by-side","content":"Roles side by side"},"807":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-7","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"808":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-8","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","content":"Most shops have more than one person: sales, buying, floor operators, a bookkeeper. This\npage shows you how to invite them and control what each one can do."},"809":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-9","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","content":"type: info"},"810":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-10","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","content":"You need to be an admin to invite people. If you set up the company, you already are.\nAt Acme that's Chase Foster (chase@carbon.ms)."},"811":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-11","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"People and access live in the Users module, inside Settings. Go to Settings → Users\nin the left navigation. You'll see everyone in your company and the type assigned to each."},"812":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-12","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#two-simple-ideas","content":"Access comes from two things. Keep them separate and it stays easy."},"813":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-13","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#two-simple-ideas","content":"A user is one login — one person, one email."},"814":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-14","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#two-simple-ideas","content":"An employee type is a role: a bundle of\npermissions you attach to a user. Set it up once, hand it to\neveryone who does that job."},"815":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-15","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#two-simple-ideas","content":"Permissions are granted per module (Sales, Purchasing, Items, and so on), with four\nactions each: View, Create, Update, Delete."},"816":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-16","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#two-simple-ideas","content":"The flow: invite the user, give them an employee type, and that type's\npermissions decide what they can touch."},"817":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-17","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#invite-your-team","content":"You add people by email. They click the link, set a password, and they're in."},"818":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-18","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#invite-your-team","content":"Click Invite. Top-right of Settings → Users."},"819":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-19","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#invite-your-team","content":"Enter their email and pick a type. Add one or more addresses (separate with commas to\ninvite several at once). Choose the employee type they should get — you can change it later."},"820":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-20","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#invite-your-team","content":"They accept. Carbon emails the invite. When they click it and set a password, they're in.\nUntil then their status shows Invited instead of Active."},"821":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-21","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#invite-your-team","content":"type: tip"},"822":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-22","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#invite-your-team","content":"When someone leaves, deactivate them instead of deleting. That frees the seat but keeps\ntheir name on records they created — like Chase Foster staying attached to\nSO000069 forever."},"823":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-23","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#choose-an-employee-type","content":"An employee type is the role you hand someone. It carries a default set of permissions, so\nyou don't set up each person from scratch. Here are types a shop like Acme would use."},"824":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-24","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#choose-an-employee-type","content":"type: info"},"825":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-25","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#choose-an-employee-type","content":"These names are examples — you create and name your own. The one type that always exists is\nAdministrator: it reaches every module and Settings. Always keep at least one."},"826":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-26","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#set-module-permissions","content":"Inside a type, you flip four switches per module: View, Create, Update, Delete."},"827":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-27","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#set-module-permissions","content":"Open the type. From Settings → Employee Types, click a type (say Sales) and open\nits Permissions tab. You'll see one row per module."},"828":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-28","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#set-module-permissions","content":"Tick what the role needs. For a salesperson: full Sales, View on Items (to pick\nparts onto a quote), and nothing else."},"829":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-29","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#set-module-permissions","content":"Save. The change applies to everyone with that type right away. No need to edit each person."},"830":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-30","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#roles-side-by-side","content":"Here's how Acme's common types map across the modules — full access, read-only (View), or none."},"831":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-31","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#roles-side-by-side","content":"type: warn"},"832":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-32","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#roles-side-by-side","content":"Give the least access that does the job. Don't make everyone an Administrator. Start\nnarrow, add a permission when someone hits a wall. Hand out Delete rarely — Carbon\nprefers to cancel or deactivate records, not erase the history other records depend on."},"833":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-33","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#roles-side-by-side","content":"type: tip"},"834":{"id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions-34","page_id":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/getting-started/users-permissions#roles-side-by-side","content":"AI and API access run through this same system. An AI agent or API key inherits the access of\nthe user it acts as, so scope it tight. More in\nDeveloping with Carbon."},"835":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","type":"page","content":"Accounting & invoicing","tags":[],"url":"/manual/accounting/overview"},"836":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-0","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview","content":"Sales and purchase invoices, payments and finance integrations."},"837":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-1","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/accounting/overview#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"838":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-2","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/accounting/overview#the-two-kinds-of-invoice","content":"The two kinds of invoice"},"839":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-3","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/accounting/overview#sales-invoices--billing-the-customer","content":"Sales invoices — billing the customer"},"840":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-4","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/accounting/overview#purchase-invoices--recording-what-you-owe","content":"Purchase invoices — recording what you owe"},"841":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-5","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/accounting/overview#recording-payments","content":"Recording payments"},"842":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-6","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/accounting/overview#it-all-posts-to-the-books-for-you","content":"It all posts to the books for you"},"843":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-7","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/accounting/overview#already-using-quickbooks","content":"Already using QuickBooks?"},"844":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-8","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/accounting/overview#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"845":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-9","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview","content":"The shop earns the money; the Accounting module counts it. This page covers the two kinds\nof invoice and how they get paid — no accounting background needed."},"846":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-10","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Invoices live in the Accounting module. Carbon builds them from what already happened —\nwhat shipped, what you received — so the numbers always match the work."},"847":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-11","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"You can also see an invoice's status right on the document it came from. Sales order\nSO000069 below is Invoiced and Paid — the same money that became sales invoice\nAR000025."},"848":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-12","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#the-two-kinds-of-invoice","content":"There are only two, and they mirror each other:"},"849":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-13","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#the-two-kinds-of-invoice","content":"Sales invoice (AR) — bills a customer for what you shipped. AR means Accounts\nReceivable: money owed to you."},"850":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-14","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#the-two-kinds-of-invoice","content":"Purchase invoice (AP) — records a bill a supplier sent you. AP means Accounts\nPayable: money you owe."},"851":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-15","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#the-two-kinds-of-invoice","content":"That's it. Acme has 25 sales invoices (AR000001–AR000025) and 27 purchase invoices\n(AP000001–AP000027)."},"852":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-16","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#sales-invoices--billing-the-customer","content":"A sales invoice is how you get paid. You rarely type one from scratch — you create it from a\nshipment, and Carbon copies the customer, parts, quantities and prices off what shipped."},"853":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-17","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#sales-invoices--billing-the-customer","content":"When Acme shipped 500 Counterweight Hooks to Radiant Aerospace, that became sales invoice\nAR000025 for $36,820.00."},"854":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-18","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#sales-invoices--billing-the-customer","content":"Open the source. Go to Sales Invoices and click New, then pick the shipment (or\nsales order) to bill — here, the shipment behind SO000069. Carbon pulls in the lines\nautomatically."},"855":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-19","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#sales-invoices--billing-the-customer","content":"Review the lines. Check the quantities and prices match what shipped. Last chance to catch\na wrong price before the customer sees it."},"856":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-20","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#sales-invoices--billing-the-customer","content":"Post it. Posting assigns the number (AR000025) and turns it into a live receivable — money\nthe customer now owes."},"857":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-21","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#sales-invoices--billing-the-customer","content":"Send it. Email or download the PDF. Carbon stamps the date and starts the payment-terms\nclock — here, Net 30."},"858":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-22","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#sales-invoices--billing-the-customer","content":"Sales invoices use three statuses:"},"859":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-23","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#purchase-invoices--recording-what-you-owe","content":"A purchase invoice is the mirror image: the bill a supplier sends you. When steel arrives\nfrom Ryerson, you enter their bill so the books know what's owed."},"860":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-24","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#purchase-invoices--recording-what-you-owe","content":"The key idea is matching. Carbon checks the supplier's bill against two things that already\nexist:"},"861":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-25","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#purchase-invoices--recording-what-you-owe","content":"The purchase order — the price and quantity you agreed to."},"862":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-26","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#purchase-invoices--recording-what-you-owe","content":"The receipt — what actually showed up on the dock."},"863":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-27","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#purchase-invoices--recording-what-you-owe","content":"If they agree, approve with confidence. If not — they billed for 100 but you got 90 — Carbon\nshows the gap before you pay."},"864":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-28","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#purchase-invoices--recording-what-you-owe","content":"Start from the PO. Go to Purchase Invoices → New and select the purchase order —\nfor example, Ryerson's A36 steel from PO000057. Carbon pre-fills supplier, lines and prices."},"865":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-29","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#purchase-invoices--recording-what-you-owe","content":"Match against the receipt. Confirm the billed quantities match what you received. Carbon\nflags any mismatch."},"866":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-30","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#purchase-invoices--recording-what-you-owe","content":"Enter the supplier's bill number. Type their invoice reference and date — what you'll quote\nif you call them about it."},"867":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-31","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#purchase-invoices--recording-what-you-owe","content":"Post it. The invoice moves to Open, records the payable, and sets the due date from the\nsupplier's terms."},"868":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-32","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#purchase-invoices--recording-what-you-owe","content":"Purchase invoices add a couple of statuses the sales side doesn't have:"},"869":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-33","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#recording-payments","content":"An invoice says money should move; a payment records that it did. They're separate\nsteps on purpose — the gap between them is the time an invoice is \"outstanding.\""},"870":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-34","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#recording-payments","content":"Open the invoice you're settling — say AR000025, or a supplier bill like AP000023."},"871":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-35","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#recording-payments","content":"Record the payment. Enter the amount, the date, and the method — check, ACH, wire, card.\nRadiant paid the full $36,820.00 on 2026-06-11."},"872":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-36","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#recording-payments","content":"Carbon updates the status. A full payment flips it to Paid; a partial payment leaves a\nbalance. The cash entry posts to the books automatically."},"873":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-37","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#recording-payments","content":"type: tip"},"874":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-38","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#recording-payments","content":"Payment terms drive the due date. Each invoice carries a payment term that Carbon uses to\nset when payment is due. Net 30 is Acme's default. Terms flow down from the customer or\nsupplier record onto every order and invoice, so you set them once."},"875":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-39","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#it-all-posts-to-the-books-for-you","content":"Every posted invoice and payment writes entries to the chart of accounts — the numbered\nbuckets the business tracks money in (cash, receivables, payables, sales, cost of goods). Acme's\nchart has 93 accounts, and you never post to them by hand."},"876":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-40","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#it-all-posts-to-the-books-for-you","content":"When Acme posts AR000025, two things move at once so the books always balance:"},"877":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-41","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#it-all-posts-to-the-books-for-you","content":"When Radiant pays, the $36,820 moves out of Accounts Receivable and into Bank - Cash\n(1010). On the buying side it's the reverse."},"878":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-42","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#it-all-posts-to-the-books-for-you","content":"type: info"},"879":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-43","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#it-all-posts-to-the-books-for-you","content":"You don't need to memorize any of this. Every shipment, receipt and payment lands in the\nfinancials automatically and correctly — no spreadsheet reconciliation, no double data entry."},"880":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-44","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#already-using-quickbooks","content":"Keep it. Carbon can sync the invoices and payments it generates out to QuickBooks so\nyour accountant stays in the tool they know. Carbon owns operations (what shipped, what was\nreceived); QuickBooks owns the financials."},"881":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-45","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#already-using-quickbooks","content":"type: warn"},"882":{"id":"/manual/accounting/overview-46","page_id":"/manual/accounting/overview","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/accounting/overview#already-using-quickbooks","content":"Pick your books-of-record up front. Choose one financial source of truth — Carbon or\nQuickBooks — and set up the integration before posting real invoices. See Integrating with\nCarbon."},"883":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","type":"page","content":"Integrating with Carbon","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/integrating"},"884":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-0","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating","content":"Webhooks, integrations and extending the platform."},"885":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-1","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/integrating#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"886":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-2","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/integrating#webhooks-carbon-tells-you-when-things-happen","content":"Webhooks: Carbon tells you when things happen"},"887":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-3","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/integrating#build-apps-on-the-api","content":"Build apps on the API"},"888":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-4","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/integrating#example-integrations-clone-and-adapt","content":"Example integrations: clone and adapt"},"889":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-5","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/integrating#the-quickbooks-sync-end-to-end","content":"The QuickBooks sync, end to end"},"890":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-6","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/integrating#how-the-pieces-fit","content":"How the pieces fit"},"891":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-7","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/integrating#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"892":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-8","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating","content":"Most ERP systems are a closed box. Carbon is the opposite: everything in the app runs on the\nsame public API you can use too. So you can connect Carbon to your\nother tools, or build the feature you wish existed."},"893":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-9","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"This is part of the Developer module. You set up keys and connections in\nSettings → Integrations and Settings → API."},"894":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-10","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"There are three ways to connect:"},"895":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-11","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Most integrations use the first two together: a webhook tells you something happened, then an\nAPI call gets the details."},"896":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-12","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"type: tip"},"897":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-13","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"New here? Read Using the API first to make a key and your\nfirst call. Then come back to wire things together."},"898":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-14","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#webhooks-carbon-tells-you-when-things-happen","content":"A webhook lets Carbon call you. Instead of asking \"anything new yet?\" over and over, you\ngive Carbon a URL once. Carbon sends an HTTP request to that URL whenever an event you care\nabout happens. Think of it as Carbon tapping you on the shoulder."},"899":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-15","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#webhooks-carbon-tells-you-when-things-happen","content":"Pick the events you care about. For a shop like Acme: a quote sent, a sales order confirmed,\na job completed, a shipment shipped, an invoice paid. Subscribe only to what you'll act on."},"900":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-16","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#webhooks-carbon-tells-you-when-things-happen","content":"Give Carbon a URL. Your endpoint is a small web service that accepts an HTTP POST. Carbon\nsends a short JSON body saying what happened and which record it was."},"901":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-17","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#webhooks-carbon-tells-you-when-things-happen","content":"The payload is small on purpose: it tells you what and which record, not every field. Use the\nrecordId to fetch the full, current details with an API call."},"902":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-18","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#webhooks-carbon-tells-you-when-things-happen","content":"Check it's really from Carbon. Carbon signs each request. Verify the signature before you act.\nThen reply fast with a 2xx status and do the slow work after, so Carbon doesn't think delivery\nfailed and retry."},"903":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-19","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#webhooks-carbon-tells-you-when-things-happen","content":"Act on it. Fetch the details, then push them where they need to go. For SO000069, that could\nmean grabbing the line for 500 Counterweight Hooks at $73.14 and posting \"New order: $36,820 from\nRadiant Aerospace\" to Slack."},"904":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-20","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#webhooks-carbon-tells-you-when-things-happen","content":"type: tip"},"905":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-21","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#webhooks-carbon-tells-you-when-things-happen","content":"If you're running a script every five minutes to ask \"anything new?\", use a webhook instead.\nPolling wastes calls and adds delay; webhooks fire the instant the thing happens."},"906":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-22","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#build-apps-on-the-api","content":"When you need to do something to Carbon, you use the API. The same API powers the whole app, so\nanything you can do by clicking, you can do with code."},"907":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-23","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#build-apps-on-the-api","content":"A read is as direct as it sounds. Ask for sales order SO000069, get its lines back. A webhook\nhandler can use the recordId it received:"},"908":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-24","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#build-apps-on-the-api","content":"type: info"},"909":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-25","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#build-apps-on-the-api","content":"The field names you see here (salesOrderId, unitPrice) are the same ones used inside the app.\nThere's no separate \"integration data model\" to learn."},"910":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-26","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#example-integrations-clone-and-adapt","content":"Carbon ships real, open-source examples. They're the fastest way to go from \"I think this is\npossible\" to a working pattern."},"911":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-27","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#example-integrations-clone-and-adapt","content":"quote-configurator asks the customer a few questions (size, material, finish) and turns the\nanswers into a priced quote automatically. Acme already has one in its item list: the Flame Cut\nPart Configurator (FLAME CONFIG). The app computes a price and creates a quote through the API,\njust like the Q000061 quote you'd build by hand in Quoting."},"912":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-28","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#example-integrations-clone-and-adapt","content":"upload-3d-model attaches a 3D model to an item so anyone can\nsee the part. The Counterweight Hook already carries one: counterweight hook 3d.stl. The repo\nshows how to upload a model file and link it to the right item."},"913":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-29","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#example-integrations-clone-and-adapt","content":"type: tip"},"914":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-30","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#example-integrations-clone-and-adapt","content":"Treat these as templates, not products. Clone one, point it at your own company with your API key,\nand reshape it. Same field names as the app, so the gap is usually small."},"915":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-31","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#the-quickbooks-sync-end-to-end","content":"The most common integration is keeping your accounting system in step. Acme runs its books in\nQuickBooks. Carbon owns what was made, shipped and billed;\nQuickBooks owns the general ledger. The sync keeps them agreeing without double data entry, and\nit's a textbook example of the webhook-plus-API pattern."},"916":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-32","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#the-quickbooks-sync-end-to-end","content":"Connect once. In Settings → Integrations, authorize Carbon to talk to your QuickBooks\ncompany. The link persists; you don't log in every time."},"917":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-33","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#the-quickbooks-sync-end-to-end","content":"Match existing records. Both systems have customers and items, so the sync maps them: Carbon's\nRadiant Aerospace links to the matching QuickBooks customer. Getting this right stops the same\ncustomer appearing twice."},"918":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-34","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#the-quickbooks-sync-end-to-end","content":"Carbon posts an invoice. When Acme issues AR000025, a webhook fires and the sync wakes up."},"919":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-35","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#the-quickbooks-sync-end-to-end","content":"The sync writes it across. It pulls the full invoice ($36,570 subtotal, $250 shipping,\n$36,820 total) and creates the matching invoice in QuickBooks. When Radiant pays, that status can\nflow over too."},"920":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-36","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#the-quickbooks-sync-end-to-end","content":"See your connected systems in Settings → Integrations. Here's Acme's:"},"921":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-37","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#the-quickbooks-sync-end-to-end","content":"type: warn"},"922":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-38","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#the-quickbooks-sync-end-to-end","content":"Decide who owns each piece of data before you connect anything. At Acme, Carbon is the source of\ntruth for invoices and QuickBooks just receives them. Two systems editing the same field is the\nfastest way to a reconciliation headache. Pick one owner per field and let the sync flow one way."},"923":{"id":"/manual/developing/integrating-39","page_id":"/manual/developing/integrating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/integrating#how-the-pieces-fit","content":"Every real integration is the same four pieces, and each one is just a normal API call or HTTP\nrequest — nothing magic:"},"924":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","type":"page","content":"AI & the MCP server","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai"},"925":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-0","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","content":"Let AI assistants work in Carbon through the Model Context Protocol."},"926":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-1","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"927":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-2","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-mcp-is-in-one-line","content":"What MCP is, in one line"},"928":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-3","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#the-three-meta-tools","content":"The three meta-tools"},"929":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-4","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#three-safety-classes","content":"Three safety classes"},"930":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-5","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-you-can-actually-ask","content":"What you can actually ask"},"931":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-6","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#how-the-assistant-reaches-carbon","content":"How the assistant reaches Carbon"},"932":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-7","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#connect-an-assistant","content":"Connect an assistant"},"933":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-8","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#a-worked-example","content":"A worked example"},"934":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-9","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"935":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-10","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","content":"Carbon has a built-in MCP server. It lets an AI assistant — Claude, ChatGPT, or your\ncode editor — read and act inside your Carbon company using plain English. You ask a\nquestion; the assistant does the clicking for you."},"936":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-11","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"This is part of the Developer module — the same place as the API.\nCarbon hosts the server for you at app.carbon.ms/mcp. Nothing to install. You connect an\nassistant to that URL, and it can run Carbon on your behalf."},"937":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-12","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"type: info"},"938":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-13","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"The API is the raw machinery — every Carbon action as a callable endpoint. MCP wraps\nthat machinery so an AI assistant can drive it. Want to wire Carbon to another system\ninstead of talking to it? See Integrating with other systems."},"939":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-14","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-mcp-is-in-one-line","content":"MCP (Model Context Protocol) is a USB port for AI: any\nassistant that \"speaks MCP\" can plug into any system that exposes an MCP server — no custom\ncode in between."},"940":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-15","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-mcp-is-in-one-line","content":"Carbon's server exposes about 1,188 tools across 15 modules (Sales, Purchasing,\nItems, Production, Inventory, Quality, Accounting, and more). In short: almost anything you\ncan click in Carbon, an assistant can do through MCP."},"941":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-16","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#the-three-meta-tools","content":"A thousand-plus tools is too many to hand an assistant at once. So Carbon hides them behind\njust three tools. The assistant uses these to find and run everything else on demand."},"942":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-17","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#the-three-meta-tools","content":"The pattern is always: search → describe (if needed) → call. You never see these steps —\nyou just see the answer. Ask \"what's the on-hand quantity of A36 steel?\" and the assistant:"},"943":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-18","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#the-three-meta-tools","content":"Finds the tool. Runs search_tools({ query: \"inventory quantity\" }) and gets back\ncandidates like inventory_getItemQuantities."},"944":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-19","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#the-three-meta-tools","content":"Checks the inputs. If unsure, runs describe_tool to read which fields are required."},"945":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-20","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#the-three-meta-tools","content":"Calls it. Runs call_tool with the A36 plate's item ID, then answers in a sentence."},"946":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-21","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#three-safety-classes","content":"Reading a quantity is harmless; deleting a sales order is not. So Carbon tags every tool\nwith one of three safety classes. You can filter by them — for example,\nsearch_tools({ classification: \"READ\" }) returns only the look-but-don't-touch tools."},"947":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-22","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#three-safety-classes","content":"type: warn"},"948":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-23","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#three-safety-classes","content":"Treat WRITE and DESTRUCTIVE tools like a teammate with edit access. The assistant is\nchanging your live data, just like a colleague clicking the buttons. When exploring, keep\nit to READ tools. Turn on WRITE access deliberately, for one task, with a human checking\nthe result."},"949":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-24","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-you-can-actually-ask","content":"You don't memorize tool names. You describe what you want; the assistant finds the tools.\nHere are real asks against Acme's data."},"950":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-25","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-you-can-actually-ask","content":"\"What's the on-hand quantity of A36 steel?\""},"951":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-26","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-you-can-actually-ask","content":"A pure READ. Nothing changes. More safe reads:"},"952":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-27","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-you-can-actually-ask","content":"\"Show every job for Radiant Aerospace that isn't finished yet.\""},"953":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-28","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-you-can-actually-ask","content":"\"What did we invoice Radiant on AR000025, and is it paid?\""},"954":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-29","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-you-can-actually-ask","content":"\"List open purchase orders to Ryerson.\""},"955":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-30","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-you-can-actually-ask","content":"\"Which sales orders have been stuck in Needs Approval for 3+ days?\""},"956":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-31","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-you-can-actually-ask","content":"The assistant reads the order list, filters by status and date, and hands you the offenders.\nThis is MCP's sweet spot — a question that would take several filtered screens, answered in\none sentence. More triage:"},"957":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-32","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-you-can-actually-ask","content":"\"Any purchase orders in Draft older than a week?\" (PO000056 to Ryerson would surface.)"},"958":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-33","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-you-can-actually-ask","content":"\"List jobs past their due date that aren't complete.\""},"959":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-34","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-you-can-actually-ask","content":"\"Which invoices are overdue and unpaid?\""},"960":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-35","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-you-can-actually-ask","content":"\"Release every sales order stuck in Needs Approval for 3+ days.\""},"961":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-36","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-you-can-actually-ask","content":"Now the assistant reads to find the stuck orders, then issues a WRITE call to release\neach one. Approve WRITE access first, and ask to see the list before it acts. More actions:"},"962":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-37","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-you-can-actually-ask","content":"\"Create a quote for 500 Counterweight Hooks for Radiant Aerospace at $73.14 each.\""},"963":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-38","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-you-can-actually-ask","content":"\"Bump the priority on job J000099 to the top of the queue.\""},"964":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-39","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-you-can-actually-ask","content":"type: tip"},"965":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-40","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#what-you-can-actually-ask","content":"Good prompts are specific. \"Release the stuck orders\" works; \"Release sales orders in\nNeeds Approval with an order date 3+ days ago, and show me the list first\" gives the\nassistant a clean target and you a checkpoint."},"966":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-41","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#how-the-assistant-reaches-carbon","content":"On every request the assistant signs in as a real Carbon user, and Carbon enforces that\nuser's permissions on every call."},"967":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-42","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#how-the-assistant-reaches-carbon","content":"Sign-in is either an OAuth login (you log in to Carbon once; the assistant gets a\nscoped token) or an API key from Carbon's settings — the same key you'd use for the\nAPI."},"968":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-43","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#how-the-assistant-reaches-carbon","content":"Permissions come from whoever owns the credentials. If that user can't delete sales\norders in the app, the assistant can't either. MCP is a new doorway into Carbon, not a way\naround its permission model."},"969":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-44","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#how-the-assistant-reaches-carbon","content":"type: warn"},"970":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-45","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#how-the-assistant-reaches-carbon","content":"An API key is a password. Store it in your assistant's secret settings (never paste it into\na chat), give each integration its own key, and revoke a key the moment it's done."},"971":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-46","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#connect-an-assistant","content":"The menu differs by assistant, but the shape is the same: point it at Carbon's MCP URL and\ngive it credentials."},"972":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-47","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#connect-an-assistant","content":"Make credentials in Carbon. Open Settings → API keys and create a key (or set up\nOAuth). Copy it somewhere safe — you won't see it again."},"973":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-48","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#connect-an-assistant","content":"Add Carbon as an MCP server. In your assistant's connectors or MCP section, add a server\npointing at app.carbon.ms/mcp. Paste your key, or finish the OAuth sign-in."},"974":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-49","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#connect-an-assistant","content":"Confirm it. The assistant should now list Carbon's three meta-tools —\nsearch_tools, describe_tool, call_tool. That's exactly right; the full catalog stays\nhidden behind them."},"975":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-50","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#connect-an-assistant","content":"Start with a READ. Ask something safe, like \"List Radiant Aerospace's open jobs.\" If you\nget a sensible answer, you're connected. Only then move to WRITE asks, deliberately."},"976":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-51","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#connect-an-assistant","content":"Once connected, the assistant exposes Carbon's three meta-tools; everything else stays\nhidden behind them and is discovered on demand."},"977":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-52","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#connect-an-assistant","content":"type: info"},"978":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-53","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#connect-an-assistant","content":"call_tool takes on the safety class of whatever it runs. Calling\ninventory_getItemQuantities through it is a READ; calling sales_deleteSalesOrder through\nit is DESTRUCTIVE. So the READ-first habit still matters."},"979":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-54","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#a-worked-example","content":"Here's the full round-trip behind the on-hand-steel question. You'd only type the first line."},"980":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-55","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#a-worked-example","content":"That last sentence is the real value: the assistant didn't just fetch a number — it tied it\nto something you care about. You can't build a hook until you raise another\npurchase order to Ryerson, like PO000057."},"981":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-56","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#a-worked-example","content":"type: tip"},"982":{"id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai-57","page_id":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/mcp-and-ai#a-worked-example","content":"Because the assistant chains reads, you can ask layered questions: \"Do we have enough A36\nsteel to finish job J000099 (3,000 hooks), and if not, how much do we need to buy?\" It\nreads the job's material need, reads inventory, and does the math."},"983":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","type":"page","content":"Using the API","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api"},"984":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-0","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","content":"Carbon is API-first — create a key and make your first call."},"985":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-1","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"986":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-2","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#step-1--create-an-api-key","content":"Step 1 — Create an API key"},"987":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-3","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#open-settings--api-keys","content":"Open Settings → API Keys"},"988":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-4","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#click-new-api-key-and-name-it","content":"Click New API Key and name it"},"989":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-5","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#copy-the-secret-right-away","content":"Copy the secret right away"},"990":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-6","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#api-key-or-oauth","content":"API key or OAuth?"},"991":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-7","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#step-2--install-a-client-library","content":"Step 2 — Install a client library"},"992":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-8","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#step-3--make-your-first-call","content":"Step 3 — Make your first call"},"993":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-9","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#put-your-key-in-the-environment","content":"Put your key in the environment"},"994":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-10","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#list-your-items","content":"List your items"},"995":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-11","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#fetch-one-sales-order","content":"Fetch one sales order"},"996":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-12","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#good-to-know","content":"Good to know"},"997":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-13","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#the-full-reference-developer-docs","content":"The full reference: Developer Docs"},"998":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-14","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"999":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-15","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","content":"Anything you can do by clicking in Carbon, you can also do with code. Carbon is API-first:\nthe web app and the API talk to the same backend. If it's in the app, it's in the API."},"1000":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-16","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","content":"In three steps, you'll create a key, install a client, and read real data back out of Carbon."},"1001":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-17","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Module: Settings. Create and manage keys under Settings → API Keys. A key is a secret\nthat lets your code log in as you."},"1002":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-18","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"type: info"},"1003":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-19","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"If it's in the app, it's in the API. Carbon's UI is built on top of the public API, so\nevery feature is callable from your code the day it ships. That's the one thing to remember."},"1004":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-20","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Your code and the web app point at the same backend. The API isn't a copy of your data — it\nis your data."},"1005":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-21","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#open-settings--api-keys","content":"Go to Settings → API Keys. This page lists every key, who made it, and when it was last used."},"1006":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-22","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#click-new-api-key-and-name-it","content":"Click New API Key and give it a clear name (like Nightly export). Naming by purpose makes\nit easy to revoke the right one later."},"1007":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-23","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#click-new-api-key-and-name-it","content":"A key has the same permissions as the user who made it. If you can't approve purchase orders\nin the app, your key can't either. See Users & permissions."},"1008":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-24","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#copy-the-secret-right-away","content":"Carbon shows the full key value once. Copy it now and store it somewhere safe — a secrets\nmanager or password manager. Lose it and you just delete the key and make a new one."},"1009":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-25","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#copy-the-secret-right-away","content":"type: warn"},"1010":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-26","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#copy-the-secret-right-away","content":"Treat a key like a password. Anyone with it can act as you. Never put it in client-side\ncode, a public repo, or a screenshot. Keep it in an environment variable, and delete any key\nthe moment you think it leaked."},"1011":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-27","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#api-key-or-oauth","content":"Two ways to prove who's calling. Pick by whose data you're touching."},"1012":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-28","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#api-key-or-oauth","content":"An API key authenticates you (or one service account). Best for the work most readers do:"},"1013":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-29","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#api-key-or-oauth","content":"A nightly script that exports your orders."},"1014":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-30","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#api-key-or-oauth","content":"A backend that pushes shipments into Carbon."},"1015":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-31","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#api-key-or-oauth","content":"One-off migration or reporting jobs."},"1016":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-32","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#api-key-or-oauth","content":"Send it as a header. Carbon reads your company from the key automatically:"},"1017":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-33","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#api-key-or-oauth","content":"OAuth is for apps that act on behalf of other Carbon users — a product where its users\nconnect their Carbon account. Your app sends each user through a consent screen and gets a\nshort-lived token scoped to that user."},"1018":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-34","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#api-key-or-oauth","content":"Automating your own company? Use an API key and skip OAuth. Building an app other companies\ninstall? The full OAuth flow is in the Developer Docs."},"1019":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-35","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#api-key-or-oauth","content":"type: info"},"1020":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-36","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#api-key-or-oauth","content":"Rule of thumb: automating your data → API key. Building an app other customers log\ninto → OAuth."},"1021":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-37","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#step-2--install-a-client-library","content":"You can call Carbon with raw HTTP, but the official client libraries handle auth, paging,\nand errors for you. Reach for these first."},"1022":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-38","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#step-2--install-a-client-library","content":"type: tip"},"1023":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-39","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#step-2--install-a-client-library","content":"Always-current package names and install commands live in the Clients section of\nthe Developer Docs."},"1024":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-40","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#step-3--make-your-first-call","content":"To prove your key works, read something — don't write. You'll list items, then fetch one\nsales order: the Counterweight Hook (CWH-A36-15) and its order, SO000069."},"1025":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-41","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#put-your-key-in-the-environment","content":"Don't hard-code the secret. Set it once so your code reads it at runtime:"},"1026":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-42","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#list-your-items","content":"Ask Carbon for a page of items. Rows back means your key works."},"1027":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-43","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#list-your-items","content":"You get back the same item records you see under the Items module:"},"1028":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-44","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#fetch-one-sales-order","content":"Now grab a single record: SO000069, Radiant Aerospace's order for 500 Counterweight Hooks."},"1029":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-45","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#fetch-one-sales-order","content":"This is the same record the Sales Order page shows — same\nnumbers, no copy:"},"1030":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-46","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#fetch-one-sales-order","content":"type: tip"},"1031":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-47","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#fetch-one-sales-order","content":"Read before you write. Read endpoints can't change anything, so they're safe to learn on.\nWhen you're ready to write (creating a quote line, releasing a job), use a test or demo\ncompany first — never your live data."},"1032":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-48","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#good-to-know","content":"List endpoints return one page at a time. Pass limit (how many) and offset (how many to\nskip): limit: 50, offset: 50 gets the second page of fifty. A count tells you the total."},"1033":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-49","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#good-to-know","content":"Records have two IDs: a friendly readable ID (SO000069, CWH-A36-15) and an internal\nrecord ID used in URLs (so_Fx6FCeSpx9sxut9Qns6y91). Fetch by either. Readable IDs are for\npeople; internal IDs are stable references for linking records."},"1034":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-50","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#good-to-know","content":"Standard HTTP codes: 401 key missing or wrong, 403 key lacks permission, 404 record not\nfound, 429 too many requests. The clients surface these as typed errors. On a 429, wait and\nretry."},"1035":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-51","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#good-to-know","content":"Dates are ISO 8601 strings (2026-06-11). Money comes back as plain numbers in the base\ncurrency (USD for Acme) — 36820 is $36,820.00. Format it for display on your side."},"1036":{"id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api-52","page_id":"/manual/developing/using-the-api","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/developing/using-the-api#the-full-reference-developer-docs","content":"This page is the on-ramp. For every endpoint, field, auth flow, and webhook, go to the\nDeveloper Docs:"},"1037":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","type":"page","content":"Locations & stock","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock"},"1038":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-0","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","content":"Warehouses, shelves, on-hand quantities and the item ledger."},"1039":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-1","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"1040":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-2","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#the-four-building-blocks","content":"The four building blocks"},"1041":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-3","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#locations","content":"Locations"},"1042":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-4","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#storage-units-shelves--bins","content":"Storage units (shelves & bins)"},"1043":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-5","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#on-hand-quantities","content":"On-hand quantities"},"1044":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-6","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#the-item-ledger","content":"The item ledger"},"1045":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-7","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#fix-a-count-inventory-adjustment","content":"Fix a count: inventory adjustment"},"1046":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-8","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#verify-counts-cycle-count","content":"Verify counts: cycle count"},"1047":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-9","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"1048":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-10","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","content":"Carbon always knows two things about your stuff: where it is and how much you have.\nThis page shows how the Inventory module tracks both."},"1049":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-11","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"This all lives in the Inventory module. Open it, then go to Quantities to see\non-hand stock for every item, with its reorder policy."},"1050":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-12","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#the-four-building-blocks","content":"Inventory is just four ideas stacked together:"},"1051":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-13","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#the-four-building-blocks","content":"We'll follow one item to make it real: Acme's stock of A36 Steel Plate 1″\n(A36-STEEL-PLT-1\".96x240), the raw material for the\nCounterweight Hook."},"1052":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-14","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#locations","content":"A location is a physical site where you hold stock. Small shops run one; bigger ones run\nseveral. Acme has two:"},"1053":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-15","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#locations","content":"On-hand is always per location. The same item can have one amount at Headquarters and\nanother in Texas. Carbon never mixes them. Acme builds the Counterweight Hook at Headquarters."},"1054":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-16","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#locations","content":"type: tip"},"1055":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-17","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#locations","content":"Moving stock between sites is a transfer, not an adjustment. Use a stock transfer so the\namount that leaves one site is exactly the amount that arrives at the other."},"1056":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-18","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#storage-units-shelves--bins","content":"Inside a location, a storage unit pins down exactly where something sits — a shelf, rack,\nrow, or bin. They can nest (a warehouse holds rows, a row holds bins)."},"1057":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-19","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#storage-units-shelves--bins","content":"Acme names bins by position. R02-B01-01 means Rack 02, Row B, Level 01,\nPosition 01. The A36 Steel Plate lives in R02-B01-01. That bin is its default\nstorage unit, so Carbon suggests it automatically when you receive or pick the plate."},"1058":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-20","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#storage-units-shelves--bins","content":"type: info"},"1059":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-21","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#storage-units-shelves--bins","content":"Item vs. storage unit. An item is what the thing is (A36 Steel Plate). A storage\nunit is where a quantity of it sits (bin R02-B01-01). One item can live in several\nbins; one bin can hold several items."},"1060":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-22","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#on-hand-quantities","content":"On-hand is just one of several numbers Carbon tracks per item. Open the Counterweight\nHook and check the Inventory tab: 100 are in stock, but 4,500 are already promised\nto Radiant Aerospace on open sales orders."},"1061":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-23","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#on-hand-quantities","content":"Here's what each number means:"},"1062":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-24","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#on-hand-quantities","content":"type: tip"},"1063":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-25","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#on-hand-quantities","content":"Available is the number to watch when promising work: roughly on hand minus committed,\nplus confidently inbound. For a buy-to-stock material like A36 plate, a low available number\nis your cue to reorder. The hook is Make-to-Order, so Carbon builds each batch on a job\ninstead of stocking ahead."},"1064":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-26","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#the-item-ledger","content":"Behind those live numbers sits the item ledger — a log of every stock move, ever.\nReceipts, job consumption, shipments, and adjustments each write one row. On-hand is just the\nrunning total of the ledger, so every number traces back to the move that caused it."},"1065":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-27","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#the-item-ledger","content":"Every row names the document that caused it, so the ledger doubles as an audit trail: who\nmoved this, when, and why."},"1066":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-28","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#the-item-ledger","content":"type: info"},"1067":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-29","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#the-item-ledger","content":"Batch tracking. A36 Steel Plate has batch tracking on, so Carbon records a batch\nnumber (often the supplier's heat number) on receipt and remembers which batch went into\nwhich finished parts. That's genealogy — full detail in\nTracking quality."},"1068":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-30","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#fix-a-count-inventory-adjustment","content":"When the shelf and Carbon disagree, an inventory adjustment makes Carbon match reality.\nIt writes one ledger entry and posts the value change to the books."},"1069":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-31","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#fix-a-count-inventory-adjustment","content":"Open the item at the right location. Adjustments are per location — adjusting at\nHeadquarters never touches Texas."},"1070":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-32","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#fix-a-count-inventory-adjustment","content":"Start the adjustment. Choose Adjust quantity and pick the storage unit, e.g.\nR02-B01-01."},"1071":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-33","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#fix-a-count-inventory-adjustment","content":"Enter the corrected quantity, not the difference. If Carbon says 17,507 LB but you\ncounted 17,450, type the new on-hand — Carbon works out the −57 LB. If the item is\nbatch-tracked, pick which batch."},"1072":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-34","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#fix-a-count-inventory-adjustment","content":"Add a reason and post. Pick a reason (damaged, miscount, found stock). Posting updates\non-hand, writes the ledger entry, and books the value change."},"1073":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-35","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#fix-a-count-inventory-adjustment","content":"type: warn"},"1074":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-36","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#fix-a-count-inventory-adjustment","content":"Adjustments are for corrections only. Don't adjust stock down to \"use it up\" (that's\nconsuming material on a job) or to move it between sites\n(that's a transfer)."},"1075":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-37","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#verify-counts-cycle-count","content":"A cycle count is a scheduled count of part of your inventory — a few bins at a time,\nrotating through everything — so you catch drift without stopping production."},"1076":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-38","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#verify-counts-cycle-count","content":"Pick what to count. A rack, an item class, or your highest-value stock. Counting the\ncostliest items most often (an \"ABC\" approach) catches the errors that matter most."},"1077":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-39","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#verify-counts-cycle-count","content":"Pull the count sheet and walk the floor. A counter writes down what's actually in each\nbin — ideally without seeing the expected number, so the count stays honest."},"1078":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-40","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#verify-counts-cycle-count","content":"Enter the counted quantities. Carbon compares each to the expected on-hand and flags any\nvariance."},"1079":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-41","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#verify-counts-cycle-count","content":"Post the variances. For each bin that differs, Carbon posts an adjustment so the ledger,\non-hand, and books all move together."},"1080":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-42","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#verify-counts-cycle-count","content":"type: tip"},"1081":{"id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock-43","page_id":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/locations-and-stock#verify-counts-cycle-count","content":"Treat a bin that's always short as a signal, not just a number to fix — the cause is usually\nupstream (material used but never recorded on a job, or scrap that skipped the system)."},"1082":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","type":"page","content":"Shipping & receiving","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving"},"1083":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-0","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","content":"Move goods in and out with shipments and receipts."},"1084":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-1","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"1085":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-2","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#receive-against-a-purchase-order","content":"Receive against a purchase order"},"1086":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-3","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#start-the-receipt","content":"Start the receipt"},"1087":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-4","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#confirm-what-actually-arrived","content":"Confirm what actually arrived"},"1088":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-5","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#record-the-batch-if-asked","content":"Record the batch (if asked)"},"1089":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-6","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#tell-carbon-where-it-goes","content":"Tell Carbon where it goes"},"1090":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-7","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#post-the-receipt","content":"Post the receipt"},"1091":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-8","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#ship-against-a-sales-order","content":"Ship against a sales order"},"1092":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-9","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#start-the-shipment","content":"Start the shipment"},"1093":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-10","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#pick-the-finished-goods","content":"Pick the finished goods"},"1094":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-11","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#choose-a-shipping-method","content":"Choose a shipping method"},"1095":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-12","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#add-tracking-optional","content":"Add tracking (optional)"},"1096":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-13","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#post-the-shipment","content":"Post the shipment"},"1097":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-14","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#one-number-entered-once","content":"One number, entered once"},"1098":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-15","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#common-questions","content":"Common questions"},"1099":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-16","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"1100":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-17","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","content":"Goods cross your dock two ways:"},"1101":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-18","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","content":"In from a supplier — that's a receipt. It closes a purchase order line."},"1102":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-19","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","content":"Out to a customer — that's a shipment. It closes a sales order line."},"1103":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-20","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","content":"You never start from scratch. Each one points back to a document you already made."},"1104":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-21","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Both live in the Inventory module. Open it from the home screen, then use the sub-nav at the top to switch between Quantities, Receipts, and Shipments."},"1105":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-22","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"type: tip"},"1106":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-23","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"\"Post\" is the verb that matters. Until you post, a receipt or shipment is a draft you can edit or delete — nothing has moved. Posting is the commit: stock levels change and the source document updates. Get the numbers right before you post."},"1107":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-24","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#receive-against-a-purchase-order","content":"When a truck arrives with material you ordered, you create a receipt against the matching PO. Carbon already knows the part, quantity, and price — you're mostly confirming reality."},"1108":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-25","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#receive-against-a-purchase-order","content":"For the hero thread, Acme ordered 54,001 LB of A36 Steel Plate from Ryerson on PO000057."},"1109":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-26","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#start-the-receipt","content":"Go to Inventory → Receipts → New and pick PO000057 (or open the PO and choose Receive). Carbon copies the open lines onto a fresh Draft receipt."},"1110":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-27","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#start-the-receipt","content":"type: warn"},"1111":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-28","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#start-the-receipt","content":"The PO must be issued to the supplier first. You can't receive against a PO that's still a draft."},"1112":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-29","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#confirm-what-actually-arrived","content":"Each line pre-fills with the quantity still outstanding. Edit the received quantity to match the packing slip:"},"1113":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-30","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#confirm-what-actually-arrived","content":"Exact — all 54,001 LB came. Leave it as-is."},"1114":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-31","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#confirm-what-actually-arrived","content":"Short — receive what arrived; the PO line stays open for the rest."},"1115":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-32","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#confirm-what-actually-arrived","content":"Over — Carbon flags the overage so you can accept it or send it back."},"1116":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-33","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#record-the-batch-if-asked","content":"A36 Steel Plate is batch-tracked, so Carbon asks which heat of steel this is. Type the supplier's heat/lot number into the Batch field. This is what later lets you trace the steel that went into Radiant's hooks. Plain items don't show this field."},"1117":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-34","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#tell-carbon-where-it-goes","content":"Each line needs a location and shelf (bin). Acme's steel lives at Headquarters in bin R02-B01-01 — its default — so the receipt suggests it for you. Change it if you're stocking it elsewhere."},"1118":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-35","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#post-the-receipt","content":"Choose Post. At that instant:"},"1119":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-36","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#post-the-receipt","content":"On-hand stock of A36 Steel Plate goes up in bin R02-B01-01."},"1120":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-37","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#post-the-receipt","content":"The PO line moves toward Received / To Invoice."},"1121":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-38","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#post-the-receipt","content":"The material is now real stock the job can pull from."},"1122":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-39","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#ship-against-a-sales-order","content":"Once parts are made and inspected, you send them. A shipment records what left the building, against the sales order. Job J000097 finished all 500 Counterweight Hooks; now they ship to Radiant Aerospace on SO000069."},"1123":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-40","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#start-the-shipment","content":"Go to Inventory → Shipments → New and pick SO000069 (or open the order and choose Ship). Carbon brings the order lines across as a Draft."},"1124":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-41","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#pick-the-finished-goods","content":"Picking is choosing which stock fills the shipment. Carbon pulls the hooks from the job's finished-goods bin (8-1-H). Confirm the quantity per line — here, all 500 EA. For batch/serial items, you pick the exact lots here, which closes the traceability loop."},"1125":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-42","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#pick-the-finished-goods","content":"type: warn"},"1126":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-43","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#pick-the-finished-goods","content":"You can only ship what you have. Carbon won't let you ship more than is on hand. Short shipments are fine — the SO line stays open for the balance."},"1127":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-44","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#choose-a-shipping-method","content":"The shipping method is the carrier the goods leave on. Acme has ten configured. A pallet of 500 steel hooks is freight, not a parcel — so pick LTL (Less Than Truckload) or FTL (Full Truckload), not UPS Ground."},"1128":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-45","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#choose-a-shipping-method","content":"type: tip"},"1129":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-46","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#choose-a-shipping-method","content":"The method is where a shipping cost rides along. SO000069 carries $250 of freight, which shows on the invoice but not in the goods subtotal."},"1130":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-47","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#add-tracking-optional","content":"If the carrier gives you a tracking number, add it here with package counts and weights. It travels with the record so anyone can answer \"where is it?\" later."},"1131":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-48","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#post-the-shipment","content":"Choose Post. A cascade fires:"},"1132":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-49","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#post-the-shipment","content":"The 500 hooks leave inventory from the picking bin."},"1133":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-50","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#post-the-shipment","content":"The SO line shows 500 of 500 sent and moves toward Completed."},"1134":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-51","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#post-the-shipment","content":"A shipment record is created — the link the invoice reads from next."},"1135":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-52","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#one-number-entered-once","content":"You recorded one fact — \"500 hooks left the dock\" — and Carbon updated everything downstream. Acme can now raise sales invoice AR000025, built straight from what shipped (500 EA at $73.14, plus $250 freight), with no re-keying."},"1136":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-53","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#common-questions","content":"Yes. Receipts and shipments are per-line and per-quantity. Receive 30,000 of 54,001 LB today and the PO line stays open for the rest; ship 200 of 500 hooks and the SO line keeps the other 300 open. A line only goes \"complete\" once the full quantity has moved."},"1137":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-54","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#common-questions","content":"Posting is a committed inventory transaction, so you don't just edit it after the fact. You reverse it with a correcting movement — a negative inventory adjustment, a return, or a credit — which keeps a clean audit trail. Fix it before you post whenever you can."},"1138":{"id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving-55","page_id":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/inventory/shipping-receiving#common-questions","content":"Only when the item asks for one. The field shows up for batch- or serial-tracked items, like A36 Steel Plate. Plain Inventory items, like the finished Counterweight Hook, just track a quantity and skip the step."},"1139":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","type":"page","content":"Jobs","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs"},"1140":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-0","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","content":"Create production jobs from a sales order or from scratch."},"1141":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-1","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"1142":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-2","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#what-a-job-carries","content":"What a job carries"},"1143":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-3","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#how-a-job-gets-created","content":"How a job gets created"},"1144":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-4","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#the-fields-that-drive-a-job","content":"The fields that drive a job"},"1145":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-5","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#the-method-the-job-carries","content":"The method the job carries"},"1146":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-6","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#operations-the-steps-in-order","content":"Operations: the steps, in order"},"1147":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-7","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#materials-what-the-job-consumes","content":"Materials: what the job consumes"},"1148":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-8","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#releasing-a-job-to-the-floor","content":"Releasing a job to the floor"},"1149":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-9","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#job-statuses","content":"Job statuses"},"1150":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-10","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#where-the-numbers-go-next","content":"Where the numbers go next"},"1151":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-11","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"1152":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-12","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","content":"A job tells the shop floor to make a set quantity of a part by a set date."},"1153":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-13","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","content":"We'll follow one real job: J000097 — 500 Counterweight Hooks for Radiant Aerospace."},"1154":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-14","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Jobs live in the Production module. Open it from the home screen, and the dashboard shows\nyour live shop at a glance — Active Jobs, work center use, and more. Click View Active\nJobs to see the full list."},"1155":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-15","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#what-a-job-carries","content":"One job answers five questions:"},"1156":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-16","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#what-a-job-carries","content":"What are we making? The part — here, CWH-A36-15, the Counterweight Hook."},"1157":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-17","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#what-a-job-carries","content":"How many? The production quantity — 500 EA."},"1158":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-18","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#what-a-job-carries","content":"By when? The due date — 2026-06-26."},"1159":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-19","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#what-a-job-carries","content":"How is it made? The method — its materials and steps."},"1160":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-20","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#what-a-job-carries","content":"Where are we? The status, and how many good pieces are done."},"1161":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-21","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#what-a-job-carries","content":"The big idea: a job carries its own copy of the method. When you create it, Carbon\nsnapshots the part's bill of materials and routing onto the job. Edit the part's master\nmethod later — this job keeps the recipe it was born with."},"1162":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-22","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#what-a-job-carries","content":"That's what keeps a finished job's cost and\ntraceability trustworthy months later."},"1163":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-23","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#what-a-job-carries","content":"type: tip"},"1164":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-24","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#what-a-job-carries","content":"Method = BOM + Routing. The bill of materials (BOM) is what the part is made of;\nthe routing is the ordered steps to make it. A job copies both. See\nMethods: BOM & routing."},"1165":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-25","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#how-a-job-gets-created","content":"There are two ways."},"1166":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-26","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#how-a-job-gets-created","content":"1. Automatically, from a Make-to-Order sales order line. Carbon offers to spin up a job,\npre-filled with the part, quantity, customer and due date — and keeps it linked to the line.\nThat's how J000097 was born, straight from\nsales order SO000069."},"1167":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-27","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#how-a-job-gets-created","content":"type: info"},"1168":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-28","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#how-a-job-gets-created","content":"The same link happens for Radiant's other orders: SO000070 made job J000098 (1,500 EA)\nand SO000071 made job J000099 (3,000 EA). One part, three orders, three jobs."},"1169":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-29","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#how-a-job-gets-created","content":"2. Manually, when a job stands on its own — building to stock, a rework batch, or a\none-off. Here's the click path:"},"1170":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-30","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#how-a-job-gets-created","content":"Open the Jobs list. In the Production module, click View Active Jobs (or open\nJobs). Click New Job."},"1171":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-31","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#how-a-job-gets-created","content":"Pick the part. Choose a Make item like CWH-A36-15.\nCarbon pulls in its description and unit of measure (EA)."},"1172":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-32","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#how-a-job-gets-created","content":"Set quantity, due date and priority. Enter how many to make, when they're due, and how\nurgent the job is."},"1173":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-33","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#how-a-job-gets-created","content":"Save. Carbon assigns the next job number and snapshots the method. The job opens as\nPlanned, ready for review."},"1174":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-34","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#the-fields-that-drive-a-job","content":"Open J000097 and you land on its Details tab. A few fields do most of the work."},"1175":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-35","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#the-fields-that-drive-a-job","content":"Production quantity — how many good pieces to finish. Here, 500."},"1176":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-36","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#the-fields-that-drive-a-job","content":"Due date — when they must be done. The deadline type (Hard Deadline here) tells\nCarbon how firm that date is."},"1177":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-37","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#the-fields-that-drive-a-job","content":"Priority — ranks this job against others for the same machines. J000097 is 1, the\nhighest, so it jumps the queue."},"1178":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-38","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#the-fields-that-drive-a-job","content":"type: tip"},"1179":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-39","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#the-fields-that-drive-a-job","content":"Location matters. A job runs at one\nlocation. J000097 runs at Headquarters, so it\nuses Headquarters work centers (like Burn Table — PA2) and pulls material from Headquarters\nstock."},"1180":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-40","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#the-method-the-job-carries","content":"Click the Method tab to see the recipe Carbon copied onto the job. For the Counterweight\nHook it's short: one material, three operations."},"1181":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-41","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#the-method-the-job-carries","content":"Two things to notice:"},"1182":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-42","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#the-method-the-job-carries","content":"The BOM has one material line: 40 LB of A36 steel plate per piece. Times 500, the job\nneeds 20,000 LB — Carbon does the math."},"1183":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-43","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#the-method-the-job-carries","content":"The material is Pull from Inventory, so the job draws steel from stock. The\npurchase order to Ryerson makes sure that stock is there."},"1184":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-44","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#the-method-the-job-carries","content":"type: info"},"1185":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-45","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#the-method-the-job-carries","content":"Because the job carries its own copy of the method, you can tweak it for this run only —\nswap a material, add a step, change a time — without touching the part's master method or any\nother job."},"1186":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-46","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#operations-the-steps-in-order","content":"The Operations tab lists the routing. Each operation runs at one work center and has a\ntime per piece. They run in sequence — Sandblasting can't start until Flame Cut is done."},"1187":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-47","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#operations-the-steps-in-order","content":"Labor time is per piece. As operators report finished pieces in the\nshop-floor app, the Complete and Status columns\nfill in — that's how all three reached Done."},"1188":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-48","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#operations-the-steps-in-order","content":"type: tip"},"1189":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-49","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#operations-the-steps-in-order","content":"The last operation, Inspection, is a quality gate: the parts aren't finished until they\npass. See Tracking quality."},"1190":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-50","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#materials-what-the-job-consumes","content":"The Materials tab is the job's shopping list. For J000097 it's one line."},"1191":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-51","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#materials-what-the-job-consumes","content":"The steel is batch-tracked, so Carbon records exactly which heat went into this batch of\nhooks — the foundation of Radiant's traceability. It pulls\nfrom bin R02-B01-01 at Headquarters."},"1192":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-52","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#releasing-a-job-to-the-floor","content":"A new job is Planned — a draft you can edit freely. Nothing reaches the floor until you\nrelease it."},"1193":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-53","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#releasing-a-job-to-the-floor","content":"Review the job. Confirm quantity, due date and priority on Details, then skim\nMethod, Operations and Materials."},"1194":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-54","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#releasing-a-job-to-the-floor","content":"Check material. Carbon flags shortages. For J000097, not all 20,000 LB of steel was on\nhand, so Acme raised PO000057 to Ryerson. Buying and making\ncan run in parallel."},"1195":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-55","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#releasing-a-job-to-the-floor","content":"Release the job. Click Release. Carbon stamps the released date, moves the job into the\nactive queue, and makes its operations available in the\nshop-floor app."},"1196":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-56","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#releasing-a-job-to-the-floor","content":"The floor takes over. Operators clock onto each operation and report pieces. When the last\noperation hits the production quantity, the job is Completed."},"1197":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-57","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#job-statuses","content":"A job moves through four statuses, from idea to finished parts:"},"1198":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-58","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#job-statuses","content":"type: warn"},"1199":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-59","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#job-statuses","content":"A Planned job does nothing on its own. It won't appear on the shop floor and operators\ncan't book time until you release it. If a job seems \"stuck,\" check whether it's still\nPlanned."},"1200":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs-60","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/jobs#where-the-numbers-go-next","content":"Once J000097 completed, its 500 hooks were received to stock, shipped to Radiant Aerospace,\nand billed on invoice AR000025. The job's labor and material\nrolled up into the cost of those parts."},"1201":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","type":"page","content":"Managing production","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production"},"1202":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-0","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","content":"Schedule, track and plan work across the shop."},"1203":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-1","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"1204":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-2","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-1-demand-in-plan-out","content":"Step 1: Demand in, plan out"},"1205":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-3","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-2-review-suggestions-in-planning","content":"Step 2: Review suggestions in Planning"},"1206":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-4","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-3-schedule-jobs-across-work-centers","content":"Step 3: Schedule jobs across work centers"},"1207":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-5","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-4-prioritize-what-runs-first","content":"Step 4: Prioritize what runs first"},"1208":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-6","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-5-track-progress","content":"Step 5: Track progress"},"1209":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-7","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"1210":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-8","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","content":"One job is easy to watch. Dozens at once is the real job. This page shows how Carbon turns customer demand into a plan, tells you what to make and what to buy, and shows you whether the shop is on track."},"1211":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-9","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"This is the Production module. Open it from the home screen, then use Planning, Jobs, and the dashboard inside it."},"1212":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-10","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"The dashboard is your shop at a glance: Active Jobs, Work Center Utilization, and which machines are busy. Acme runs work through machines like the DMU 50, the Inspection Station, and its Burn Tables."},"1213":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-11","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-1-demand-in-plan-out","content":"Carbon's planning compares two things:"},"1214":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-12","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-1-demand-in-plan-out","content":"Demand — what's needed: open sales orders, materials jobs will consume, safety stock."},"1215":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-13","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-1-demand-in-plan-out","content":"Supply — what covers it: stock on hand, open purchase orders, jobs in progress."},"1216":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-14","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-1-demand-in-plan-out","content":"Where demand beats supply, Carbon raises a suggestion. For a Buy item, that's a purchase order. For a Make item, it's a job."},"1217":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-15","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-1-demand-in-plan-out","content":"Here's a real example. Sales order SO000069 needs 500 Counterweight Hooks. Each hook uses 40 LB of A36 steel plate, so that's 20,000 LB of steel. Acme doesn't have that on the shelf, so Carbon suggests buying it — which became PO000057 to Ryerson. The hook itself is a Make part, so the order became job J000097."},"1218":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-16","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-1-demand-in-plan-out","content":"type: tip"},"1219":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-17","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-1-demand-in-plan-out","content":"Make vs Buy is one setting on each item. The hook is Make; its steel is Buy. That flag decides whether a shortage becomes a job or a PO. See Replenishment."},"1220":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-18","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-2-review-suggestions-in-planning","content":"Open Production → Planning. You get one row per item that needs attention — what's required, what's available, the shortage, and the suggested action."},"1221":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-19","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-2-review-suggestions-in-planning","content":"Set the horizon. At the top, choose how far ahead to look. Carbon only raises suggestions for demand inside the horizon."},"1222":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-20","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-2-review-suggestions-in-planning","content":"Read each row. When Short is above zero, Carbon proposes an action. 20,000 LB of steel with nothing on hand produces a Buy → PO."},"1223":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-21","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-2-review-suggestions-in-planning","content":"Adjust before you commit. Change a quantity or pull a date earlier. Acme's PO000057 ended up at 54,001 LB — the buyer rounded up to cover the next two Radiant orders."},"1224":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-22","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-2-review-suggestions-in-planning","content":"Convert what you accept. Buy suggestions become draft purchase orders; Make suggestions become jobs. Carbon links each one back to the demand that created it."},"1225":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-23","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-2-review-suggestions-in-planning","content":"type: warn"},"1226":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-24","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-2-review-suggestions-in-planning","content":"A suggestion is a proposal, never automatic. Carbon won't raise a PO or release a job on its own — you always confirm."},"1227":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-25","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-3-schedule-jobs-across-work-centers","content":"Every operation in a job points at a work center — a machine or station like the DMU 50 or a Burn Table. Each operation carries a time, and operations run After Previous (step 20 waits for step 10). That's how Carbon builds a schedule."},"1228":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-26","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-3-schedule-jobs-across-work-centers","content":"Job J000097 ran three operations in sequence:"},"1229":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-27","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-3-schedule-jobs-across-work-centers","content":"Find the bottleneck. The dashboard's Work Center Utilization shows load per machine. Acme has three Burn Tables but only one Sand Blasting Room — so sandblasting is the constraint."},"1230":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-28","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-3-schedule-jobs-across-work-centers","content":"Balance the load. When a process has more than one machine, move work to a less-busy one. Flame Cut can run on Burn Table PA1, PA2, or the Texas table."},"1231":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-29","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-3-schedule-jobs-across-work-centers","content":"Respect the sequence. Operations run After Previous, so Carbon keeps them in order. You decide where the whole chain fits against other jobs."},"1232":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-30","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-3-schedule-jobs-across-work-centers","content":"type: tip"},"1233":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-31","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-3-schedule-jobs-across-work-centers","content":"Work-center rates also cost your jobs. Time booked on Burn Table PA2 absorbs labor at $50/hr and machine at $25/hr — so J000097's cost came from recorded shop time, not a guess."},"1234":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-32","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-4-prioritize-what-runs-first","content":"When more work wants a machine than it can handle, priority and due date decide the order. Here's Acme's live Counterweight Hook backlog — three jobs for the same customer, stacked up:"},"1235":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-33","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-4-prioritize-what-runs-first","content":"Read it as a plan: J000097 finished first, J000098 is running now, J000099 is staged and Ready. Sequencing by due date keeps the single Sand Blasting Room from causing a missed deadline."},"1236":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-34","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-4-prioritize-what-runs-first","content":"type: warn"},"1237":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-35","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-4-prioritize-what-runs-first","content":"A job must be released before the floor can touch it. Statuses go in order: Draft → Planned → Ready → In Progress → Completed. Releasing is on the Jobs page."},"1238":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-36","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-5-track-progress","content":"The jobs list is your live status board. Completion updates itself as operators record finished pieces in the shop floor app — you never type a percentage by hand."},"1239":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-37","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-5-track-progress","content":"What to read off this screen:"},"1240":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-38","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-5-track-progress","content":"Completion is real. J000097 shows 500 of 500 because operators clocked off all 500 pieces."},"1241":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-39","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-5-track-progress","content":"Status says where to look. In Progress jobs are on the floor now — J000095 and J000098 get today's attention."},"1242":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-40","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-5-track-progress","content":"Due dates flag risk. J000095 is due 2026-04-23 — already past — and still running. That's your cue to investigate."},"1243":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-41","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-5-track-progress","content":"type: info"},"1244":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production-42","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/managing-production#step-5-track-progress","content":"The loop. Demand creates suggestions → you turn them into jobs and POs → you schedule jobs across work centers → operators run them → the dashboard updates in real time → new demand restarts it."},"1245":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","type":"page","content":"The shop floor (MES)","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor"},"1246":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-0","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","content":"How operators run jobs: clock in, record quantities and complete operations."},"1247":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-1","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"1248":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-2","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#what-an-operator-sees","content":"What an operator sees"},"1249":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-3","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#run-an-operation-start-to-finish","content":"Run an operation, start to finish"},"1250":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-4","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#open-the-operation","content":"Open the operation"},"1251":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-5","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#read-the-standard-procedure","content":"Read the standard procedure"},"1252":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-6","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#clock-on","content":"Clock ON"},"1253":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-7","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#record-good-and-scrap","content":"Record good and scrap"},"1254":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-8","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#clock-off-and-complete","content":"Clock OFF and complete"},"1255":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-9","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#what-clocking-off-feeds-back","content":"What clocking off feeds back"},"1256":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-10","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#the-last-operation-finishes-the-job","content":"The last operation finishes the job"},"1257":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-11","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"1258":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-12","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","content":"This is where planned work gets done. An operator picks an operation, clocks on, records good and scrap counts, and clocks off. Every tap feeds real labor time and cost back to the job — no clipboards."},"1259":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-13","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"The shop floor is the Shop Floor module, delivered as its own app: the MES (Manufacturing Execution System)."},"1260":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-14","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"The ERP is the full office app — Sales, Purchasing, Items, Production. Jobs are planned and costed there."},"1261":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-15","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"The MES is a stripped-down, touch-friendly app for a shop-floor tablet. It shows an operator only what they need: the operations waiting at their work center, the instructions, and big Start, Pause and Finish buttons."},"1262":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-16","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Both read the same job, so you never enter anything twice. A manager watches it all from the Production module in the ERP."},"1263":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-17","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"type: tip"},"1264":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-18","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Operators open the MES at its own address (think mes.carbon.ms) and sign in with their own account. A worker who only runs machines never has to learn the full ERP."},"1265":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-19","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"We'll follow one real job: J000097 — 500 Counterweight Hooks (CWH-A36-15) for Radiant Aerospace. It runs three operations in order: Flame Cut → Sandblasting → Inspection."},"1266":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-20","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#what-an-operator-sees","content":"The MES shows only the operations queued at the operator's work center — not the whole factory. Each row is one operation on one job. Fred Flame works the burn tables, so his queue leads with the Flame Cut on J000097."},"1267":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-21","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#what-an-operator-sees","content":"Two things to know:"},"1268":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-22","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#what-an-operator-sees","content":"The queue filters by work center, not by job. Fred sees Flame Cut work from several jobs at once. An operator at the Sand Blasting Room sees a different list."},"1269":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-23","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#what-an-operator-sees","content":"An operation turns Ready only after the step before it finishes. So a job's three operations light up one at a time, in order."},"1270":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-24","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#run-an-operation-start-to-finish","content":"Fred runs the Flame Cut on J000097: 500 hooks, on Burn Table - PA2."},"1271":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-25","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#open-the-operation","content":"Tap the Flame Cut row. The MES shows an operation card — what to make, how many, from what, and how."},"1272":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-26","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#open-the-operation","content":"The Materials tab shows what to pull: 40 LB of A36 Steel Plate 1″ per piece, from bin R02-B01-01."},"1273":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-27","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#open-the-operation","content":"The Tools tab lists any tooling the step needs."},"1274":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-28","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#open-the-operation","content":"Because the steel is batch-tracked, the operator picks which batch they used — that's what makes traceability possible later."},"1275":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-29","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#read-the-standard-procedure","content":"Most operations have a procedure attached — Carbon's name for a standard work instruction. The operator ticks off each step as they go."},"1276":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-30","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#read-the-standard-procedure","content":"Steps aren't only checkboxes. A step can also ask the operator to type a measurement (with a min and max, so bad values are caught on the spot), pick from a list, or attach a photo. A laminated sheet becomes recorded, checkable data."},"1277":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-31","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#read-the-standard-procedure","content":"type: tip"},"1278":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-32","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#read-the-standard-procedure","content":"Procedures are versioned. Operators always run the Active version; managers can revise a draft without disrupting the floor. Build them in the ERP's Production module."},"1279":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-33","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#clock-on","content":"Tap Start. This clocks the operator ON and starts a timer. From here, every minute counts against the job — at Burn Table - PA2's rate of $50/hour labor, that time is becoming real cost on J000097."},"1280":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-34","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#clock-on","content":"Tap Pause to step away — the timer stops, so breaks aren't billed to the job."},"1281":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-35","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#clock-on","content":"type: warn"},"1282":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-36","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#clock-on","content":"An operator can only be clocked on to one operation at a time. If Fred forgets to clock off before lunch, his time keeps running. Habit: Pause when you step away, Finish when the step is done. A manager can fix a bad entry later in the ERP, but it's cleaner to get it right on the floor."},"1283":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-37","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#record-good-and-scrap","content":"As pieces come off the table, the operator reports two numbers:"},"1284":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-38","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#record-good-and-scrap","content":"Good — pieces that passed and move to the next operation."},"1285":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-39","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#record-good-and-scrap","content":"Scrap — pieces that failed. Each scrap needs a reason (Acme uses Damaged, Defective, Quality) so the shop can see why parts are lost."},"1286":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-40","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#record-good-and-scrap","content":"On J000097 every hook was good — 500 made, 0 scrapped. When scrap does happen, reasons roll up into reports, and repeated failures can feed the quality side of Carbon as a non-conformance (NCR)."},"1287":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-41","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#clock-off-and-complete","content":"When the count is in, the operator taps Finish. This clocks them off, stops the timer, and marks the operation Done. The good quantity is now available to the next operation — so when Fred finishes Flame Cut, Sandblasting flips to Ready in the blast-room queue."},"1288":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-42","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#clock-off-and-complete","content":"The other operators do the same in turn: Carlos Axis runs Sandblasting, then Terry Tolerance runs the Quality Inspection at the Inspection Station and clocks off the last operation."},"1289":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-43","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#what-clocking-off-feeds-back","content":"Each clock-on/clock-off pair is a production event — a timestamped record of who worked which operation, how long, and how many good and scrap pieces resulted. These events do three jobs at once."},"1290":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-44","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#what-clocking-off-feeds-back","content":"They cost the job. Recorded minutes times the work center's labor and machine rates post to the job as actual cost — so Carbon can compare estimated vs. real cost."},"1291":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-45","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#what-clocking-off-feeds-back","content":"They advance the work. Reported good quantity flows to the next operation."},"1292":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-46","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#what-clocking-off-feeds-back","content":"They build the record. Who ran each step and when is stored for good — for traceability, payroll, and answering \"what happened on this job?\" later."},"1293":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-47","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#the-last-operation-finishes-the-job","content":"When the inspector clocks off the final Inspection operation, all three steps are Done and all 500 pieces are made. Carbon rolls the job up: the finished hooks are received into inventory, actual cost is locked in, and the job moves to Completed."},"1294":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-48","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#the-last-operation-finishes-the-job","content":"That's the hand-off back to the office: a Completed job means the parts exist, ready to ship against sales order SO000069. The shop floor did its part, and every minute it spent is now visible to the rest of Carbon."},"1295":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-49","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#the-last-operation-finishes-the-job","content":"type: tip"},"1296":{"id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor-50","page_id":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/manufacturing/shop-floor#the-last-operation-finishes-the-job","content":"Why clock time at all? Guessed labor is the most common reason a shop loses money without knowing it. When operators clock real time on the MES, your next quote rests on what work actually takes — not a hopeful estimate."},"1297":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","type":"page","content":"Core concepts","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts"},"1298":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-0","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","content":"The handful of ideas that make everything else click: items, methods, jobs, orders and traceability."},"1299":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-1","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"1300":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-2","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#1-item","content":"1. Item"},"1301":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-3","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#2-method-bom--routing","content":"2. Method (BOM + routing)"},"1302":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-4","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#3-quote-and-sales-order","content":"3. Quote and Sales Order"},"1303":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-5","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#4-job","content":"4. Job"},"1304":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-6","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#5-purchase-order","content":"5. Purchase Order"},"1305":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-7","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#6-traceability","content":"6. Traceability"},"1306":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-8","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#it-all-connects","content":"It all connects"},"1307":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-9","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"1308":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-10","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","content":"Carbon has a lot of screens, but only a few ideas. Learn these and the rest is just detail.\nWe'll show each one on the same real example: a Counterweight Hook (CWH-A36-15) that\nAcme makes for Radiant Aerospace."},"1309":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-11","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","content":"type: info"},"1310":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-12","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","content":"Just read along. You don't need to do anything in the app yet. This is the mental-model\npage. Want to see it all move at once? Try the 15-minute walkthrough."},"1311":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-13","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"These ideas span three modules. You'll spend most of your time in:"},"1312":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-14","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Items — the things you make, buy, store, and sell, plus how they're made."},"1313":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-15","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Sales — quotes and orders from customers."},"1314":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-16","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Production — the jobs that actually build parts."},"1315":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-17","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"The chain that ties them together looks like this:"},"1316":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-18","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#1-item","content":"An item is anything you make, buy, store, or sell. It's the noun everything points to."},"1317":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-19","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#1-item","content":"Every item is Make or Buy — that one setting decides how you get more of it:"},"1318":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-20","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#1-item","content":"Make — you build it. It needs a method (below) and demand creates a Job."},"1319":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-21","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#1-item","content":"Buy — you order it from a supplier. Demand creates a Purchase Order."},"1320":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-22","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#1-item","content":"Our hook CWH-A36-15 is a Make part. Its steel is a Buy material."},"1321":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-23","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#1-item","content":"type: tip"},"1322":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-24","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#1-item","content":"Items come in six types — Part, Material, Tool, Consumable, Service,\nFixture. You'll use Part and Material most. Don't overthink the rest."},"1323":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-25","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#2-method-bom--routing","content":"A method is the recipe for a Make item. It has two halves:"},"1324":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-26","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#2-method-bom--routing","content":"Bill of Materials (BOM) — what it's made of. The hook's BOM is one line: 40 LB of\nA36 steel plate."},"1325":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-27","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#2-method-bom--routing","content":"Routing — how it's made. The hook's routing is three steps: Flame Cut → Sandblasting\n→ Inspection."},"1326":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-28","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#2-method-bom--routing","content":"Carbon shows both together as one method tree in the Items module."},"1327":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-29","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#2-method-bom--routing","content":"The method earns its keep two ways:"},"1328":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-30","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#2-method-bom--routing","content":"It sets cost and price. Carbon adds up the steel plus the shop time to estimate what one\nhook costs, so you can price a quote."},"1329":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-31","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#2-method-bom--routing","content":"It drives the plan. When you build the part, Carbon copies the method onto the job."},"1330":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-32","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#3-quote-and-sales-order","content":"Selling happens in the Sales module. Two records carry demand:"},"1331":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-33","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#3-quote-and-sales-order","content":"Quote — a priced offer, before the customer commits. Ours was Q000061."},"1332":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-34","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#3-quote-and-sales-order","content":"Sales Order (SO) — the customer's commitment: who, what, how many, when, and price.\nAccept a quote and it becomes an SO in one click. Ours is SO000069."},"1333":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-35","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#3-quote-and-sales-order","content":"The line says Make to Order. Because the hook is a Make item, the next step is a Job —\nnot a pick from the shelf."},"1334":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-36","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#4-job","content":"A job is a production order — the instruction to actually make a quantity. It lives in\nthe Production module."},"1335":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-37","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#4-job","content":"When you release a job, Carbon copies the item's method onto it. The job keeps its own copy\nof the BOM and routing — so editing the master method later won't rewrite jobs already running."},"1336":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-38","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#4-job","content":"For our order, Carbon made job J000097 for 500 hooks. The shop floor reports progress\nthrough its operations: Draft → Ready → In Progress → Completed."},"1337":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-39","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#5-purchase-order","content":"A job needs materials. The hook's BOM calls for 40 LB of steel each — 20,000 LB for 500 —\nand steel is a Buy item. So Carbon raises a Purchase Order (PO) in the Purchasing\nmodule: your commitment to a supplier."},"1338":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-40","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#5-purchase-order","content":"Acme ordered the steel on PO000057 from Ryerson. When it arrives, a receipt adds it\nto inventory and stamps the incoming batch — which sets up the last idea."},"1339":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-41","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#6-traceability","content":"Traceability (or genealogy) answers, after the fact: what went into this, and where did\nit end up? It works through two kinds of tracking you can switch on per item:"},"1340":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-42","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#6-traceability","content":"Batch — a lot number shared by units made or received together (steel, paint)."},"1341":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-43","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#6-traceability","content":"Serial — a unique number per individual unit (high-value or regulated parts)."},"1342":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-44","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#6-traceability","content":"A36 steel is batch-tracked. So Carbon links the exact lot received on PO000057 to the\nexact 500 hooks on J000097, and through the order to Radiant Aerospace."},"1343":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-45","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#6-traceability","content":"If Ryerson later reports a bad heat of steel, Acme can name the affected parts and customer in\nseconds — no blanket recall."},"1344":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-46","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#6-traceability","content":"type: tip"},"1345":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-47","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#6-traceability","content":"You don't have to track everything. Turn on batch or serial only where it pays off —\nregulated, high-value, or warranty-sensitive parts."},"1346":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-48","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#it-all-connects","content":"That's the whole vocabulary, mapped to one hook:"},"1347":{"id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts-49","page_id":"/manual/overview/core-concepts","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/core-concepts#it-all-connects","content":"Enter information once, and it follows the work everywhere. Every page from here is just a\ncloser look at one of these records."},"1348":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","type":"page","content":"Glossary","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/glossary"},"1349":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-0","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/glossary","content":"Plain-English definitions of every Carbon and manufacturing term in this manual."},"1350":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-1","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/glossary#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"1351":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-2","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/glossary#the-three-letters-erp-mes-qms","content":"The three letters: ERP, MES, QMS"},"1352":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-3","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/glossary#the-full-az","content":"The full A–Z"},"1353":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-4","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/glossary#how-the-big-terms-connect","content":"How the big terms connect"},"1354":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-5","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/glossary#a-worked-example-term-by-term","content":"A worked example, term by term"},"1355":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-6","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/glossary#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"1356":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-7","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/glossary","content":"This page is your dictionary. Carbon uses a lot of words that sound technical but are simple\nonce someone explains them plainly. That's what this page does: one short definition per term,\nplus a real example from Acme Inc. — the demo company used throughout this manual."},"1357":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-8","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/glossary","content":"You don't need to read it top to bottom. Skim it once, then look things up as you go. Most pages\nlink their jargon straight here."},"1358":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-9","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/glossary#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"The glossary isn't a Module — it's a reference for all of them. Carbon is built from a set of\nModules: Sales, Purchasing, Items, Production, Inventory, Quality, Accounting, and Shop Floor.\nEach definition below tells you which Module a term belongs to so you know where to click."},"1359":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-10","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/glossary#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"type: info"},"1360":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-11","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/glossary#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"New to Carbon? Start with What is Carbon? for the big\npicture, then follow one real order end to end in\nCarbon in 15 minutes. The example used below — the Counterweight Hook\nCWH-A36-15 that Acme makes for Radiant Aerospace — is that same order."},"1361":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-12","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/glossary#the-three-letters-erp-mes-qms","content":"Carbon is \"an ERP + MES + QMS.\" Each acronym covers one slice of running a shop. Carbon rolls\nall three into one system that shares one set of data."},"1362":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-13","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/glossary#the-three-letters-erp-mes-qms","content":"Because they share one system, finishing a shop-floor step (MES) updates the job cost (ERP) and\nrecords which material went in (QMS) — all at once, with no re-typing."},"1363":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-14","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/glossary#the-full-az","content":"Every term in the manual, alphabetical, with real Acme examples woven in."},"1364":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-15","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/glossary#how-the-big-terms-connect","content":"If a few terms still feel abstract, here's the chain they form in real life. Each box is a record\nin Carbon, and each one links to the next automatically — the same thread the\nwalkthrough follows."},"1365":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-16","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/glossary#how-the-big-terms-connect","content":"type: tip"},"1366":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-17","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/glossary#how-the-big-terms-connect","content":"A quick way to remember the item types: Part and Material become the product (one is\nmade/sold, one is consumed into it), while Tool, Fixture and Consumable are what\nyou use to do the work. A Service is work itself rather than a thing."},"1367":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-18","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/glossary#a-worked-example-term-by-term","content":"Here's the hero order one more time — as a glossary in motion. Every row is one of the terms\nabove, filled with real Acme data."},"1368":{"id":"/manual/overview/glossary-19","page_id":"/manual/overview/glossary","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/glossary#a-worked-example-term-by-term","content":"Read that table top to bottom and you've just used a dozen glossary terms in one breath — which\nis exactly how Carbon strings them together."},"1369":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","type":"page","content":"Navigating Carbon","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/navigating"},"1370":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-0","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating","content":"A tour of the app: modules, layout, search and where to find things."},"1371":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-1","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/navigating#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"1372":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-2","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/navigating#what-each-module-is-for","content":"What each Module is for"},"1373":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-3","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/navigating#open-a-module","content":"Open a Module"},"1374":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-4","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/navigating#jump-anywhere-with-search","content":"Jump anywhere with search"},"1375":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-5","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/navigating#the-two-screens-youll-always-see","content":"The two screens you'll always see"},"1376":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-6","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/navigating#list-view","content":"List view"},"1377":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-7","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/navigating#detail-view","content":"Detail view"},"1378":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-8","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/navigating#lost-two-quick-resets","content":"Lost? Two quick resets"},"1379":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-9","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/navigating#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"1380":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-10","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating","content":"Carbon looks busy at first, but it's built from a few repeating pieces. Learn them once and\nevery screen feels familiar. This is the quick tour."},"1381":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-11","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Carbon is split into Modules — Sales, Purchasing, Items, Production, Inventory, Quality,\nand more. Each Module is one area of your business. When you open Carbon you land on the\nhome screen, where every Module shows up as a tile."},"1382":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-12","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Two ways to move around:"},"1383":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-13","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Module tiles on the home screen."},"1384":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-14","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"The module rail — the column of icons down the left edge, on every page."},"1385":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-15","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"type: tip"},"1386":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-16","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"You don't need every Module on day one. Most people live in one or two. What you can see also\ndepends on your permissions, so your rail may be\nshorter than the screenshots here."},"1387":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-17","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#what-each-module-is-for","content":"Module"},"1388":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-18","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#what-each-module-is-for","content":"What you do here"},"1389":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-19","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#what-each-module-is-for","content":"Sales"},"1390":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-20","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#what-each-module-is-for","content":"Quote, sell and ship to customers"},"1391":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-21","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#what-each-module-is-for","content":"Purchasing"},"1392":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-22","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#what-each-module-is-for","content":"Buy materials and services from suppliers"},"1393":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-23","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#what-each-module-is-for","content":"Items"},"1394":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-24","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#what-each-module-is-for","content":"Define the parts and materials you make and buy"},"1395":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-25","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#what-each-module-is-for","content":"Production"},"1396":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-26","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#what-each-module-is-for","content":"Plan and run jobs on the shop floor"},"1397":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-27","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#what-each-module-is-for","content":"Inventory"},"1398":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-28","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#what-each-module-is-for","content":"Track stock across locations"},"1399":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-29","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#what-each-module-is-for","content":"Quality"},"1400":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-30","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#what-each-module-is-for","content":"Inspect work and log issues"},"1401":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-31","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#what-each-module-is-for","content":"Accounting"},"1402":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-32","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#what-each-module-is-for","content":"Invoice, get paid and post to the books"},"1403":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-33","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#what-each-module-is-for","content":"Settings"},"1404":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-34","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#what-each-module-is-for","content":"Set up your company and account"},"1405":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-35","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#open-a-module","content":"Click a Module tile (or its icon in the rail) and Carbon opens that area. Below, clicking\nItems opens the Items Module and its Parts list."},"1406":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-36","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#open-a-module","content":"The outer frame stays put. Only the content area in the middle swaps to show the Module\nyou picked."},"1407":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-37","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#jump-anywhere-with-search","content":"The fastest way to get around is search. Press ⌘K (Ctrl+K on\nWindows), or click the search bar up top, and a box opens over whatever you're doing."},"1408":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-38","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#jump-anywhere-with-search","content":"You can search three ways:"},"1409":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-39","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#jump-anywhere-with-search","content":"A record number you already know — type SO000069 and press Enter to land on it."},"1410":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-40","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#jump-anywhere-with-search","content":"A part name — type Counterweight Hook to find the item plus the orders and jobs that use it."},"1411":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-41","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#jump-anywhere-with-search","content":"A screen — type Suppliers or Work Centers to jump straight to that list."},"1412":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-42","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#jump-anywhere-with-search","content":"type: tip"},"1413":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-43","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#jump-anywhere-with-search","content":"Think of ⌘K like a browser address bar: don't navigate to a thing — just name it."},"1414":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-44","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#the-two-screens-youll-always-see","content":"Almost everything in Carbon is one of two screens. Knowing the difference is most of \"knowing\nthe app.\""},"1415":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-45","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#list-view","content":"A list shows many records of one kind — every order, every part — one per row. Use it to\nfind, filter and scan."},"1416":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-46","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#list-view","content":"Click a row to open that record."},"1417":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-47","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#list-view","content":"Search and filter at the top to narrow the rows."},"1418":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-48","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#list-view","content":"Sort by clicking a column header."},"1419":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-49","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#list-view","content":"New button (top-right) creates a record."},"1420":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-50","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#detail-view","content":"A record (or detail) shows one thing in full — all its fields, a status badge, and\ntabs that group related info. On a sales order like SO000069, the Lines tab holds the\nparts ordered, Shipments holds what was sent, Invoices holds the bills."},"1421":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-51","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#detail-view","content":"type: tip"},"1422":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-52","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#detail-view","content":"Records are linked. From a sales order you can hop to the job that makes it, the shipment\nthat sent it, and the invoice that billed it — usually by clicking the linked number. Watch the\nwhole chain in the 15-minute walkthrough."},"1423":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-53","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#lost-two-quick-resets","content":"Press ⌘K to search from anywhere."},"1424":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-54","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#lost-two-quick-resets","content":"Click the Carbon logo (top-left) to return home."},"1425":{"id":"/manual/overview/navigating-55","page_id":"/manual/overview/navigating","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/navigating#lost-two-quick-resets","content":"You can't get truly stuck — every record is reachable by its number."},"1426":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","type":"page","content":"What is Carbon?","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon"},"1427":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-0","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","content":"ERP, MES and QMS in one system of record — and who uses each part."},"1428":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-1","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"1429":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-2","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#erp-mes-and-qms--three-jobs-one-system","content":"ERP, MES and QMS — three jobs, one system"},"1430":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-3","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#erp--the-office","content":"ERP — the office"},"1431":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-4","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#mes--the-shop-floor","content":"MES — the shop floor"},"1432":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-5","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#qms--quality","content":"QMS — quality"},"1433":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-6","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#who-uses-which-module","content":"Who uses which Module"},"1434":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-7","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#one-database-underneath","content":"One database underneath"},"1435":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-8","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#meet-acme--our-running-example","content":"Meet Acme — our running example"},"1436":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-9","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#what-makes-carbon-different","content":"What makes Carbon different"},"1437":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-10","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#the-one-idea-to-remember","content":"The one idea to remember"},"1438":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-11","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"1439":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-12","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","content":"Carbon is software for running a manufacturing business. It tracks your orders, parts,\nmaterials, and money in one place. Write something down once, and Carbon carries it\neverywhere. Nobody re-types anything."},"1440":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-13","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","content":"Most shops glue this together from spreadsheets, an accounting program, paper travelers,\nand inspection forms. None of them talk to each other. Carbon replaces that pile with one\nsystem of record — one trusted place where the real state of the business lives."},"1441":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-14","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Carbon is organized into Modules — Sales, Purchasing, Items, Production, Inventory,\nQuality, Accounting, and more. Each Module is one job. You open a Module from the home\nscreen, where every Module shows up as a tile."},"1442":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-15","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"You don't have to learn all of Carbon. Most people live in one or two Modules. Pick the\ntile for the work you do."},"1443":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-16","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#erp-mes-and-qms--three-jobs-one-system","content":"People describe business software with three acronyms — ERP, MES, and QMS. Many shops buy\nthree separate programs. Carbon does all three — not bolted together, but as three views of\nthe same data."},"1444":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-17","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#erp--the-office","content":"ERP means Enterprise Resource Planning. In plain words, it's the office side. The\nModules here let you:"},"1445":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-18","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#erp--the-office","content":"Quote a customer, then turn the quote into a sales order when they say yes."},"1446":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-19","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#erp--the-office","content":"Raise purchase orders to suppliers for the materials you need."},"1447":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-20","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#erp--the-office","content":"Track inventory — what's on the shelf, where, and how much."},"1448":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-21","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#erp--the-office","content":"Roll up cost automatically, so you know if a price leaves a profit."},"1449":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-22","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#erp--the-office","content":"For Acme, ERP took Radiant Aerospace's order for 500 Counterweight Hooks (sales order\nSO000069, $36,820) and bought the steel from Ryerson (purchase order PO000057)."},"1450":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-23","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#mes--the-shop-floor","content":"MES means Manufacturing Execution System. It's what operators use on the floor. When\nthe office releases a job (an order to make a quantity of a part), it shows up for an\noperator. They open it, clock on to an operation, and record finished pieces."},"1451":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-24","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#mes--the-shop-floor","content":"For Acme's hook, the floor ran three steps in order — Flame Cut, Sandblasting, then\nInspection — all on job J000097."},"1452":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-25","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#qms--quality","content":"QMS means Quality Management System. It's how you make sure each part is right and\ncan prove it later:"},"1453":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-26","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#qms--quality","content":"Inspections — a quality check, often built into a job as a step."},"1454":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-27","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#qms--quality","content":"Non-conformances (NCRs) — a record you raise when something is wrong, so it gets fixed."},"1455":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-28","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#qms--quality","content":"Traceability — the linked chain from finished part back to the exact batch of raw\nmaterial. Carbon can answer \"which heat of steel went into Radiant's hooks?\" in seconds."},"1456":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-29","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#who-uses-which-module","content":"Because it's one system, hand-offs are automatic. The estimator doesn't email the order to\nthe floor — the order becomes a job. The inspector doesn't keep a separate binder — the\ninspection is a step on that same job."},"1457":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-30","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#one-database-underneath","content":"The three sides feel like one tool because they sit on one database. A sales order, the\njob that fulfills it, the purchase order for its material, the inspection that passed it,\nand the invoice that bills it are all linked records."},"1458":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-31","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#one-database-underneath","content":"That's what \"system of record\" buys you: enter it once, and it follows the work\neverywhere. Here is Acme's single hook order seen through all three sides at once."},"1459":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-32","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#one-database-underneath","content":"type: warn"},"1460":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-33","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#one-database-underneath","content":"This is the biggest difference from spreadsheets. There, each row lives in a different\nfile, gets copied by hand, and drifts out of sync. In Carbon they are the same data —\nchange one, and everyone sees it."},"1461":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-34","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#meet-acme--our-running-example","content":"Every page in this manual uses one real demo company so the examples stay concrete.\nAcme Inc. is a metal-fabrication shop in Springfield, OH. It cuts, machines, and\nfinishes steel and aluminum parts for aerospace, defense, energy, mining, and construction."},"1462":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-35","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#meet-acme--our-running-example","content":"Throughout the manual we follow one part Acme makes — a Counterweight Hook\n(part number CWH-A36-15) for the customer Radiant Aerospace. One order for it touches\nevery Module, so it's the thread that ties the whole manual together."},"1463":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-36","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#what-makes-carbon-different","content":"Everything lives together, so there's no re-keying and nothing drifts out of sync.\nA quote becomes a sales order becomes a job becomes a shipment becomes an invoice — each\ninheriting from the last. The walkthrough follows that chain for\nAcme's hook, from price request to paid invoice."},"1464":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-37","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#what-makes-carbon-different","content":"An API lets other software read and write your data. Carbon is API-first: every\nscreen you click does the same thing a program could do through the API. So you can\nconnect Carbon to your other tools and automate the boring parts. More in\nUsing the API."},"1465":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-38","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#what-makes-carbon-different","content":"Carbon ships with a built-in MCP server — a safe doorway that lets an AI assistant\noperate Carbon for you (look things up, draft a quote, check a job) in plain language.\nThe demo data in this manual was pulled through it. See\nMCP & AI."},"1466":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-39","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#what-makes-carbon-different","content":"Carbon's code is open source — anyone can read it, run it, and extend it. You can\nself-host, audit how it works, and shape it to your shop. More in\nIntegrating with Carbon."},"1467":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-40","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#what-makes-carbon-different","content":"type: tip"},"1468":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-41","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#what-makes-carbon-different","content":"You don't need the API or AI features to get full value from Carbon. Day one, you can\nquote, order, make, buy, inspect and invoice entirely by clicking. New to a bolded term?\nEvery one is defined in the glossary."},"1469":{"id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon-42","page_id":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/overview/what-is-carbon#the-one-idea-to-remember","content":"Carbon is one connected system of record for the whole business. ERP runs the office,\nMES runs the floor, QMS keeps it good — three views into the same data, organized as\nModules. Information goes in once and follows the work from the first quote to the final\npayment."},"1470":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","type":"page","content":"Defining an item","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item"},"1471":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-0","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","content":"Parts, materials, tools and services — how to create and describe the things you make and buy."},"1472":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-1","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"1473":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-2","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#the-six-item-types","content":"The six item types"},"1474":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-3","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#create-a-part","content":"Create a Part"},"1475":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-4","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#open-the-parts-list","content":"Open the Parts list"},"1476":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-5","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#enter-the-basics","content":"Enter the basics"},"1477":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-6","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#set-tracking-and-make-or-buy","content":"Set tracking and Make-or-Buy"},"1478":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-7","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#save","content":"Save"},"1479":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-8","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#reading-the-item-detail-page","content":"Reading the item detail page"},"1480":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-9","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#a-look-at-acmes-items","content":"A look at Acme's items"},"1481":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-10","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"1482":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-11","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","content":"Almost everything in Carbon starts with an item — a single, named thing you make, buy,\nsell, or use. Every quote, order, job and invoice points back to an item."},"1483":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-12","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","content":"This page lives in the Items module. It covers the six kinds of item and how to create one."},"1484":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-13","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Items live in the Items module. Open it from the left rail, then pick a list:\nParts, Materials, Tools, and so on. Each list has the same green Add button,\ntop-right."},"1485":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-14","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"You describe an item once. After that, Carbon reuses the same record everywhere — so a\nprice fix happens in one place."},"1486":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-15","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#the-six-item-types","content":"The first thing you choose is the type. It tells Carbon what role the item plays. Acme\nuses all six."},"1487":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-16","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#the-six-item-types","content":"You'll use Part and Material the most. They sit at opposite ends of the same job:"},"1488":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-17","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#the-six-item-types","content":"A Part is what you deliver. Acme's Counterweight Hook (CWH-A36-15) is a Part."},"1489":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-18","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#the-six-item-types","content":"A Material is what you consume to make a Part. The hook is cut from A36 Steel Plate\n(A36-STEEL-PLT-1\".96x240), which is a Material."},"1490":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-19","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#the-six-item-types","content":"type: tip"},"1491":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-20","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#the-six-item-types","content":"Tool vs Consumable is just value and durability. A Tool (a caliper, a torque wrench)\nlasts years and is worth tracking. A Consumable (sandpaper, welding wire) is cheap and\nused up. Ask: \"would I notice if one walked off?\" If yes, it's probably a Tool."},"1492":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-21","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#create-a-part","content":"Let's create the Counterweight Hook the way Acme did. The flow is the same for any type — you\njust pick a different Type in step 2."},"1493":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-22","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#open-the-parts-list","content":"In the left rail, open the Items module and choose Parts. Click the green\nAdd Part button, top-right."},"1494":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-23","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#enter-the-basics","content":"Fill in the four fields every item needs. Acme enters:"},"1495":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-24","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#enter-the-basics","content":"Type — Part"},"1496":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-25","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#enter-the-basics","content":"Part number — CWH-A36-15"},"1497":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-26","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#enter-the-basics","content":"Description — Counterweight Hook"},"1498":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-27","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#enter-the-basics","content":"Unit of measure — EA (Each)"},"1499":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-28","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#enter-the-basics","content":"The part number must be unique. Pick a readable scheme and stick to it."},"1500":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-29","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#set-tracking-and-make-or-buy","content":"Tracking — Inventory (Carbon keeps a running on-hand count). Use Batch when the lot\nmatters, Serial for high-value parts, Non-Inventory for services."},"1501":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-30","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#set-tracking-and-make-or-buy","content":"Replenishment — Make or Buy. The hook is Make: Carbon builds it on a job. The\nsteel plate is Buy: Carbon orders it on a purchase order."},"1502":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-31","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#set-tracking-and-make-or-buy","content":"type: warn"},"1503":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-32","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#set-tracking-and-make-or-buy","content":"Tracking is hard to change once an item has history, so set it now. When unsure: Inventory\nfor physical goods, Non-Inventory for services."},"1504":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-33","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#save","content":"Click Save. Carbon creates the item, marks it Active, and opens its detail page.\nThat's the whole foundation."},"1505":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-34","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#reading-the-item-detail-page","content":"The detail page groups everything into tabs. The hook is a Make part, so its\nManufacturing tab holds the method (the recipe) and a 3D model."},"1506":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-35","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#reading-the-item-detail-page","content":"type: info"},"1507":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-36","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#reading-the-item-detail-page","content":"Manufacturing and Purchasing are mirror images. A Make item fills in\nManufacturing and leaves Purchasing empty; a Buy item is the reverse. The A36 steel\nplate fills in Purchasing (Ryerson, $0.25/LB) and has no method."},"1508":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-37","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#a-look-at-acmes-items","content":"Each type is its own list under Items, but they all create the same way. Here's one of\neach kind Acme keeps."},"1509":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-38","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#a-look-at-acmes-items","content":"type: tip"},"1510":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-39","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#a-look-at-acmes-items","content":"Don't perfect every field up front. Number, description, UoM, type, tracking and Make/Buy is\nenough to start. Refine costs, suppliers and the method as you go."},"1511":{"id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item-40","page_id":"/manual/items/defining-an-item","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/defining-an-item#next-steps","content":"You can create an item — now teach Carbon how to make it and how to keep it in stock."},"1512":{"id":"/manual/items/materials","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","type":"page","content":"Materials","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/materials"},"1513":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-0","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials","content":"Raw materials, forms, grades and dimensions for cut-to-size stock."},"1514":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-1","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/materials#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"1515":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-2","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/materials#material-vs-part","content":"Material vs. part"},"1516":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-3","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/materials#the-four-parts-of-a-material","content":"The four parts of a material"},"1517":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-4","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/materials#acmes-material-catalog","content":"Acme's material catalog"},"1518":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-5","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/materials#cut-to-size-stock-and-stock-on-hand","content":"Cut-to-size stock and stock on hand"},"1519":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-6","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/materials#batch-tracking-and-traceability","content":"Batch tracking and traceability"},"1520":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-7","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/materials#create-a-material","content":"Create a material"},"1521":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-8","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/materials#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"1522":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-9","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials","content":"A material is the raw stock you buy and then cut, machine or form into parts — a steel\nplate, an aluminum billet, a length of brass bar. In Carbon, a material is a kind of\nitem, described the way a metals distributor sells it:\na substance, a form, a grade, and dimensions."},"1523":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-10","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Materials live in the Items module, on the Materials tab next to Parts. Open Items\nfrom the home screen, then switch to Materials to see your raw stock."},"1524":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-11","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#material-vs-part","content":"Both are items, so they share the same fields — ID, unit of measure, costs, inventory,\nsuppliers. They differ in what they describe and how you get them."},"1525":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-12","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#material-vs-part","content":"type: tip"},"1526":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-13","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#material-vs-part","content":"Use a material for anything you cut, machine, weld or form from raw stock. Not sure which\nitem type to pick? See defining an item."},"1527":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-14","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#the-four-parts-of-a-material","content":"Every material is described by four attributes. Acme packs all four into a readable ID so the\ncatalog reads at a glance."},"1528":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-15","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#the-four-parts-of-a-material","content":"Substance — the alloy. Carbon ships 17 built-in (Steel, Stainless Steel, Aluminum,\nBrass, Inconel, Titanium and more). Acme uses six, plus a custom one (Foam) for packaging."},"1529":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-16","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#the-four-parts-of-a-material","content":"Form — the shape it arrives in. Carbon has 21 built-in: Plate, Billet, Flat Bar, Round\nBar, Hex Bar, Sheet, Tube, Angle, Channel and more."},"1530":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-17","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#the-four-parts-of-a-material","content":"Grade — the temper or spec, like T6 on aluminum or 304 vs 316 on stainless."},"1531":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-18","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#the-four-parts-of-a-material","content":"Dimensions — the physical size: plate thickness, sheet size, bar diameter."},"1532":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-19","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#the-four-parts-of-a-material","content":"type: tip"},"1533":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-20","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#the-four-parts-of-a-material","content":"Reading an Acme ID. A36-STEEL-PLT-1\".96x240 = A36 (grade) · STEEL (substance) ·\nPLT (form) · 1″ (thickness) · 96×240 (sheet, inches)."},"1534":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-21","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#acmes-material-catalog","content":"Here's a slice of Acme's 19-material catalog. The same substance shows up in several sizes —\neach is its own item, because each is a different piece of stock to buy, store and cut."},"1535":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-22","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#acmes-material-catalog","content":"type: info"},"1536":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-23","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#acmes-material-catalog","content":"Most metal is bought in LB (pounds) — even when the part it feeds is counted in EA.\nCarbon mixes units happily: the Counterweight Hook consumes 40 LB of plate per 1 EA hook."},"1537":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-24","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#cut-to-size-stock-and-stock-on-hand","content":"You rarely use a whole sheet. Each job pulls only the quantity it needs, in the material's\nunit:"},"1538":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-25","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#cut-to-size-stock-and-stock-on-hand","content":"The Counterweight Hook (CWH-A36-15) pulls 40 LB of A36 plate per hook."},"1539":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-26","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#cut-to-size-stock-and-stock-on-hand","content":"A batch of 500 hooks needs 20,000 LB — not 500 whole sheets."},"1540":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-27","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#cut-to-size-stock-and-stock-on-hand","content":"Carbon tracks the running pounds on hand and counts them down as you consume."},"1541":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-28","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#cut-to-size-stock-and-stock-on-hand","content":"To see live stock, open the Inventory module. It lists on-hand quantity, reorder policy\nand replenishment for every item — including Acme's steel and aluminum."},"1542":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-29","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#batch-tracking-and-traceability","content":"For materials, where the metal came from can matter as much as how much you have. A\nbatch (also lot, or heat for steel) is stock that arrived together in one shipment.\nAcme's A36 plate has batch tracking on, so:"},"1543":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-30","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#batch-tracking-and-traceability","content":"At receipt, Carbon records a batch number when steel arrives from\nRyerson on PO000057. The\npounds are tagged with that batch."},"1544":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-31","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#batch-tracking-and-traceability","content":"During the job, when plate is issued to job J000097, Carbon records which batch was used."},"1545":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-32","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#batch-tracking-and-traceability","content":"Forever after, each finished hook links back to that exact heat of steel — so if Ryerson\nreports a problem, Acme can answer \"which orders shipped that steel?\" in seconds."},"1546":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-33","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#batch-tracking-and-traceability","content":"This chain — shipment → batch → job → part → customer — is traceability. It's why Radiant\nAerospace cares that Acme runs batch-tracked steel. More in\ntracking quality."},"1547":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-34","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#batch-tracking-and-traceability","content":"type: warn"},"1548":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-35","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#batch-tracking-and-traceability","content":"Turn on batch tracking before you receive any stock. Switching it on later leaves existing\nquantity with no batch number. For regulated work, enable it when you first create the material."},"1549":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-36","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#create-a-material","content":"Here's how Acme added the 1-inch A36 plate. Same steps for steel, stainless, aluminum or brass."},"1550":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-37","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#create-a-material","content":"Start a new material. In the Items module, on the Materials tab, click the green\nAdd button (top-right). Picking Material gives you the substance/form/grade fields."},"1551":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-38","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#create-a-material","content":"Pick substance, form and grade. Choose Steel and Plate (PLT), enter grade A36,\nand dimensions 1″ thick, 96 × 240 sheet. Carbon builds a readable ID like\nA36-STEEL-PLT-1\".96x240."},"1552":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-39","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#create-a-material","content":"Set the unit of measure. Choose LB (Pound) — the unit you buy and consume the plate in."},"1553":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-40","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#create-a-material","content":"Set replenishment to Buy. Acme buys plate, so set\nreplenishment to Buy. This unlocks supplier and reorder settings."},"1554":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-41","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#create-a-material","content":"Turn on batch tracking (if needed). For traceable stock, switch on Requires batch\ntracking now — before any inventory exists."},"1555":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-42","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#create-a-material","content":"Add the supplier and save. On the Suppliers tab, add Ryerson at $0.25/LB, then\nSave. The material can now drop onto any method and onto a\npurchase order like PO000057."},"1556":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-43","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#create-a-material","content":"type: tip"},"1557":{"id":"/manual/items/materials-44","page_id":"/manual/items/materials","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/materials#create-a-material","content":"Reuse, don't duplicate. Search first — Acme already stocks A36 plate in 1″, 2″, 3″ and 4″.\nOnly create a new material when the physical stock is genuinely different."},"1558":{"id":"/manual/items/methods","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","type":"page","content":"Methods: BOM & routing","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/methods"},"1559":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-0","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods","content":"Tell Carbon how a part is made with a bill of materials and a routing."},"1560":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-1","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/methods#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"1561":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-2","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/methods#the-two-halves-of-a-method","content":"The two halves of a method"},"1562":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-3","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/methods#build-the-bill-of-materials","content":"Build the bill of materials"},"1563":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-4","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/methods#open-the-manufacturing-tab","content":"Open the Manufacturing tab"},"1564":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-5","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/methods#add-a-material-line","content":"Add a material line"},"1565":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-6","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/methods#set-the-quantity-per-piece","content":"Set the quantity per piece"},"1566":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-7","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/methods#choose-the-method-type","content":"Choose the method type"},"1567":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-8","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/methods#build-the-routing","content":"Build the routing"},"1568":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-9","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/methods#add-the-first-operation","content":"Add the first operation"},"1569":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-10","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/methods#enter-the-times","content":"Enter the times"},"1570":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-11","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/methods#add-the-other-two-steps","content":"Add the other two steps"},"1571":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-12","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/methods#multi-level-methods-sub-assemblies","content":"Multi-level methods (sub-assemblies)"},"1572":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-13","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/methods#versions-and-revisions","content":"Versions and revisions"},"1573":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-14","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/methods#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"1574":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-15","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods","content":"A method is Carbon's recipe for a part you make. It has two halves: what the part is made of (the bill of materials) and how it's built (the routing)."},"1575":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-16","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods","content":"Set it once. Every quote, job, and cost estimate is built from it automatically."},"1576":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-17","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods","content":"This page builds the method for Acme's hero part, the Counterweight Hook (CWH-A36-15)."},"1577":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-18","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Methods live in the Items module, on each part's Manufacturing tab. Open the part, click Manufacturing, and you'll see the whole recipe as a tree: the part on top, its materials and operations nested underneath."},"1578":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-19","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"type: tip"},"1579":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-20","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"The part itself — name, unit, Make or Buy — is set on the item. See Defining an item. The method is where the making lives."},"1580":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-21","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#the-two-halves-of-a-method","content":"Bill of materials (BOM) — what the part is made of. A list of materials and sub-parts, each with a quantity per finished piece. The hook needs one line: 40 LB of A36 steel plate."},"1581":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-22","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#the-two-halves-of-a-method","content":"Routing — how the part is made. An ordered list of operations, each run at a work center with a time. The hook: flame cut, then sandblast, then inspect."},"1582":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-23","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#build-the-bill-of-materials","content":"The BOM answers one question: to make one, what do I use? Enter the quantity for a single piece. Carbon scales it later — a job for 500 hooks needs 40 × 500 = 20,000 LB of plate, automatically."},"1583":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-24","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#open-the-manufacturing-tab","content":"In the Items module, open the Counterweight Hook (CWH-A36-15) and click the Manufacturing tab."},"1584":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-25","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#add-a-material-line","content":"Under Bill of Material, click Add Material. Pick A36 Steel Plate 1″ (A36-STEEL-PLT-1\".96x240). Carbon fills in the description and unit."},"1585":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-26","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#set-the-quantity-per-piece","content":"Enter 40 in LB (pounds) — the amount one hook uses. Don't multiply by your batch size."},"1586":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-27","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#choose-the-method-type","content":"Set the line to Pull from Inventory. That tells Carbon to pull the steel off the shelf when a job runs."},"1587":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-28","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#choose-the-method-type","content":"type: tip"},"1588":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-29","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#choose-the-method-type","content":"Pull from Inventory vs. Make. Use Pull from Inventory for stocked materials like the steel plate. Use Make when the line is itself something you build — that makes it a sub-assembly (see below)."},"1589":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-30","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#build-the-routing","content":"The routing is the ordered list of shop-floor steps. Each operation says what you do, where (a work center), and how long it takes. Steps are numbered in tens (10, 20, 30…) so you can slot one in between later."},"1590":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-31","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#build-the-routing","content":"The hook's routing is three operations:"},"1591":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-32","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#add-the-first-operation","content":"Under Routing, click Add Operation. Pick the process Flame Cut and the work center Burn Table — PA2. Carbon assigns it sequence 10."},"1592":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-33","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#enter-the-times","content":"Setup time — one-time per job. The flame cut has 0 setup."},"1593":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-34","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#enter-the-times","content":"Run time — per-piece time. Here, 45 Minutes/Piece."},"1594":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-35","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#enter-the-times","content":"Minutes/Piece scales with quantity; Total Minutes stays fixed."},"1595":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-36","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#add-the-other-two-steps","content":"20 · Sandblasting — Sand Blasting Room, 2 Minutes/Piece."},"1596":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-37","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#add-the-other-two-steps","content":"30 · Inspection — Inspection Station, 10 Minutes/Piece."},"1597":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-38","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#add-the-other-two-steps","content":"Inspection comes last on purpose — it's the quality gate before the hooks can ship."},"1598":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-39","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#add-the-other-two-steps","content":"type: tip"},"1599":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-40","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#add-the-other-two-steps","content":"Setup vs. run time. Run time scales with quantity; setup doesn't. That's why bigger batches usually cost less per piece — and Carbon does the math the moment you set a job quantity."},"1600":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-41","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#multi-level-methods-sub-assemblies","content":"The hook goes straight from raw material to finished part — a single-level method. But many products are built from sub-parts you also make."},"1601":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-42","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#multi-level-methods-sub-assemblies","content":"Set a BOM line's method type to Make instead of Pull from Inventory, and it becomes a sub-assembly — Carbon nests that child part's whole method underneath. When a job runs, it can build the sub-assemblies first."},"1602":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-43","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#multi-level-methods-sub-assemblies","content":"type: info"},"1603":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-44","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#multi-level-methods-sub-assemblies","content":"Define a sub-assembly's method once on its own item, then drop it into as many parent BOMs as you like. Update it in one place and every parent picks up the change on its next job."},"1604":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-45","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#versions-and-revisions","content":"Parts change, so methods aren't frozen. Carbon keeps history so today's edit doesn't rewrite what you already shipped."},"1605":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-46","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#versions-and-revisions","content":"A revision is a named iteration of the part (Rev 0, Rev A…). The hook is at revision 0."},"1606":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-47","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#versions-and-revisions","content":"A version is Carbon's snapshot of a method. A job takes its own copy when it's created. Editing the part's master method later does not change a job already in flight."},"1607":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-48","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#versions-and-revisions","content":"type: warn"},"1608":{"id":"/manual/items/methods-49","page_id":"/manual/items/methods","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/methods#versions-and-revisions","content":"Editing the master method only affects future jobs. To change a job that's already running, edit it on that job's method — not the part. This is why job J000097 built 500 hooks against the method exactly as it stood the day it was released."},"1609":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","type":"page","content":"Replenishment: make vs. buy","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/replenishment"},"1610":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-0","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment","content":"Reorder policies, lead times and planning parameters that keep stock flowing."},"1611":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-1","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/replenishment#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"1612":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-2","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/replenishment#make-or-buy","content":"Make or buy"},"1613":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-3","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/replenishment#how-a-line-gets-filled","content":"How a line gets filled"},"1614":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-4","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/replenishment#plan-when-to-reorder","content":"Plan when to reorder"},"1615":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-5","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/replenishment#a-few-real-items-side-by-side","content":"A few real items, side by side"},"1616":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-6","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/items/replenishment#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"1617":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-7","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment","content":"Every item has to come from somewhere. You either make it\nor buy it. Replenishment is how you tell Carbon which one — and the few numbers that\nlet Carbon top up your stock before you run out."},"1618":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-8","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Replenishment lives in two Modules:"},"1619":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-9","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Items — set Make or Buy on the item, in the Replenishment area."},"1620":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-10","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Inventory — see the reorder policy and stock levels Carbon uses to plan."},"1621":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-11","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Open an item from the Items module and look at its Manufacturing view. The\nReplenishment field is the make-or-buy switch."},"1622":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-12","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#make-or-buy","content":"Pick one of these on every item:"},"1623":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-13","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#make-or-buy","content":"Make — Carbon builds it on a job. It needs a\nmethod (a BOM + routing). The Counterweight Hook CWH-A36-15\nis Make."},"1624":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-14","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#make-or-buy","content":"Buy — Carbon orders it from a supplier on a purchase order.\nIt needs a supplier and a price. The A36 steel plate it's cut from is Buy."},"1625":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-15","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#make-or-buy","content":"Make & Buy — both are allowed. You pick make-or-buy on each order line."},"1626":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-16","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#make-or-buy","content":"type: tip"},"1627":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-17","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#make-or-buy","content":"Rule of thumb: if an item has a method, it's Make. If it has a supplier and a\npurchase price, it's Buy."},"1628":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-18","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#how-a-line-gets-filled","content":"When an item is ordered (a sales order, or a part needed by a job), Carbon picks how to fill\nthat one line:"},"1629":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-19","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#how-a-line-gets-filled","content":"Make to Order — start a fresh job just for this order. Best for custom parts you don't stock."},"1630":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-20","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#how-a-line-gets-filled","content":"Make to Stock — build a batch into inventory ahead of demand, then ship from the shelf."},"1631":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-21","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#how-a-line-gets-filled","content":"Pull from Inventory — take what's already on the shelf. No new job or PO."},"1632":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-22","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#how-a-line-gets-filled","content":"On Acme's hook order, the line is Make to Order, so Carbon created job J000097. Inside\nthat job, the A36 steel is set to Pull from Inventory — Carbon draws it from the shelf\ninstead of buying fresh for the job."},"1633":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-23","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#how-a-line-gets-filled","content":"type: info"},"1634":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-24","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#how-a-line-gets-filled","content":"If the shelf is short when Carbon goes to pull, that shortage becomes new demand. Because\nsteel is a Buy item, that turns into a suggested purchase order — exactly how\nPO000057 to Ryerson came to exist."},"1635":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-25","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#plan-when-to-reorder","content":"For pure make-to-order parts, planning is simple: an order arrives, a job runs. The numbers\nbelow matter most for items you stock — bulk raw materials and make-to-stock parts."},"1636":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-26","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#plan-when-to-reorder","content":"Open the Inventory module to see the reorder policy and stock levels Carbon plans against,\nitem by item."},"1637":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-27","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#plan-when-to-reorder","content":"Set these on the item's Planning tab, per location (Headquarters and Texas can differ):"},"1638":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-28","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#plan-when-to-reorder","content":"Pick a reordering policy — when Carbon suggests a top-up:"},"1639":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-29","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#plan-when-to-reorder","content":"Manual Reorder — no auto-suggestions; you create jobs and POs yourself."},"1640":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-30","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#plan-when-to-reorder","content":"Demand-Based Reorder — Carbon adds up demand over a window (Acme uses 4 weeks) and\nsuggests enough to cover it."},"1641":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-31","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#plan-when-to-reorder","content":"Maximum Quantity — keep the shelf topped up toward a target level."},"1642":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-32","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#plan-when-to-reorder","content":"Set the reorder point and quantity. Drop below the reorder point and Carbon raises a\nsuggestion. The reorder quantity is how much to order each time."},"1643":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-33","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#plan-when-to-reorder","content":"Set safety stock. A buffer kept on the shelf beyond known demand. Acme keeps 3,000 LB\nof A36 steel at Headquarters. The hook keeps none — it's made to order."},"1644":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-34","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#plan-when-to-reorder","content":"Set the lead time. How long replenishment takes. Both hero items use 7 days. Carbon\nworks back from the due date to tell you the latest day to order or release."},"1645":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-35","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#plan-when-to-reorder","content":"type: warn"},"1646":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-36","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#plan-when-to-reorder","content":"Reorder points are per location, not per company. If you stock the same material in two\nplaces, give each location its own numbers — or one site runs dry while the other overflows."},"1647":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-37","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#a-few-real-items-side-by-side","content":"Same shop, four different strategies — all driven by make-or-buy plus a couple of numbers."},"1648":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-38","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#a-few-real-items-side-by-side","content":"type: tip"},"1649":{"id":"/manual/items/replenishment-39","page_id":"/manual/items/replenishment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/items/replenishment#a-few-real-items-side-by-side","content":"Start simple. Set Make or Buy on every item, add a lead time so dates are\nrealistic, and add safety stock only where running out actually hurts. Tighten the rest later."},"1650":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","type":"page","content":"Tracking quality","tags":[],"url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality"},"1651":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-0","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","content":"Non-conformances, inspections, corrective actions and full traceability."},"1652":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-1","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"1653":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-2","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#inspections-a-gate-inside-the-job","content":"Inspections: a gate inside the job"},"1654":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-3","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#non-conformances-ncrs-record-what-went-wrong","content":"Non-conformances (NCRs): record what went wrong"},"1655":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-4","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#raise-an-ncr","content":"Raise an NCR"},"1656":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-5","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#gauges-and-calibration-trust-your-measurements","content":"Gauges and calibration: trust your measurements"},"1657":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-6","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#traceability-prove-what-went-where","content":"Traceability: prove what went where"},"1658":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-7","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"1659":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-8","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","content":"The Quality module keeps bad parts from leaving the building — and lets you prove later that what you shipped was good. It has four jobs: inspections, non-conformances (NCRs), gauges, and traceability."},"1660":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-9","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Open the Quality module from the home screen. The dashboard shows your open work and a sub-nav for Issues, Gauges, Records, and Inspections."},"1661":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-10","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"The two numbers up top tell you the workload at a glance:"},"1662":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-11","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"You don't have to use all four tools to start. Many shops begin with one inspection on their most important part and grow from there."},"1663":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-12","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#inspections-a-gate-inside-the-job","content":"In Carbon an inspection isn't a separate thing to set up — it's just an operation in a routing, run at an inspection work center. The hero Counterweight Hook shows it: its method ends with an Inspection operation, so no part ships before it's checked."},"1664":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-13","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#inspections-a-gate-inside-the-job","content":"How it runs on the shop floor:"},"1665":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-14","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#inspections-a-gate-inside-the-job","content":"Clock onto the inspection operation. In the shop floor app, the inspector opens the job, taps the Inspection operation, and clocks on — like any other step."},"1666":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-15","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#inspections-a-gate-inside-the-job","content":"Check parts against the spec using calibrated gauges. The procedure says what to measure."},"1667":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-16","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#inspections-a-gate-inside-the-job","content":"Record good and scrap counts. Good pieces become quantity complete; failures become scrap with a reason."},"1668":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-17","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#inspections-a-gate-inside-the-job","content":"Raise an NCR for failures. Bad parts trigger a non-conformance (next section), and the job can be held so they can't ship by mistake."},"1669":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-18","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#inspections-a-gate-inside-the-job","content":"type: tip"},"1670":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-19","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#inspections-a-gate-inside-the-job","content":"Want first-article or incoming inspection instead of a final check? Put the inspection operation first in the routing. Same mechanism — only the position changes."},"1671":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-20","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#non-conformances-ncrs-record-what-went-wrong","content":"An NCR — also called an Issue in Carbon — is the record you open when something is off-spec: a bad part, a bad batch of steel, a customer complaint. It captures what happened, how bad it is, what you did, and how you proved the fix worked."},"1672":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-21","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#non-conformances-ncrs-record-what-went-wrong","content":"Two settings shape every NCR:"},"1673":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-22","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#non-conformances-ncrs-record-what-went-wrong","content":"Type — the cause, so you can spot patterns later (e.g. three Material Issue NCRs all from one supplier). Acme ships with ten types like Manufacturing Defect, Material Issue, and Customer Complaint."},"1674":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-23","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#non-conformances-ncrs-record-what-went-wrong","content":"Workflow — the playbook, matched to severity. It lists the required actions you must finish before closing."},"1675":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-24","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#non-conformances-ncrs-record-what-went-wrong","content":"Acme uses three workflows, from lightest to heaviest:"},"1676":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-25","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#non-conformances-ncrs-record-what-went-wrong","content":"type: info"},"1677":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-26","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#non-conformances-ncrs-record-what-went-wrong","content":"Corrective vs preventive. A corrective action fixes the parts in front of you. A preventive action changes the process so it can't happen again. Heavier workflows make you do both — and Carbon won't let you close the NCR until every required action is checked off."},"1678":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-27","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#raise-an-ncr","content":"Start from the problem. Open the failing operation, or go to Issues → New. Starting from the operation pre-fills the job, part, and work center."},"1679":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-28","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#raise-an-ncr","content":"Pick the type and workflow. Choose the cause (e.g. Manufacturing Defect) and the right playbook (CAPA for a recurring defect, 8D if parts reached the customer)."},"1680":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-29","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#raise-an-ncr","content":"Describe and quantify. Write what you saw, attach a photo, and record the non-conforming quantity with a scrap reason if you're scrapping."},"1681":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-30","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#raise-an-ncr","content":"Assign and work the actions. Each required action is a checklist item with an owner and status."},"1682":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-31","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#raise-an-ncr","content":"Close it. Once every action is done — and MRB has signed off if the workflow needs it — close the NCR. It stays linked to the job and part forever."},"1683":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-32","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#raise-an-ncr","content":"type: warn"},"1684":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-33","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#raise-an-ncr","content":"Don't reach for 8D on every scratch. Over-classifying buries your team and hides what truly matters. Most shop-floor defects are a 5 Why 2 How; save 8D for problems that reached the customer or carry safety risk."},"1685":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-34","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#gauges-and-calibration-trust-your-measurements","content":"An inspection is only as good as the tool doing the measuring. A gauge is any measuring instrument — a micrometer, height gauge, or thread plug. Gauges drift over time, so each one is calibrated on a schedule. Open Gauges from the Quality sub-nav."},"1686":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-35","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#gauges-and-calibration-trust-your-measurements","content":"Acme registers ten gauges (G00001–G00010), each on a six-month interval. Carbon computes the next-due date and flips overdue tools to Out of Calibration on its own:"},"1687":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-36","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#gauges-and-calibration-trust-your-measurements","content":"To keep gauges current:"},"1688":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-37","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#gauges-and-calibration-trust-your-measurements","content":"Register the gauge in Gauges → New — a number, description, type, and home location."},"1689":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-38","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#gauges-and-calibration-trust-your-measurements","content":"Set the calibration interval (Acme uses six months). Carbon uses it to compute the next-due date."},"1690":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-39","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#gauges-and-calibration-trust-your-measurements","content":"Log each calibration. Carbon rolls the due date forward and flips the status back to In Calibration."},"1691":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-40","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#gauges-and-calibration-trust-your-measurements","content":"Work the overdue list. Filter by Out of Calibration to see what needs attention this week."},"1692":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-41","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#gauges-and-calibration-trust-your-measurements","content":"type: warn"},"1693":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-42","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#gauges-and-calibration-trust-your-measurements","content":"An out-of-calibration gauge taints every measurement made with it. If G00003 was used to accept parts after its 2026-03-03 due date, you can't trust those results — which can itself become a Testing Failure NCR."},"1694":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-43","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#traceability-prove-what-went-where","content":"Traceability (or genealogy) follows a part backward and forward: which raw material went in, which job made it, which customer it shipped to. The enabler is tracking set on the item:"},"1695":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-44","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#traceability-prove-what-went-where","content":"Batch tracking groups material by lot. A36 Steel Plate has batch tracking on, so every receipt records the heat of steel from the mill."},"1696":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-45","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#traceability-prove-what-went-where","content":"Serial tracking gives each finished unit its own number — for parts a customer needs to trace one by one."},"1697":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-46","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#traceability-prove-what-went-where","content":"Because every record links to the next, you can read the chain either way:"},"1698":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-47","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#traceability-prove-what-went-where","content":"Backward (recall): \"A bad heat shipped — which orders?\" Follow the batch forward to J000097, then SO000069, and you land on Radiant Aerospace in seconds."},"1699":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-48","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#traceability-prove-what-went-where","content":"Forward (provenance): \"Radiant wants the material certs.\" Walk back from the shipment through the job to the exact heat of A36 steel and the Ryerson PO."},"1700":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-49","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#traceability-prove-what-went-where","content":"type: tip"},"1701":{"id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality-50","page_id":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/quality/tracking-quality#traceability-prove-what-went-where","content":"Turn on tracking before you receive material. Set batch (or serial) tracking on the item up front, so every receipt, job, and shipment records the lot automatically."},"1702":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"page","content":"Customers","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers"},"1703":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-0","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers","content":"Create customers, contacts, locations and payment terms."},"1704":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-1","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"1705":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-2","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#two-things-to-know-first","content":"Two things to know first"},"1706":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-3","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#create-a-customer","content":"Create a customer"},"1707":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-4","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#open-the-form","content":"Open the form"},"1708":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-5","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#enter-the-basics","content":"Enter the basics"},"1709":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-6","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#save","content":"Save"},"1710":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-7","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#add-contacts","content":"Add contacts"},"1711":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-8","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#open-the-contacts-tab","content":"Open the Contacts tab"},"1712":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-9","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#enter-their-details","content":"Enter their details"},"1713":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-10","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#save-and-repeat","content":"Save and repeat"},"1714":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-11","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#add-ship-to-and-bill-to-locations","content":"Add ship-to and bill-to locations"},"1715":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-12","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#open-the-locations-tab","content":"Open the Locations tab"},"1716":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-13","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#enter-the-address-and-role","content":"Enter the address and role"},"1717":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-14","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#save-1","content":"Save"},"1718":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-15","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#set-payment-terms","content":"Set payment terms"},"1719":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-16","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#open-the-payment-tab","content":"Open the Payment tab"},"1720":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-17","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#pick-the-terms","content":"Pick the terms"},"1721":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-18","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#save-2","content":"Save"},"1722":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-19","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#customer-specific-part-numbers","content":"Customer-specific part numbers"},"1723":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-20","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#reading-a-customer-record","content":"Reading a customer record"},"1724":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-21","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/customers#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"1725":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-22","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers","content":"A customer is anyone you sell to. Set one up once, and Carbon reuses their people, addresses,\nand payment terms on every quote, order, and invoice — no re-typing."},"1726":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-23","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Customers live in the Sales module. Open Sales from the home screen, then click\nCustomers in the sub-nav across the top."},"1727":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-24","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"The Customers list shows one row per company. We'll build out Radiant Aerospace — Acme's\nmost active customer, behind the Counterweight Hook order SO000069."},"1728":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-25","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#two-things-to-know-first","content":"Before you add customers, two fields are worth a quick look."},"1729":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-26","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#two-things-to-know-first","content":"Status — shows where a customer is in your relationship:"},"1730":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-27","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#two-things-to-know-first","content":"Lead — a prospect you're quoting, no order yet."},"1731":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-28","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#two-things-to-know-first","content":"Active — a live customer you can quote, order, and invoice."},"1732":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-29","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#two-things-to-know-first","content":"On Hold — paused, often for a payment issue."},"1733":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-30","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#two-things-to-know-first","content":"Inactive — no longer trading, kept for history."},"1734":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-31","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#two-things-to-know-first","content":"Cancelled — relationship closed."},"1735":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-32","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#two-things-to-know-first","content":"Type — a label for grouping customers, handy for filtering and reports. Acme groups by\nindustry. Radiant Aerospace is Aerospace & Defense."},"1736":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-33","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#two-things-to-know-first","content":"type: tip"},"1737":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-34","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#two-things-to-know-first","content":"Both lists are editable under Settings. Set up your statuses and types once so new customers\nland in the right bucket. See Set up your company."},"1738":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-35","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#create-a-customer","content":"Only a name is required. Filling in the rest now saves re-keying later."},"1739":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-36","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#open-the-form","content":"On the Customers list, click New Customer (top right)."},"1740":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-37","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#enter-the-basics","content":"Give the customer a name, then set the optional type, status, and currency."},"1741":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-38","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#save","content":"Click Save. Carbon assigns a customer ID automatically (Radiant's internal ID is\ncust_LxoH7AbowNVjTwGSoqkW1Q). The customer now appears on the list, and you can add the rest\nanytime."},"1742":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-39","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#add-contacts","content":"A contact is a person at the customer — a buyer, an engineer, an AP clerk. You pick a contact\nwhen you quote or order, and Carbon emails them the PDF."},"1743":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-40","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#open-the-contacts-tab","content":"On the customer record, click the Contacts tab, then New Contact."},"1744":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-41","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#enter-their-details","content":"Fill in name, email, phone, and (optionally) job title. Email matters most — it's what Carbon\nuses to send quotes and orders."},"1745":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-42","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#save-and-repeat","content":"Save, then add anyone else you deal with — for example a separate AP contact for invoices."},"1746":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-43","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#save-and-repeat","content":"type: tip"},"1747":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-44","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#save-and-repeat","content":"Contacts follow the paperwork. The contact you pick on an order flows straight onto its invoice —\non Radiant's order SO000069, the same contact appeared on invoice AR000025."},"1748":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-45","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#add-ship-to-and-bill-to-locations","content":"A location is an address. Carbon uses two roles:"},"1749":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-46","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#add-ship-to-and-bill-to-locations","content":"Ship-to — where goods are delivered. Drives shipments."},"1750":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-47","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#add-ship-to-and-bill-to-locations","content":"Bill-to — where invoices go. Drives accounting."},"1751":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-48","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#open-the-locations-tab","content":"On the customer record, click the Locations tab, then New Location."},"1752":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-49","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#enter-the-address-and-role","content":"Type the address, then tag it Ship-to, Bill-to, or both. Mark one as the default so\nCarbon pre-fills it on new orders. Radiant uses one HQ address for both roles — the most common\nsetup."},"1753":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-50","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#save-1","content":"Save each address. Carbon proposes the defaults on every new order, and you can switch in one click."},"1754":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-51","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#set-payment-terms","content":"Payment terms say when a customer should pay — for example Net 30 means \"due 30 days\nafter the invoice date.\" Set them on the customer and every invoice inherits the right due date."},"1755":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-52","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#open-the-payment-tab","content":"On the customer record, click the Payment tab."},"1756":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-53","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#pick-the-terms","content":"Choose the default payment terms and currency. Radiant Aerospace is Net 30 in USD."},"1757":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-54","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#save-2","content":"Save. From now on, invoices for this customer default to Net 30 — exactly what shows on\nRadiant's real invoice AR000025."},"1758":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-55","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#save-2","content":"type: tip"},"1759":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-56","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#save-2","content":"Terms are defaults, not handcuffs. You can override them on a single order or invoice anytime."},"1760":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-57","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#customer-specific-part-numbers","content":"Your customer often calls your part by their number. Acme's part is CWH-A36-15, but Radiant\norders it as 730562. Record that mapping once on the customer, and Carbon recognizes their PO\nreferences and prints their number on your paperwork."},"1761":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-58","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#customer-specific-part-numbers","content":"type: info"},"1762":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-59","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#customer-specific-part-numbers","content":"You'll see 730562 again on Radiant's order line in\nSales orders — Carbon carried it over with no extra typing."},"1763":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-60","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#reading-a-customer-record","content":"A finished customer is one screen of tabs. Here's Radiant Aerospace in Acme's system: the\nDetails tab summarizes the company, and the other tabs hold the contacts, locations, and terms\nyou just set up."},"1764":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-61","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#reading-a-customer-record","content":"type: warn"},"1765":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-62","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#reading-a-customer-record","content":"Don't create the same company twice — duplicates split a customer's history across two records.\nSearch the list first; if they're already there (even as a Lead), edit that record instead."},"1766":{"id":"/manual/selling/customers-63","page_id":"/manual/selling/customers","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/customers#next-steps","content":"You've got a customer with contacts, addresses, and terms. Now put them to work."},"1767":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","type":"page","content":"Quoting & estimating","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/quoting"},"1768":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-0","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting","content":"Build a quote, price it, send it and turn it into an order."},"1769":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-1","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/quoting#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"1770":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-2","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/quoting#build-the-quote","content":"Build the quote"},"1771":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-3","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/quoting#price-the-line","content":"Price the line"},"1772":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-4","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/quoting#send-it","content":"Send it"},"1773":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-5","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/quoting#convert-to-an-order","content":"Convert to an order"},"1774":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-6","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/quoting#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"1775":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-7","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting","content":"A quote answers a customer's \"what would this cost?\" You add a line for the part and a\nquantity, Carbon rolls up the cost behind it, and you set a price. When the customer says yes,\none click turns the quote into a sales order — nothing gets re-typed."},"1776":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-8","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting","content":"We'll follow Acme's real quote Q000061: 500 Counterweight Hooks for Radiant Aerospace\nat $73.14 each."},"1777":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-9","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Quotes live in the Sales module. Open Sales → Quotes to see every quote. Click a row\nto open one, or click the green Add Quote button (top-right) to start a new one."},"1778":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-10","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"type: info"},"1779":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-11","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"A quote is a price offer, not a commitment. Nothing gets made, bought, or billed until\nyou convert it to a sales order. So it's the safe place to\ntry quantities and adjust your margin."},"1780":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-12","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#build-the-quote","content":"Start it. Click the green Add Quote button, then pick Radiant Aerospace as the\ncustomer. Carbon pulls in their address, contact, currency (USD) and payment terms\n(Net 30) — so you don't re-key any of it."},"1781":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-13","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#build-the-quote","content":"Add a line. Click Add Line, set the type to Part, and choose Counterweight\nHook (CWH-A36-15). Carbon fills in the description and unit (EA, Each) from the item."},"1782":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-14","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#build-the-quote","content":"Enter the quantity. Type 500. Want to show a price ladder? Add more quantities to the\nsame line (say 100, 500, 1,000) and Carbon prices each one."},"1783":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-15","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#build-the-quote","content":"type: tip"},"1784":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-16","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#build-the-quote","content":"Quotes start in Draft — yours to edit freely before the customer sees them. Carbon also\nassigns the number (Q000061) and a revision automatically."},"1785":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-17","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#price-the-line","content":"For a Make to Order part, Carbon already knows the recipe — what it's made of and how it's\nmade. So it rolls up a real cost instead of asking you to guess."},"1786":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-18","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#price-the-line","content":"The Counterweight Hook is short: 40 lb of 1-inch A36 steel plate, then three operations."},"1787":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-19","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#price-the-line","content":"You set the price; Carbon shows the margin — the gap between what the work costs and\nwhat you charge. Type a price and the margin updates live; type a target margin and Carbon\nback-solves the price. Acme set $73.14 each:"},"1788":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-20","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#price-the-line","content":"type: warn"},"1789":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-21","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#price-the-line","content":"The cost rollup is only as good as the part's method. No bill of\nmaterials or routing yet? Carbon can't estimate the cost — build the method first, or quote\na known price and refine it later."},"1790":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-22","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#price-the-line","content":"type: tip"},"1791":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-23","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#price-the-line","content":"Selling the same kind of part in many shapes (cut plate, machined bar)? Use a\nconfigurator — one item that asks a few questions, then builds the method and cost for\nyou. Acme has the Flame Cut Part Configurator (FLAME CONFIG). See\nMethods: BOM & routing."},"1792":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-24","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#send-it","content":"Check the total. On Q000061 that's one line: 500 EA × $73.14 = $36,570.00."},"1793":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-25","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#send-it","content":"Click Send. Carbon builds the PDF, emails it to Radiant's contact, and moves the status\nfrom Draft to Sent — the ball is now in the customer's court."},"1794":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-26","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#convert-to-an-order","content":"When Radiant says yes, don't rebuild anything. On the quote, click Convert to Order.\nCarbon copies the customer, lines, quantities and prices onto a new\nsales order — here, SO000069 — and the two stay linked."},"1795":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-27","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#convert-to-an-order","content":"type: info"},"1796":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-28","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#convert-to-an-order","content":"The order total ($36,820.00) is higher than the quote line total ($36,570.00) because $250\nof shipping was added on the order. Quotes price the work; the order is where freight and\ntaxes get finalized."},"1797":{"id":"/manual/selling/quoting-29","page_id":"/manual/selling/quoting","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/quoting#convert-to-an-order","content":"Converting marks the quote Ordered (so you can always see what you offered) instead of\ndeleting it. A quote the customer passes on can be marked Lost instead — which keeps your\nwin/loss history honest."},"1798":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","type":"page","content":"Sales orders","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders"},"1799":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-0","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","content":"Capture demand and drive fulfillment from a sales order."},"1800":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-1","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"1801":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-2","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#two-parts-of-an-order","content":"Two parts of an order"},"1802":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-3","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#create-a-sales-order","content":"Create a sales order"},"1803":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-4","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#whats-on-a-line","content":"What's on a line"},"1804":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-5","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#pick-a-fulfillment-method","content":"Pick a fulfillment method"},"1805":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-6","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#order-statuses","content":"Order statuses"},"1806":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-7","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#track-shipments-and-invoices","content":"Track shipments and invoices"},"1807":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-8","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#common-gotchas","content":"Common gotchas"},"1808":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-9","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"1809":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-10","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","content":"A sales order is your customer's commitment to buy: who's ordering, what, how many,\nwhen it's due, and at what price. Enter it once and Carbon carries it everywhere — the\njob that makes the part, the shipment\nthat sends it, and the invoice that bills for it."},"1810":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-11","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","content":"This page follows Acme's real order SO000069 — 500 Counterweight Hooks for Radiant\nAerospace, $36,820, Make to Order."},"1811":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-12","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Sales orders live in the Sales module. Open Sales, then click Orders in the\nleft sub-nav to see every order and its status."},"1812":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-13","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"The list shows each order's number, customer, total, and status at a glance. Click a\nrow to open the order."},"1813":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-14","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#two-parts-of-an-order","content":"Every sales order has two parts:"},"1814":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-15","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#two-parts-of-an-order","content":"A header — facts for the whole order: the customer, the order date, the\npayment terms, the ship-from location, and the customer's own\nPO number."},"1815":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-16","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#two-parts-of-an-order","content":"One or more lines — each line is one thing the customer is buying: an item, a quantity,\na unit price, a promised date, and a fulfillment method."},"1816":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-17","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#two-parts-of-an-order","content":"Here's SO000069 open. The line CWH-A36-15 is 500 EA at $73.14. The tabs along the\ntop — Shipments and Invoices — show what went out and what was billed."},"1817":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-18","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#create-a-sales-order","content":"There are two ways an order is born. Converting a quote is by far the most common — it's\nhow SO000069 was created."},"1818":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-19","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#create-a-sales-order","content":"When a customer accepts a quote, you don't re-type anything.\nCarbon copies the lines, quantities, prices, and the linked method,\nand keeps the two records linked."},"1819":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-20","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#create-a-sales-order","content":"Open the accepted quote. Go to Sales → Quotes and open it — for Acme that's\nQ000061. Confirm the line, quantity, and price."},"1820":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-21","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#create-a-sales-order","content":"Convert to Order. Click Convert to Order in the top-right. Carbon creates SO000069\nand copies every line, including the Make to Order method on the hook line."},"1821":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-22","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#create-a-sales-order","content":"Review the header. Confirm the customer PO reference (55557777) and the\nship-from location (Headquarters). Set the order date if it isn't today."},"1822":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-23","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#create-a-sales-order","content":"Not every order comes from a quote — a repeat customer might just email a PO."},"1823":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-24","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#create-a-sales-order","content":"Add a new order. In Sales → Orders, click the green Add button, top-right. Pick\nthe customer (Radiant Aerospace). Carbon fills in their default\nterms, currency, and ship-to address."},"1824":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-25","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#create-a-sales-order","content":"Fill in the header. Set the order date, the ship-from location, and the\ncustomer's PO reference. Save to get an order number."},"1825":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-26","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#create-a-sales-order","content":"Add the lines. Add one line per item — covered next."},"1826":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-27","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#create-a-sales-order","content":"type: tip"},"1827":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-28","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#create-a-sales-order","content":"The customer PO reference (55557777) is the number your customer uses for the order.\nCapturing it prints it on the packing slip and invoice, so their accounts-payable team can\nmatch your bill without a phone call."},"1828":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-29","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#whats-on-a-line","content":"A line is one thing being sold. Open the Lines tab, pick the item, and Carbon pulls\nits description, unit, and a default price. Then you set quantity and the promised date."},"1829":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-30","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#pick-a-fulfillment-method","content":"The fulfillment method is the most important choice on a line. You set it per line, so\none order can ship some items from stock and make others to order."},"1830":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-31","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#pick-a-fulfillment-method","content":"SO000069's line is Make to Order — Acme doesn't stock 500 finished hooks, so each order is\nbuilt fresh. That one setting spawns Job J000097 when the order is confirmed."},"1831":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-32","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#pick-a-fulfillment-method","content":"type: info"},"1832":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-33","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#pick-a-fulfillment-method","content":"A line's default method comes from the item's\nreplenishment setting: a Make part defaults to Make to\nOrder, a Buy part to Pull from Stock. You can override it on any line."},"1833":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-34","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#order-statuses","content":"The status column on the Orders list tells you where each order is."},"1834":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-35","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#track-shipments-and-invoices","content":"The Shipments and Invoices buttons on the order are where fulfillment shows up. You\ndon't fill them in by hand — they populate as goods leave and bills post."},"1835":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-36","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#track-shipments-and-invoices","content":"Shipments — every time goods leave, a shipment record appears with the quantity and date.\nSO000069 has one shipment for all 500 hooks, sent 2026-06-11."},"1836":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-37","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#track-shipments-and-invoices","content":"Invoices — when you bill, the invoice pulls its lines from what shipped. SO000069 was\nbilled on AR000025 for $36,820 (goods plus $250 shipping) and marked Paid the same day."},"1837":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-38","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#track-shipments-and-invoices","content":"type: info"},"1838":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-39","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#track-shipments-and-invoices","content":"Radiant Aerospace keeps coming back: the same hook runs on SO000070 (1,500 EA, in\nprogress) and SO000071 (3,000 EA, queued). Each is its own order with its own job, but all\npoint back to the same item and method."},"1839":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-40","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#common-gotchas","content":"Check the line's fulfillment method. A job is only created for Make to Order lines. If\nthe line is Pull from Stock, Carbon reserves inventory instead — no job."},"1840":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-41","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#common-gotchas","content":"Lines copied from a quote carry the quoted price. A line you add by hand uses the item's default\nsell price, which may differ. When in doubt, convert from the quote rather than re-keying."},"1841":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders-42","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-orders","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-orders#common-gotchas","content":"Yes. A line can ship partially — send what's ready now, the rest later. The line stays To Ship\nuntil the full quantity has gone out. The order reaches Completed only when every line is fully\nshipped and invoiced."},"1842":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","type":"page","content":"From sales order to shipment","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment"},"1843":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-0","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","content":"Follow an order all the way to a shipped, invoiced job."},"1844":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-1","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this lives in Carbon"},"1845":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-2","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#the-path-in-four-moves","content":"The path, in four moves"},"1846":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-3","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#everything-runs-from-the-order","content":"Everything runs from the order"},"1847":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-4","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-1--a-make-to-order-line-creates-a-job","content":"Step 1 — A Make-to-Order line creates a job"},"1848":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-5","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-2--watch-fulfillment-on-the-order","content":"Step 2 — Watch fulfillment on the order"},"1849":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-6","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-3--create-the-shipment","content":"Step 3 — Create the shipment"},"1850":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-7","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-4--the-line-reads-shipped","content":"Step 4 — The line reads Shipped"},"1851":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-8","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-5--invoice-the-order","content":"Step 5 — Invoice the order"},"1852":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-9","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#the-back-half-in-one-table","content":"The back half, in one table"},"1853":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-10","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"1854":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-11","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","content":"You took the order. Now you have to deliver it. This page follows the back half of a sale:\nhow a confirmed order becomes a finished, shipped, and invoiced job."},"1855":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-12","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","content":"We use one real example all the way through — the 500 Counterweight Hooks (part\nCWH-A36-15) Acme made for Radiant Aerospace on sales order SO000069."},"1856":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-13","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"This flow lives mostly in the Sales module, with one stop in Inventory (the shipment).\nOpen Sales → Orders, then click your order to see the buttons that drive everything below."},"1857":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-14","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"type: info"},"1858":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-15","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#where-this-lives-in-carbon","content":"Where this fits. This is the last leg of selling: Quote → Sales Order → make it → ship\nit → invoice it. It picks up after Sales orders and hands\noff to Accounting."},"1859":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-16","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#the-path-in-four-moves","content":"Our line is Make to Order, so it gets built before it ships. Here is the whole chain:"},"1860":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-17","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#everything-runs-from-the-order","content":"Open SO000069 and you get a row of action buttons across the top — including Shipments and\nInvoices. You do not leave the order to ship or bill. You click these buttons, and Carbon\nfills in the rest from the order."},"1861":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-18","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#everything-runs-from-the-order","content":"type: tip"},"1862":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-19","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#everything-runs-from-the-order","content":"Carbon copies the part, quantity, and price forward at every step. You confirm numbers — you\nalmost never re-type them."},"1863":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-20","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-1--a-make-to-order-line-creates-a-job","content":"Each order line is set to Make to Order or Pull from Inventory."},"1864":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-21","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-1--a-make-to-order-line-creates-a-job","content":"Make to Order — the part gets built. Confirming the order creates a job."},"1865":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-22","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-1--a-make-to-order-line-creates-a-job","content":"Pull from Inventory — the part is already on a shelf, so you skip straight to shipping."},"1866":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-23","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-1--a-make-to-order-line-creates-a-job","content":"Line 1 on SO000069 is Make to Order. Confirming the order created job J000097 for 500\npieces, due 2026-06-26. The job links back to its order, customer, and quote — so the shop\nfloor knows why it's building these hooks."},"1867":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-24","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-1--a-make-to-order-line-creates-a-job","content":"type: warn"},"1868":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-25","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-1--a-make-to-order-line-creates-a-job","content":"A Make-to-Order line can't ship until its job is done. Building the job is covered in\nJobs. The rest of this page assumes the 500 hooks are made and\nin stock."},"1869":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-26","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-2--watch-fulfillment-on-the-order","content":"The sales order is your dashboard for \"how close are we?\" Every line keeps three running tallies,\nupdated automatically:"},"1870":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-27","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-2--watch-fulfillment-on-the-order","content":"Ordered — how many the customer asked for."},"1871":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-28","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-2--watch-fulfillment-on-the-order","content":"Shipped — how many have left the dock."},"1872":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-29","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-2--watch-fulfillment-on-the-order","content":"Invoiced — how many you've billed."},"1873":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-30","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-2--watch-fulfillment-on-the-order","content":"When shipped catches up to ordered, the line is delivered. When invoiced catches up\ntoo, the line is done."},"1874":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-31","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-3--create-the-shipment","content":"A shipment is the record of goods leaving your dock. It's also the event that bumps the\nshipped tally. Start it from the order's Shipments button."},"1875":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-32","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-3--create-the-shipment","content":"Click Shipments → New. Carbon pre-fills the customer (Radiant Aerospace), the ship-to\naddress, and the open order lines."},"1876":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-33","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-3--create-the-shipment","content":"Pick the finished goods. Enter how many of each line you're sending. All 500 hooks came in\nfrom job J000097, so enter 500 EA. Because A36 steel is batch-tracked, Carbon records which\nbatch ships — that's the traceability link."},"1877":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-34","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-3--create-the-shipment","content":"Choose a shipping method. Pick the carrier and service you quoted. For a heavy steel order,\nthat's usually a freight method like LTL (Less Than Truckload), not a parcel service."},"1878":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-35","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-3--create-the-shipment","content":"Post the shipment. Posting removes the hooks from inventory and adds 500 to the line's\nshipped count. The shipment is saved and linked to the order."},"1879":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-36","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-3--create-the-shipment","content":"type: tip"},"1880":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-37","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-3--create-the-shipment","content":"You can ship a line in more than one go. Finish only 300 of 500? Ship 300 now — Carbon\nrecords a partial shipment and keeps the line open for the rest."},"1881":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-38","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-4--the-line-reads-shipped","content":"Once shipped equals ordered, the line status flips to Shipped. For SO000069, one\nshipment of 500 finished the line."},"1882":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-39","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-5--invoice-the-order","content":"With the goods shipped, you can bill. A sales invoice is your request for payment. Carbon\nbuilds it from what actually shipped, so it can't drift from reality. Start it from the order's\nInvoices button."},"1883":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-40","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-5--invoice-the-order","content":"Click Invoices → New. Carbon drafts invoice AR000025, pulling line 1 in at the shipped\nquantity (500) and the order price ($73.14)."},"1884":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-41","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-5--invoice-the-order","content":"Check the totals. Goods are 500 × $73.14 = $36,570. The $250 shipping cost carries\nover, making the total $36,820. Payment terms (Net 30) come from the customer record."},"1885":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-42","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-5--invoice-the-order","content":"Post and send it. Posting books the revenue and marks the line fully invoiced. Send it to\nRadiant; when they pay, mark it Paid — exactly how AR000025 ended, paid the same day."},"1886":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-43","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-5--invoice-the-order","content":"type: info"},"1887":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-44","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#step-5--invoice-the-order","content":"Subtotal vs. total. The subtotal ($36,570) is the goods alone. The total ($36,820)\nadds the $250 freight. The order total and invoice total match — the gap is always shipping."},"1888":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-45","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#the-back-half-in-one-table","content":"One line, one self-linking chain — nothing re-typed between steps:"},"1889":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-46","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#the-back-half-in-one-table","content":"type: tip"},"1890":{"id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment-47","page_id":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/manual/selling/sales-to-shipment#the-back-half-in-one-table","content":"Want the wider context? The 15-minute walkthrough runs this exact\nexample end to end, from quote to cash."}},"count":1890},"sorting":{"l