":1463,"1834":1456,"1835":1259,"1836":710,"1837":1614,"1838":1082,"1839":312,"1840":758,"1841":1852,"1842":575,"1843":553,"1844":1840,"1845":1438,"1846":527,"1847":1306,"1848":1312,"1849":1314,"1850":1319,"1851":1322,"1852":1366,"1853":880,"1854":1882,"1855":1760,"1856":1500,"1857":1615,"1858":1812,"1859":974,"1860":943,"1861":1677,"1862":278,"1863":471,"1864":786,"1865":1049,"1866":756,"1867":1713,"1868":84,"1869":1454,"1870":972,"1871":1260,"1872":709,"1873":1798,"1874":110,"1875":336,"1876":1005,"1877":317,"1878":1026,"1879":1678,"1880":1861,"1881":925,"1882":1845,"1883":328,"1884":314,"1885":1020,"1886":1616,"1887":1336,"1888":929,"1889":1679,"1890":1754},"orderedDocs":[[188,"\"active\" BOOLEAN DEFAULT TRUE - Soft delete pattern"],[957,"\"Any purchase orders in Draft older than a week?\" (PO000056 to Ryerson would surface.)"],[963,"\"Bump the priority on job J000099 to the top of the queue.\""],[962,"\"Create a quote for 500 Counterweight Hooks for Radiant Aerospace at $73.14 each.\""],[191,"\"createdAt\" TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE NOT NULL DEFAULT NOW()"],[190,"\"createdBy\" TEXT NOT NULL - FK to user"],[189,"\"customFields\" JSONB - Extensibility"],[186,"\"description\" TEXT - Optional descriptions"],[184,"\"id\" TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT id() - Primary key"],[958,"\"List jobs past their due date that aren't complete.\""],[954,"\"List open purchase orders to Ryerson.\""],[185,"\"name\" TEXT NOT NULL - Common for most entities"],[1106,"\"Post\" is the verb that matters. Until you post, a receipt or shipment is a draft you can edit or delete — nothing has moved. Posting is the commit: stock levels change and the source document updates. Get the numbers right before you post."],[960,"\"Release every sales order stuck in Needs Approval for 3+ days.\""],[952,"\"Show every job for Radiant Aerospace that isn't finished yet.\""],[187,"\"status\" ENUM - Status of the entity"],[193,"\"updatedAt\" TIMESTAMP WITH TIME ZONE - Nullable timestamp"],[192,"\"updatedBy\" TEXT - Nullable FK to user"],[953,"\"What did we invoice Radiant on AR000025, and is it paid?\""],[950,"\"What's the on-hand quantity of A36 steel?\""],[959,"\"Which invoices are overdue and unpaid?\""],[955,"\"Which sales orders have been stuck in Needs Approval for 3+ days?\""],[116,"@carbon/* - For packages"],[42,"/apps/erp/"],[43,"/apps/mes/"],[295,"<module>_create"],[297,"<module>_delete"],[296,"<module>_update"],[294,"<module>_view"],[117,"~/ - For app-specific imports (configured in tsconfig)"],[701,"1 — Units & locations"],[1166,"1. Automatically, from a Make-to-Order sales order line. Carbon offers to spin up a job,\npre-filled with the part, quantity, customer and due date — and keeps it linked to the line.\nThat's how J000097 was born, straight from\nsales order SO000069."],[753,"1. Company profile"],[1300,"1. Item"],[136,"1. Table Creation Patterns"],[702,"2 — Items"],[138,"2. ID Generation"],[754,"2. Locations"],[1169,"2. Manually, when a job stands on its own — building to stock, a rework batch, or a\none-off. Here's the click path:"],[1301,"2. Method (BOM + routing)"],[1595,"20 · Sandblasting — Sand Blasting Room, 2 Minutes/Piece."],[703,"3 — Customers & suppliers"],[140,"3. Company-Based Multi-Tenancy"],[1302,"3. Quote and Sales Order"],[756,"3. Units of measure"],[1596,"30 · Inspection — Inspection Station, 10 Minutes/Piece."],[704,"4 — Opening inventory"],[1303,"4. Job"],[757,"4. Number sequences"],[142,"4. RLS (Row Level Security) Patterns"],[705,"5 — BOMs & methods"],[150,"5. Common Column Types and Constraints"],[758,"5. Payment terms"],[1304,"5. Purchase Order"],[706,"6 — Open orders"],[155,"6. Foreign Key Relationships"],[1305,"6. Traceability"],[158,"7. Indexes and Unique Constraints"],[162,"8. Views"],[164,"9. Additional Patterns"],[1014,"A backend that pushes shipments into Carbon."],[1539,"A batch of 500 hooks needs 20,000 LB — not 500 whole sheets."],[1742,"A contact is a person at the customer — a buyer, an engineer, an AP clerk. You pick a contact\nwhen you quote or order, and Carbon emails them the PDF."],[1725,"A customer is anyone you sell to. Set one up once, and Carbon reuses their people, addresses,\nand payment terms on every quote, order, and invoice — no re-typing."],[1075,"A cycle count is a scheduled count of part of your inventory — a few bins at a time,\nrotating through everything — so you catch drift without stopping production."],[629,"A draft commits you to nothing. Two steps make it a real order."],[1615,"A few real items, side by side"],[1763,"A finished customer is one screen of tabs. Here's Radiant Aerospace in Acme's system: the\nDetails tab summarizes the company, and the other tabs hold the contacts, locations, and terms\nyou just set up."],[1814,"A header — facts for the whole order: the customer, the order date, the\npayment terms, the ship-from location, and the customer's own\nPO number."],[1334,"A job is a production order — the instruction to actually make a quantity. It lives in\nthe Production module."],[1197,"A job moves through four statuses, from idea to finished parts:"],[1237,"A job must be released before the floor can touch it. Statuses go in order: Draft → Planned → Ready → In Progress → Completed. Releasing is on the Jobs page."],[1337,"A job needs materials. The hook's BOM calls for 40 LB of steel each — 20,000 LB for 500 —\nand steel is a Buy item. So Carbon raises a Purchase Order (PO) in the Purchasing\nmodule: your commitment to a supplier."],[1152,"A job tells the shop floor to make a set quantity of a part by a set date."],[1007,"A key has the same permissions as the user who made it. If you can't approve purchase orders\nin the app, your key can't either. See Users & permissions."],[74,"A lightweight Supabase client for calling the Carbon API from C# projects."],[94,"A lightweight Supabase client for calling the Carbon API from TypeScript or JavaScript projects."],[1828,"A line is one thing being sold. Open the Lines tab, pick the item, and Carbon pulls\nits description, unit, and a default price. Then you set quantity and the promised date."],[1832,"A line's default method comes from the item's\nreplenishment setting: a Make part defaults to Make to\nOrder, a Buy part to Pull from Stock. You can override it on any line."],[1415,"A list shows many records of one kind — every order, every part — one per row. Use it to\nfind, filter and scan."],[1052,"A location is a physical site where you hold stock. Small shops run one; bigger ones run\nseveral. Acme has two:"],[774,"A location is a physical site where you make things, hold\nstock, or ship from. Carbon tracks inventory and work centers per location. Acme runs two."],[1748,"A location is an address. Carbon uses two roles:"],[1480,"A look at Acme's items"],[1868,"A Make-to-Order line can't ship until its job is done. Building the job is covered in\nJobs. The rest of this page assumes the 500 hooks are made and\nin stock."],[1522,"A material is the raw stock you buy and then cut, machine or form into parts — a steel\nplate, an aluminum billet, a length of brass bar. In Carbon, a material is a kind of\nitem, described the way a metals distributor sells it:\na substance, a form, a grade, and dimensions."],[1489,"A Material is what you consume to make a Part. The hook is cut from A36 Steel Plate\n(A36-STEEL-PLT-1\".96x240), which is a Material."],[1574,"A method is Carbon's recipe for a part you make. It has two halves: what the part is made of (the bill of materials) and how it's built (the routing)."],[730,"A method is how a made item is built: its bill of materials\n(what it's made of) plus its routing (the operations that make it). Methods only work once\nthe parent and all child items already exist — which is why they come after Step 2."],[1323,"A method is the recipe for a Make item. It has two halves:"],[1192,"A new job is Planned — a draft you can edit freely. Nothing reaches the floor until you\nrelease it."],[1013,"A nightly script that exports your orders."],[1488,"A Part is what you deliver. Acme's Counterweight Hook (CWH-A36-15) is a Part."],[1410,"A part name — type Counterweight Hook to find the item plus the orders and jobs that use it."],[1199,"A Planned job does nothing on its own. It won't appear on the shop floor and operators\ncan't book time until you release it. If a job seems \"stuck,\" check whether it's still\nPlanned."],[611,"A PO has two parts, shown as tabs on the record:"],[631,"A PO walks through these statuses:"],[859,"A purchase invoice is the mirror image: the bill a supplier sends you. When steel arrives\nfrom Ryerson, you enter their bill so the books know what's owed."],[951,"A pure READ. Nothing changes. More safe reads:"],[1366,"A quick way to remember the item types: Part and Material become the product (one is\nmade/sold, one is consumed into it), while Tool, Fixture and Consumable are what\nyou use to do the work. A Service is work itself rather than a thing."],[1775,"A quote answers a customer's \"what would this cost?\" You add a line for the part and a\nquantity, Carbon rolls up the cost behind it, and you set a price. When the customer says yes,\none click turns the quote into a sales order — nothing gets re-typed."],[1779,"A quote is a price offer, not a commitment. Nothing gets made, bought, or billed until\nyou convert it to a sales order. So it's the safe place to\ntry quantities and adjust your margin."],[907,"A read is as direct as it sounds. Ask for sales order SO000069, get its lines back. A webhook\nhandler can use the recordId it received:"],[673,"A real shop keeps a mix of vendors. The Type column groups them so you can filter the\nlist later."],[1420,"A record (or detail) shows one thing in full — all its fields, a status badge, and\ntabs that group related info. On a sales order like SO000069, the Lines tab holds the\nparts ordered, Shipments holds what was sent, Invoices holds the bills."],[1409,"A record number you already know — type SO000069 and press Enter to land on it."],[1605,"A revision is a named iteration of the part (Rev 0, Rev A…). The hook is at revision 0."],[852,"A sales invoice is how you get paid. You rarely type one from scratch — you create it from a\nshipment, and Carbon copies the customer, parts, quantities and prices off what shipped."],[1809,"A sales order is your customer's commitment to buy: who's ordering, what, how many,\nwhen it's due, and at what price. Enter it once and Carbon carries it everywhere — the\njob that makes the part, the shipment\nthat sends it, and the invoice that bills for it."],[1411,"A screen — type Suppliers or Work Centers to jump straight to that list."],[1874,"A shipment is the record of goods leaving your dock. It's also the event that bumps the\nshipped tally. Start it from the order's Shipments button."],[1134,"A shipment record is created — the link the invoice reads from next."],[354,"A smaller subset of the table can be listened to by passing a second argument. Here we listen for the rows with an id of 1, 2, or 3:"],[1226,"A suggestion is a proposal, never automatic. Carbon won't raise a PO or release a job on its own — you always confirm."],[668,"A supplier (or vendor) is any company you buy from — a steel mill, a parts\ndistributor, an anodizer. Add one before you can order from it. This page shows how, using\nAcme's real vendors."],[554,"A supplier quote is the buying-side mirror of a sales quote. Carbon\nmakes one per supplier you ask."],[941,"A thousand-plus tools is too many to hand an assistant at once. So Carbon hides them behind\njust three tools. The assistant uses these to find and run everything else on demand."],[1370,"A tour of the app: modules, layout, search and where to find things."],[780,"A unit of measure (UoM) is how you count a thing — each, pounds, gallons, feet. Every\nitem has one. The Counterweight Hook is counted in EA (Each);\nthe steel plate it's cut from is measured in LB (Pound). Acme runs 16 in total."],[715,"A unit of measure (UoM) is how you count an item: EA for each, LB for pounds. A\nlocation is a site that holds stock. Carbon ships with the common UoMs, so usually you're\njust confirming they exist."],[813,"A user is one login — one person, one email."],[287,"A user's permissions are stored in the userPermissions table and the role is stored in the auth.users table in the raw_app_meta_data column."],[1606,"A version is Carbon's snapshot of a method. A job takes its own copy when it's created. Editing the part's master method later does not change a job already in flight."],[898,"A webhook lets Carbon call you. Instead of asking \"anything new yet?\" over and over, you\ngive Carbon a URL once. Carbon sends an HTTP request to that URL whenever an event you care\nabout happens. Think of it as Carbon tapping you on the shoulder."],[933,"A worked example"],[1354,"A worked example, term by term"],[1342,"A36 steel is batch-tracked. So Carbon links the exact lot received on PO000057 to the\nexact 500 hooks on J000097, and through the order to Radiant Aerospace."],[1116,"A36 Steel Plate is batch-tracked, so Carbon asks which heat of steel this is. Type the supplier's heat/lot number into the Batch field. This is what later lets you trace the steel that went into Radiant's hooks. Plain items don't show this field."],[640,"A36 Steel Plate is batch-tracked, so the receipt asks for a lot number — that's how Acme can\nlater trace a hook back to the exact heat of steel it came from."],[224,"Academy (Training App) - Located at /apps/academy/"],[812,"Access comes from two things. Keep them separate and it stays easy."],[129,"Accessibility considerations (ARIA attributes)"],[1401,"Accounting"],[835,"Accounting & invoicing"],[687,"Acme buys from Ryerson on Net 30 — the same terms that carry onto purchase order\nPO000057."],[513,"Acme is short on 1-inch plate, so Carbon flags it and you raise a purchase order to your\nsteel supplier, Ryerson (PO000057). The Purchasing module tracks all of this."],[716,"Acme keeps it small — EA for parts, LB for raw materials — and runs two sites,\nHeadquarters and Texas."],[1057,"Acme names bins by position. R02-B01-01 means Rack 02, Row B, Level 01,\nPosition 01. The A36 Steel Plate lives in R02-B01-01. That bin is its default\nstorage unit, so Carbon suggests it automatically when you receive or pick the plate."],[1338,"Acme ordered the steel on PO000057 from Ryerson. When it arrives, a receipt adds it\nto inventory and stamps the incoming batch — which sets up the last idea."],[1686,"Acme registers ten gauges (G00001–G00010), each on a six-month interval. Carbon computes the next-due date and flips overdue tools to Out of Calibration on its own:"],[544,"Acme sends parts to two outside suppliers, both set as Subcontractors and Service Providers:"],[1675,"Acme uses three workflows, from lightest to heaviest:"],[789,"Acme's hero order flows through these sequences: quote Q000061 becomes sales order\nSO000069, spawns job J000097, triggers purchase order PO000057, and finishes\nwith invoice AR000025."],[1517,"Acme's material catalog"],[658,"Acme's suppliers"],[903,"Act on it. Fetch the details, then push them where they need to go. For SO000069, that could\nmean grabbing the line for 500 Counterweight Hooks at $73.14 and posting \"New order: $36,820 from\nRadiant Aerospace\" to Slack."],[110,"Action Pattern"],[1731,"Active — a live customer you can quote, order, and invoice."],[662,"Add a contact"],[1781,"Add a line. Click Add Line, set the type to Part, and choose Counterweight\nHook (CWH-A36-15). Carbon fills in the description and unit (EA, Each) from the item."],[663,"Add a location"],[779,"Add a location for every site that holds inventory or ships product. One building? One\nlocation is fine. Just don't lump two separate warehouses together, or your on-hand counts\nwon't match reality. More in Locations & stock."],[1564,"Add a material line"],[1823,"Add a new order. In Sales → Orders, click the green Add button, top-right. Pick\nthe customer (Radiant Aerospace). Carbon fills in their default\nterms, currency, and ship-to address."],[1072,"Add a reason and post. Pick a reason (damaged, miscount, found stock). Posting updates\non-hand, writes the ledger entry, and books the value change."],[973,"Add Carbon as an MCP server. In your assistant's connectors or MCP section, add a server\npointing at app.carbon.ms/mcp. Paste your key, or finish the OAuth sign-in."],[1710,"Add contacts"],[1714,"Add ship-to and bill-to locations"],[1568,"Add the first operation"],[594,"Add the line"],[1825,"Add the lines. Add one line per item — covered next."],[546,"Add the operation and set its type to Outside. Open the part's Manufacturing tab, add\nthe operation where the service belongs, and choose Outside as the type."],[1570,"Add the other two steps"],[1555,"Add the supplier and save. On the Suppliers tab, add Ryerson at $0.25/LB, then\nSave. The material can now drop onto any method and onto a\npurchase order like PO000057."],[689,"Add them two ways:"],[1095,"Add tracking (optional)"],[293,"Additionally, each user has a set of permissions for each module. Generally, the permissions are:"],[637,"Adds the material to inventory at the deliver-to location."],[1223,"Adjust before you commit. Change a quantity or pull a date earlier. Acme's PO000057 ended up at 54,001 LB — the buyer rounded up to cover the next two Radiant orders."],[1074,"Adjustments are for corrections only. Don't adjust stock down to \"use it up\" (that's\nconsuming material on a job) or to move it between sites\n(that's a transfer)."],[520,"Advanced purchasing"],[64,"After setup, sync your Novu workflows with the Carbon application:"],[924,"AI & the MCP server"],[834,"AI and API access run through this same system. An AI agent or API key inherits the access of\nthe user it acts as, so scope it tight. More in\nDeveloping with Carbon."],[174,"Almost all business tables include \"companyId\" TEXT NOT NULL"],[1414,"Almost everything in Carbon is one of two screens. Knowing the difference is most of \"knowing\nthe app.\""],[1482,"Almost everything in Carbon starts with an item — a single, named thing you make, buy,\nsell, or use. Every quote, order, job and invoice points back to an item."],[843,"Already using QuickBooks?"],[747,"Always run a small test batch first — five or ten rows — before importing thousands. A\ntiny run surfaces a wrong mapping or bad UoM code in seconds, not after you've created 5,000\nmis-mapped parts."],[1023,"Always-current package names and install commands live in the Clients section of\nthe Developer Docs."],[1012,"An API key authenticates you (or one service account). Best for the work most readers do:"],[970,"An API key is a password. Store it in your assistant's secret settings (never paste it into\na chat), give each integration its own key, and revoke a key the moment it's done."],[1464,"An API lets other software read and write your data. Carbon is API-first: every\nscreen you click does the same thing a program could do through the API. So you can\nconnect Carbon to your other tools and automate the boring parts. More in\nUsing the API."],[632,"An approver opens the order, checks the lines and total, and approves it. If something's\nwrong, they reject it back to Draft."],[814,"An employee type is a role: a bundle of\npermissions you attach to a user. Set it up once, hand it to\neveryone who does that job."],[823,"An employee type is the role you hand someone. It carries a default set of permissions, so\nyou don't set up each person from scratch. Here are types a shop like Acme would use."],[1685,"An inspection is only as good as the tool doing the measuring. A gauge is any measuring instrument — a micrometer, height gauge, or thread plug. Gauges drift over time, so each one is calibrated on a schedule. Open Gauges from the Quality sub-nav."],[869,"An invoice says money should move; a payment records that it did. They're separate\nsteps on purpose — the gap between them is the time an invoice is \"outstanding.\""],[1316,"An item is anything you make, buy, store, or sell. It's the noun everything points to."],[1671,"An NCR — also called an Issue in Carbon — is the record you open when something is off-spec: a bad part, a bad batch of steel, a customer complaint. It captures what happened, how bad it is, what you did, and how you proved the fix worked."],[340,"An open source ERP system has a number of benefits, including:"],[1269,"An operation turns Ready only after the step before it finishes. So a job's three operations light up one at a time, in order."],[1282,"An operator can only be clocked on to one operation at a time. If Fred forgets to clock off before lunch, his time keeps running. Habit: Pause when you step away, Finish when the step is done. A manager can fix a bad entry later in the ERP, but it's cleaner to get it right on the floor."],[1693,"An out-of-calibration gauge taints every measurement made with it. If G00003 was used to accept parts after its 2026-03-03 due date, you can't trust those results — which can itself become a Testing Failure NCR."],[207,"An overview of the Carbon repo"],[999,"Anything you can do by clicking in Carbon, you can also do with code. Carbon is API-first:\nthe web app and the API talk to the same backend. If it's in the app, it's in the API."],[990,"API key or OAuth?"],[72,"API Reference"],[83,"API Reference"],[92,"API Reference"],[267,"API routes under api+/ prefix"],[8,"API-first: Carbon apps are built with a single API that you have access to"],[165,"Approval Workflow"],[597,"Approve"],[583,"Approve and send. New POs land in Draft or Needs Approval (like PO000057 did).\nFrom there it's the normal purchasing basics loop."],[595,"Approve it and send it"],[462,"apps/erp/app/modules/inventory/inventory.service.ts:"],[98,"apps/erp/app/modules/production/production.service.ts"],[97,"apps/erp/app/modules/purchasing/purchasing.service.ts"],[99,"apps/erp/app/modules/sales/sales.service.ts"],[466,"apps/mes/app/services/operations.service.ts:"],[205,"Arrays: DEFAULT ARRAY[]::text[]"],[1283,"As pieces come off the table, the operator reports two numbers:"],[1026,"Ask Carbon for a page of items. Rows back means your key works."],[1681,"Assign and work the actions. Each required action is a checklist item with an owner and status."],[79,"Async Python client for implementing Carbon into your apps"],[1543,"At receipt, Carbon records a batch number when steel arrives from\nRyerson on PO000057. The\npounds are tagged with that batch."],[413,"attributes - Additional metadata about the transformation"],[395,"attributes - JSONB containing:"],[152,"Audit Columns"],[238,"auth - Authentication services and utilities"],[112,"Authentication Pattern"],[232,"Authentication: Cookie based session and environment management via /packages/auth/"],[1018,"Automating your own company? Use an API key and skip OAuth. Building an app other companies\ninstall? The full OAuth flow is in the Developer Docs."],[1063,"Available is the number to watch when promising work: roughly on hand minus committed,\nplus confidently inbound. For a buy-to-stock material like A36 plate, a low available number\nis your cue to reorder. The hook is Make-to-Order, so Carbon builds each batch on a job\ninstead of stocking ahead."],[211,"Backend"],[1698,"Backward (recall): \"A bad heat shipped — which orders?\" Follow the batch forward to J000097, then SO000069, and you land on Radiant Aerospace in seconds."],[1230,"Balance the load. When a process has more than one machine, move work to a less-busy one. Flame Cut can run on Burn Table PA1, PA2, or the Texas table."],[137,"Basic Table Structure"],[1340,"Batch — a lot number shared by units made or received together (steel, paint)."],[397,"Batch numbers"],[1519,"Batch tracking and traceability"],[1695,"Batch tracking groups material by lot. A36 Steel Plate has batch tracking on, so every receipt records the heat of steel from the mill."],[1067,"Batch tracking. A36 Steel Plate has batch tracking on, so Carbon records a batch\nnumber (often the supplier's heat number) on receipt and remembers which batch went into\nwhich finished parts. That's genealogy — full detail in\nTracking quality."],[514,"Because A36 plate is batch-tracked, Carbon records exactly which steel went into this batch\nof hooks — the start of full traceability."],[1697,"Because every record links to the next, you can read the chain either way:"],[1456,"Because it's one system, hand-offs are automatic. The estimator doesn't email the order to\nthe floor — the order becomes a job. The inspector doesn't keep a separate binder — the\ninspection is a step on that same job."],[982,"Because the assistant chains reads, you can ask layered questions: \"Do we have enough A36\nsteel to finish job J000099 (3,000 hooks), and if not, how much do we need to buy?\" It\nreads the job's material need, reads inventory, and does the math."],[1185,"Because the job carries its own copy of the method, you can tweak it for this run only —\nswap a material, add a step, change a time — without touching the part's master method or any\nother job."],[511,"Because the order is Make to Order, Carbon creates a job (J000097) for 500 pieces. The\nProduction module is mission control for the shop — here you can see active jobs and how busy\neach work center is."],[1274,"Because the steel is batch-tracked, the operator picks which batch they used — that's what makes traceability possible later."],[1362,"Because they share one system, finishing a shop-floor step (MES) updates the job cost (ERP) and\nrecords which material went in (QMS) — all at once, with no re-typing."],[1728,"Before you add customers, two fields are worth a quick look."],[553,"Before you buy something expensive, you usually want more than one price. A Request for Quote\n(RFQ) does that: describe what you want, send it to several suppliers, collect their\nsupplier quotes, compare, then convert the winner to a PO — no re-typing."],[1064,"Behind those live numbers sits the item ledger — a log of every stock move, ever.\nReceipts, job consumption, shipments, and adjustments each write one row. On-hand is just the\nrunning total of the ledger, so every number traces back to the move that caused it."],[327,"Best open-source software"],[343,"Better security"],[749,"Big or repeatable migration? Carbon is API-first — anything\nyou can type in, you can script. For a large move or a recurring sync, scripting against the\nAPI beats hand-mapping CSVs. You can even have an AI assistant drive it through Carbon's\nbuilt-in MCP server. See\nUsing the API."],[1324,"Bill of Materials (BOM) — what it's made of. The hook's BOM is one line: 40 LB of\nA36 steel plate."],[1580,"Bill of materials (BOM) — what the part is made of. A list of materials and sub-parts, each with a quantity per finished piece. The hook needs one line: 40 LB of A36 steel plate."],[1750,"Bill-to — where invoices go. Drives accounting."],[733,"BOM lines — one row per material, linking a parent readableId to a child\nreadableId with a quantity. For the hook: parent CWH-A36-15, child\nA36-STEEL-PLT-1\".96x240, qty 40 LB."],[203,"Booleans: DEFAULT TRUE or DEFAULT FALSE"],[1524,"Both are items, so they share the same fields — ID, unit of measure, costs, inventory,\nsuppliers. They differ in what they describe and how you get them."],[1737,"Both lists are editable under Settings. Set up your statuses and types once so new customers\nland in the right bucket. See Set up your company."],[1104,"Both live in the Inventory module. Open it from the home screen, then use the sub-nav at the top to switch between Quantities, Receipts, and Shipments."],[1262,"Both read the same job, so you never enter anything twice. A manager watches it all from the Production module in the ERP."],[364,"Bridge Tables: trackedActivityInput & trackedActivityOutput"],[698,"Bring your items, customers and suppliers into Carbon."],[1768,"Build a quote, price it, send it and turn it into an order."],[887,"Build apps on the API"],[1562,"Build the bill of materials"],[1770,"Build the quote"],[1567,"Build the routing"],[212,"Build Tools"],[234,"Bundler: Vite"],[1624,"Buy — Carbon orders it from a supplier on a purchase order.\nIt needs a supplier and a price. The A36 steel plate it's cut from is Buy."],[1319,"Buy — you order it from a supplier. Demand creates a Purchase Order."],[1392,"Buy materials and services from suppliers"],[1158,"By when? The due date — 2026-06-26."],[67,"C# Client"],[978,"call_tool takes on the safety class of whatever it runs. Calling\ninventory_getItemQuantities through it is a READ; calling sales_deleteSalesOrder through\nit is DESTRUCTIVE. So the READ-first habit still matters."],[945,"Calls it. Runs call_tool with the A36 plate's item ID, then answers in a sentence."],[311,"can - a function that takes a module (sales) and an action (view, create, update, delete) and returns a boolean indicating whether the user has the required permission."],[1734,"Cancelled — relationship closed."],[1799,"Capture demand and drive fulfillment from a sales order."],[1048,"Carbon always knows two things about your stuff: where it is and how much you have.\nThis page shows how the Inventory module tracks both."],[680,"Carbon assigns the next ID (SUP000013) and opens the full record. The other tabs now unlock."],[1862,"Carbon copies the part, quantity, and price forward at every step. You confirm numbers — you\nalmost never re-type them."],[672,"Carbon gives every supplier a short ID like SUP000013. The friendly name shows\neverywhere; the ID keeps it stable even if you rename the company."],[935,"Carbon has a built-in MCP server. It lets an AI assistant — Claude, ChatGPT, or your\ncode editor — read and act inside your Carbon company using plain English. You ask a\nquestion; the assistant does the clicking for you."],[1308,"Carbon has a lot of screens, but only a few ideas. Learn these and the rest is just detail.\nWe'll show each one on the same real example: a Counterweight Hook (CWH-A36-15) that\nAcme makes for Radiant Aerospace."],[490,"Carbon in 15 minutes"],[1361,"Carbon is \"an ERP + MES + QMS.\" Each acronym covers one slice of running a shop. Carbon rolls\nall three into one system that shares one set of data."],[221,"Carbon is a manufacturing system built with modern web technologies. It consists of three main applications:"],[7,"Carbon is an open-source manufacturing platform for vertically integrated manufacturing. It provides a modern, minimal, starting-point for building end-to-end manufacturing systems."],[26,"Carbon is an open-source manufacturing platform for vertically integrated manufacturing. It provides a modern, minimal, starting-point for building end-to-end manufacturing systems."],[984,"Carbon is API-first — create a key and make your first call."],[66,"Carbon is designed to be hosted on Vercel. In order to host the ERP and MES apps, you will need to create a new Vercel project for each app with the following configurations and required environment variables:"],[477,"Carbon is made of Modules"],[1469,"Carbon is one connected system of record for the whole business. ERP runs the office,\nMES runs the floor, QMS keeps it good — three views into the same data, organized as\nModules. Information goes in once and follows the work from the first quote to the final\npayment."],[1441,"Carbon is organized into Modules — Sales, Purchasing, Items, Production, Inventory,\nQuality, Accounting, and more. Each Module is one job. You open a Module from the home\nscreen, where every Module shows up as a tile."],[1439,"Carbon is software for running a manufacturing business. It tracks your orders, parts,\nmaterials, and money in one place. Write something down once, and Carbon carries it\neverywhere. Nobody re-types anything."],[1381,"Carbon is split into Modules — Sales, Purchasing, Items, Production, Inventory, Quality,\nand more. Each Module is one area of your business. When you open Carbon you land on the\nhome screen, where every Module shows up as a tile."],[1380,"Carbon looks busy at first, but it's built from a few repeating pieces. Learn them once and\nevery screen feels familiar. This is the quick tour."],[625,"Carbon multiplies them into the extended price: 54,001 × $0.25 = $13,500.25."],[918,"Carbon posts an invoice. When Acme issues AR000025, a webhook fires and the sync wakes up."],[712,"Carbon records are linked. A part needs a unit of measure. Opening stock needs the part\nand a location. A sales order needs a customer and an item. So you load the bottom\nlayer first and build up."],[910,"Carbon ships real, open-source examples. They're the fastest way to go from \"I think this is\npossible\" to a working pattern."],[1465,"Carbon ships with a built-in MCP server — a safe doorway that lets an AI assistant\noperate Carbon for you (look things up, draft a quote, check a job) in plain language.\nThe demo data in this manual was pulled through it. See\nMCP & AI."],[1326,"Carbon shows both together as one method tree in the Items module."],[1008,"Carbon shows the full key value once. Copy it now and store it somewhere safe — a secrets\nmanager or password manager. Lose it and you just delete the key and make a new one."],[735,"Carbon stitches the two into the parent's method. From then on, any\njob for that part copies the recipe automatically."],[1540,"Carbon tracks the running pounds on hand and counts them down as you consume."],[872,"Carbon updates the status. A full payment flips it to Paid; a partial payment leaves a\nbalance. The cash entry posts to the books automatically."],[1466,"Carbon's code is open source — anyone can read it, run it, and extend it. You can\nself-host, audit how it works, and shape it to your shop. More in\nIntegrating with Carbon."],[1213,"Carbon's planning compares two things:"],[940,"Carbon's server exposes about 1,188 tools across 15 modules (Sales, Purchasing,\nItems, Production, Inventory, Quality, Accounting, and more). In short: almost anything you\ncan click in Carbon, an assistant can do through MCP."],[380,"Carbon's traceability system tracks the complete lineage of materials and products through the manufacturing process. The system is built around two core concepts:"],[902,"Check it's really from Carbon. Carbon signs each request. Verify the signature before you act.\nThen reply fast with a 2xx status and do the slow work after, so Carbon doesn't think delivery\nfailed and retry."],[1194,"Check material. Carbon flags shortages. For J000097, not all 20,000 LB of steel was on\nhand, so Acme raised PO000057 to Ryerson. Buying and making\ncan run in parallel."],[1666,"Check parts against the spec using calibrated gauges. The procedure says what to measure."],[1839,"Check the line's fulfillment method. A job is only created for Make to Order lines. If\nthe line is Pull from Stock, Carbon reserves inventory instead — no job."],[1792,"Check the total. On Q000061 that's one line: 500 EA × $73.14 = $36,570.00."],[1884,"Check the totals. Goods are 500 × $73.14 = $36,570. The $250 shipping cost carries\nover, making the total $36,820. Payment terms (Net 30) come from the customer record."],[944,"Checks the inputs. If unsure, runs describe_tool to read which fields are required."],[1094,"Choose a shipping method"],[1877,"Choose a shipping method. Pick the carrier and service you quoted. For a heavy steel order,\nthat's usually a freight method like LTL (Less Than Truckload), not a parcel service."],[804,"Choose an employee type"],[1131,"Choose Post. A cascade fires:"],[1118,"Choose Post. At that instant:"],[1756,"Choose the default payment terms and currency. Radiant Aerospace is Net 30 in USD."],[1566,"Choose the method type"],[617,"Choose the supplier. Acme picks Ryerson. Carbon then fills in that supplier's\ncurrency (USD), payment terms (Net 30), and contact and address for you."],[557,"Choose the suppliers and send. Add the four suppliers as recipients. Carbon makes a supplier\nquote for each and sends it — by email or through the supplier portal."],[1405,"Click a Module tile (or its icon in the rail) and Carbon opens that area. Below, clicking\nItems opens the Items Module and its Parts list."],[1416,"Click a row to open that record."],[818,"Click Invite. Top-right of Settings → Users."],[1883,"Click Invoices → New. Carbon drafts invoice AR000025, pulling line 1 in at the shipped\nquantity (500) and the order price ($73.14)."],[1006,"Click New API Key and give it a clear name (like Nightly export). Naming by purpose makes\nit easy to revoke the right one later."],[988,"Click New API Key and name it"],[647,"Click Post. Carbon then:"],[771,"Click Save."],[1741,"Click Save. Carbon assigns a customer ID automatically (Radiant's internal ID is\ncust_LxoH7AbowNVjTwGSoqkW1Q). The customer now appears on the list, and you can add the rest\nanytime."],[1504,"Click Save. Carbon creates the item, marks it Active, and opens its detail page.\nThat's the whole foundation."],[1793,"Click Send. Carbon builds the PDF, emails it to Radiant's contact, and moves the status\nfrom Draft to Sent — the ball is now in the customer's court."],[1875,"Click Shipments → New. Carbon pre-fills the customer (Radiant Aerospace), the ship-to\naddress, and the open order lines."],[1424,"Click the Carbon logo (top-left) to return home."],[1180,"Click the Method tab to see the recipe Carbon copied onto the job. For the Counterweight\nHook it's short: one material, three operations."],[71,"Client Reference"],[82,"Client Reference"],[91,"Client Reference"],[283,"Client-Side Permission Checks"],[303,"Client-side permission checks - a helper function that checks the user's permissions before making a call to the server."],[1254,"Clock OFF and complete"],[1252,"Clock ON"],[1665,"Clock onto the inspection operation. In the shop floor app, the inspector opens the job, taps the Inspection operation, and clocks on — like any other step."],[1682,"Close it. Once every action is done — and MRB has signed off if the workflow needs it — close the NCR. It stays linked to the job and part forever."],[73,"Code Examples"],[93,"Code Examples"],[100,"Coding Conventions"],[558,"Collect the replies. Prices land back on each supplier quote. The list shows which are still\noutstanding."],[105,"Common Component Patterns"],[1807,"Common gotchas"],[214,"Common Patterns"],[377,"Common Queries"],[1098,"Common questions"],[157,"Common Variations"],[370,"Common Workflows"],[751,"Company profile, locations, units of measure and number sequences."],[176,"CompanyId is often part of the primary key for tenant isolation"],[141,"companyId Pattern"],[559,"Compare side by side. Open the comparison view. Carbon lines the suppliers up so the\ncheapest price and best lead time jump out. The lowest number isn't always the right one — a\nslightly higher price that arrives sooner can win when a job is waiting."],[1240,"Completion is real. J000097 shows 500 of 500 because operators clocked off all 500 pieces."],[103,"Component Patterns"],[104,"Component Structure"],[121,"Components are exported from index.ts files for cleaner imports"],[119,"Components are typically functional components using TypeScript"],[249,"components/ - React components"],[161,"Composite Indexes"],[54,"Configure the following environment variables:"],[61,"Configure the following environment variables:"],[974,"Confirm it. The assistant should now list Carbon's three meta-tools —\nsearch_tools, describe_tool, call_tool. That's exactly right; the full catalog stays\nhidden behind them."],[1087,"Confirm what actually arrived"],[601,"Confirm what arrived"],[932,"Connect an assistant"],[916,"Connect once. In Settings → Integrations, authorize Carbon to talk to your QuickBooks\ncompany. The link persists; you don't log in every time."],[127,"Consistent use of the Carbon design system"],[436,"Constructs nodes and links from entities and activities"],[1747,"Contacts follow the paperwork. The contact you pick on an order flows straight onto its invoice —\non Radiant's order SO000069, the same contact appeared on invoice AR000025."],[421,"Contain attributes specific to the entity"],[259,"Contains .models.ts, .service.ts, and UI components"],[372,"Conversion Pattern"],[560,"Convert the winner to a PO. Pick the quote and convert it to a\npurchase order in one click. Supplier, item, price, and\nquantity carry over, and the PO stays linked to the quote. That's exactly how Acme's\nPO000057 to Ryerson came to be: A36 plate at $0.25/LB."],[1773,"Convert to an order"],[1820,"Convert to Order. Click Convert to Order in the top-right. Carbon creates SO000069\nand copies every line, including the Make to Order method on the hook line."],[1224,"Convert what you accept. Buy suggestions become draft purchase orders; Make suggestions become jobs. Carbon links each one back to the demand that created it."],[1797,"Converting marks the quote Ordered (so you can always see what you offered) instead of\ndeleting it. A quote the customer passes on can be marked Lost instead — which keeps your\nwin/loss history honest."],[989,"Copy the secret right away"],[1297,"Core concepts"],[361,"Core Tables"],[1677,"Corrective vs preventive. A corrective action fixes the parts in front of you. A preventive action changes the process so it can't happen again. Heavier workflows make you do both — and Carbon won't let you close the NCR until every required action is checked off."],[1706,"Create a customer"],[1520,"Create a material"],[30,"Create a new API Key"],[60,"Create a Novu account"],[1474,"Create a Part"],[53,"Create a Resend account"],[1802,"Create a sales order"],[659,"Create a supplier"],[456,"Create a trackedActivity record describing the transformation"],[1703,"Create customers, contacts, locations and payment terms."],[425,"Create parent-child relationships in the lineage"],[1140,"Create production jobs from a sales order or from scratch."],[590,"Create the purchase order"],[556,"Create the RFQ and add what you want priced. In the Purchasing module, create a new RFQ\nand add a line per item — here, one line for A36 Steel Plate 1″ (A36-STEEL-PLT-1\".96x240)."],[457,"Create trackedActivityInput records for consumed entities"],[458,"Create trackedActivityOutput records for produced items"],[447,"Creates output entities via trackedActivityOutput"],[445,"Creates trackedActivity"],[441,"Creates trackedEntity for received materials"],[21,"Creating a Carbon Client with Supabase"],[20,"Creating an API Key"],[371,"Creating Tracked Entities"],[299,"Currently, all customers and suppliers have hard-coded permissions, which are set when the customer account or supplier account is created."],[401,"Custom properties"],[291,"customer"],[1722,"Customer-specific part numbers"],[725,"Customer/supplier types and payment terms are short lookup lists. If your CSV uses\none Carbon doesn't have yet, create it once under Settings first. More in\nCustomers and Suppliers."],[1702,"Customers"],[1726,"Customers live in the Sales module. Open Sales from the home screen, then click\nCustomers in the sub-nav across the top."],[1518,"Cut-to-size stock and stock on hand"],[130,"Dark mode support via theme system"],[239,"database - Database types and migrations"],[217,"Database Access"],[114,"Database Conventions"],[134,"Database Migrations"],[281,"Database Row-Level Security"],[301,"Database row-level security (RLS) - an in-database policy, written in SQL, that limits the data that a user can see or modify."],[230,"Database: Supabase (PostgreSQL) at /packages/database/supabase/"],[1035,"Dates are ISO 8601 strings (2026-06-11). Money comes back as plain numbers in the base\ncurrency (USD for Acme) — 36820 is $36,820.00. Format it for display on your side."],[922,"Decide who owns each piece of data before you connect anything. At Acme, Carbon is the source of\ntruth for invoices and QuickBooks just receives them. Two systems editing the same field is the\nfastest way to a reconciliation headache. Pick one owner per field and let the sync flow one way."],[320,"Decision-making is guided by four principles:"],[168,"Default Values"],[1603,"Define a sub-assembly's method once on its own item, then drop it into as many parent BOMs as you like. Update it in one place and every parent picks up the change on its next job."],[1394,"Define the parts and materials you make and buy"],[1470,"Defining an item"],[274,"deleteCustomerPortal() - Delete customer portal link"],[1214,"Demand — what's needed: open sales orders, materials jobs will consume, safety stock."],[576,"Demand comes from two places:"],[1640,"Demand-Based Reorder — Carbon adds up demand over a window (Acme uses 4 weeks) and\nsuggests enough to cover it."],[1680,"Describe and quantify. Write what you saw, attach a photo, and record the non-conforming quantity with a scrap reason if you're scrapping."],[1497,"Description — Counterweight Hook"],[1377,"Detail view"],[331,"Detailed documentation"],[1531,"Dimensions — the physical size: plate thickness, sheet size, bar diameter."],[15,"Discord: Join our community at discord.gg/spZ7MnqFT4 for support and discussions"],[798,"Do this before you import. Migrating data\nattaches parts, customers and suppliers to the company, locations and units you defined here.\nFoundation first, then data."],[240,"documents - PDF/Email/ZPL document generation"],[773,"Don't change your base currency after you start transacting — it isn't a supported flow.\nIf you picked wrong, start a fresh company instead."],[696,"Don't create a duplicate (a separate \"Ryerson Inc.\" next to \"Ryerson\"). Duplicates split\nyour spending across two records and make reports wrong. Search the list first and reuse\nthe vendor if it exists."],[1765,"Don't create the same company twice — duplicates split a customer's history across two records.\nSearch the list first; if they're already there (even as a Lead), edit that record instead."],[1025,"Don't hard-code the secret. Set it once so your code reads it at runtime:"],[486,"Don't memorize this. You'll learn each Module as you need it. The rest of this manual\nwalks through them one at a time, in the order you'd actually use them."],[1510,"Don't perfect every field up front. Number, description, UoM, type, tracking and Make/Buy is\nenough to start. Refine costs, suppliers and the method as you go."],[1684,"Don't reach for 8D on every scratch. Over-classifying buries your team and hides what truly matters. Most shop-floor defects are a 5 Why 2 How; save 8D for problems that reached the customer or carry safety risk."],[527,"Drop-ship"],[570,"Drop-ship skips your inventory on purpose. The part never appears in your\non-hand stock — by design. If you want the goods\nfirst (to inspect or kit), buy it normally and ship it yourself."],[1176,"Due date — when they must be done. The deadline type (Hard Deadline here) tells\nCarbon how firm that date is."],[1242,"Due dates flag risk. J000095 is due 2026-04-23 — already past — and still running. That's your cue to investigate."],[1544,"During the job, when plate is issued to job J000097, Carbon records which batch was used."],[248,"Each app follows a consistent structure:"],[1289,"Each clock-on/clock-off pair is a production event — a timestamped record of who worked which operation, how long, and how many good and scrap pieces resulted. These events do three jobs at once."],[510,"Each hook needs 40 lb of steel, so 500 hooks need 20,000 lb. Carbon already knows that —\nwatch what it does next."],[711,"Each importer lives in the module that owns the data — Items, Sales, Purchasing,\nInventory. You open that module, click Import, and upload a CSV. Imported parts land in\nthe Items module, on the Parts list."],[404,"Each inventory transaction can be linked to a specific tracked entity"],[796,"Each layer builds on the one before it:"],[1117,"Each line needs a location and shelf (bin). Acme's steel lives at Headquarters in bin R02-B01-01 — its default — so the receipt suggests it for you. Change it if you're stocking it elsewhere."],[1112,"Each line pre-fills with the quantity still outstanding. Edit the received quantity to match the packing slip:"],[273,"Each module defines a set of methods for interacting with the module. The convention is to have at least four methods for each table."],[258,"Each module has its own folder in /modules/"],[1863,"Each order line is set to Make to Order or Pull from Inventory."],[727,"Each row becomes an inventory adjustment that sets the item's on-hand quantity."],[785,"Each sequence has three parts you can tune:"],[1508,"Each type is its own list under Items, but they all create the same way. Here's one of\neach kind Acme keeps."],[289,"Each user has a role, which may be one of the following:"],[336,"Easy to add API endpoints"],[335,"Easy to add custom applications"],[337,"Easy to add custom database tables"],[338,"Easy to add modules and interfaces to the primary application"],[231,"Edge Functions: at /packages/functions/database/supabase/functions/"],[422,"Edges: TrackedActivity records with Input/Output relationships"],[1608,"Editing the master method only affects future jobs. To change a job that's already running, edit it on that job's method — not the part. This is why job J000097 built 500 hooks against the method exactly as it stood the day it was released."],[39,"Email Service (Resend)"],[290,"employee"],[473,"Enables scanning for instant traceability lookup"],[1585,"Enter 40 in LB (pounds) — the amount one hook uses. Don't multiply by your batch size."],[1347,"Enter information once, and it follows the work everywhere. Every page from here is just a\ncloser look at one of these records."],[1716,"Enter the address and role"],[1476,"Enter the basics"],[1708,"Enter the basics"],[602,"Enter the batch (lot) number"],[1071,"Enter the corrected quantity, not the difference. If Carbon says 17,507 LB but you\ncounted 17,450, type the new on-hand — Carbon works out the −57 LB. If the item is\nbatch-tracked, pick which batch."],[1078,"Enter the counted quantities. Carbon compares each to the expected on-hand and flags any\nvariance."],[679,"Enter the Name, pick a Type, and confirm the Currency (Carbon defaults to your\nbase currency — USD for Acme). Then click Save."],[1782,"Enter the quantity. Type 500. Want to show a price ladder? Add more quantities to the\nsame line (say 100, 500, 1,000) and Carbon prices each one."],[642,"Enter the received quantity per line. If they shipped everything, accept the suggested\namount; if part, enter the smaller number and Carbon keeps the rest open. Pick the shelf /\nbin — Acme's A36 plate goes to R02-B01-01 at Headquarters."],[866,"Enter the supplier's bill number. Type their invoice reference and date — what you'll quote\nif you call them about it."],[1569,"Enter the times"],[1712,"Enter their details"],[819,"Enter their email and pick a type. Add one or more addresses (separate with commas to\ninvite several at once). Choose the employee type they should get — you can change it later."],[768,"Enter your name and address. Acme is \"Acme Inc.\" at 2400 Anvil Way, Springfield, OH."],[154,"Enums"],[1430,"ERP — the office"],[222,"ERP (Enterprise Resource Planning) - Located at /apps/erp/"],[374,"ERP Inventory Service"],[1444,"ERP means Enterprise Resource Planning. In plain words, it's the office side. The\nModules here let you:"],[1429,"ERP, MES and QMS — three jobs, one system"],[1427,"ERP, MES and QMS in one system of record — and who uses each part."],[784,"Every document gets a short, readable ID — Q000061, SO000069, J000097, PO000057,\nAR000025. You don't type these; Carbon builds each one from a number sequence: a prefix\nplus a running counter."],[740,"Every importer follows the same five steps, so once you've done one, you've done them all."],[1617,"Every item has to come from somewhere. You either make it\nor buy it. Replenishment is how you tell Carbon which one — and the few numbers that\nlet Carbon top up your stock before you run out."],[1317,"Every item is Make or Buy — that one setting decides how you get more of it:"],[333,"Every manufacturer has unique needs that are not covered by the standard platform. We want to make it easy to extend the platform to meet their needs."],[1527,"Every material is described by four attributes. Acme packs all four into a readable ID so the\ncatalog reads at a glance."],[1227,"Every operation in a job points at a work center — a machine or station like the DMU 50 or a Burn Table. Each operation carries a time, and operations run After Previous (step 20 waits for step 10). That's how Carbon builds a schedule."],[1461,"Every page in this manual uses one real demo company so the examples stay concrete.\nAcme Inc. is a metal-fabrication shop in Springfield, OH. It cuts, machines, and\nfinishes steel and aluminum parts for aerospace, defense, energy, mining, and construction."],[509,"Every part you make has a Method — a recipe with two halves: the Bill of Material (what\nit's made of) and the routing (the steps to make it). Open the part in the Items module\nto see it."],[875,"Every posted invoice and payment writes entries to the chart of accounts — the numbered\nbuckets the business tracks money in (cash, receivables, payables, sales, cost of goods). Acme's\nchart has 93 accounts, and you never post to them by hand."],[923,"Every real integration is the same four pieces, and each one is just a normal API call or HTTP\nrequest — nothing magic:"],[1065,"Every row names the document that caused it, so the ledger doubles as an audit trail: who\nmoved this, when, and why."],[1813,"Every sales order has two parts:"],[487,"Every screenshot in this manual comes from Acme Inc., a real demo company that makes\nprecision metal parts for aerospace and defense customers. So what you see here is exactly\nwhat you'll see in the app."],[1363,"Every term in the manual, alphabetical, with real Acme examples woven in."],[538,"Everything here lives in the Purchasing module. Open it from the home screen, then use the\nsub-nav for Purchase Orders, Supplier Quotes, and Planning."],[762,"Everything here lives in the Settings module. Open it from the gear icon at the\nbottom-left of the navigation rail."],[1463,"Everything lives together, so there's no re-keying and nothing drifts out of sync.\nA quote becomes a sales order becomes a job becomes a shipment becomes an invoice — each\ninheriting from the last. The walkthrough follows that chain for\nAcme's hook, from price request to paid invoice."],[1846,"Everything runs from the order"],[143,"Evolution of RLS Policies"],[1113,"Exact — all 54,001 LB came. Leave it as-is."],[461,"Example from revision-system.md:"],[888,"Example integrations: clone and adapt"],[118,"Example:"],[555,"Example: Acme needs a big lot of 1″ A36 steel plate. The RFQ goes to four suppliers at once —\nRyerson, Olympic Steel, Reliance Steel, and MetalMart."],[260,"Examples: sales, purchasing, inventory, accounting, etc."],[399,"Expiration dates"],[317,"Extensibility"],[322,"Extensibility"],[269,"External/shared routes under share+/ prefix"],[995,"Fetch one sales order"],[215,"File Organization"],[268,"File serving routes under file+/ prefix"],[1744,"Fill in name, email, phone, and (optionally) job title. Email matters most — it's what Carbon\nuses to send quotes and orders."],[661,"Fill in the core details"],[1494,"Fill in the four fields every item needs. Acme enters:"],[1824,"Fill in the header. Set the order date, the ship-from location, and the\ncustomer's PO reference. Save to get an order number."],[516,"Finally you bill the order. The sales invoice (AR000025) pulls its lines from what\nshipped — no re-typing — and once Radiant pays, it's marked Paid."],[310,"Finally, we can use client-side permission checks to limit what the user can do in the UI. This is done using the usePermissions hook. It provides two methods:"],[153,"Financial Columns"],[1229,"Find the bottleneck. The dashboard's Work Center Utilization shows load per machine. Acme has three Burn Tables but only one Sand Blasting Room — so sandblasting is the constraint."],[480,"Find your topic"],[943,"Finds the tool. Runs search_tools({ query: \"inventory quantity\" }) and gets back\ncandidates like inventory_getItemQuantities."],[1045,"Fix a count: inventory adjustment"],[1843,"Follow an order all the way to a shipped, invoiced job."],[491,"Follow one real order from quote to cash — and see how Carbon's modules connect."],[428,"Follows: Entity → Activity Input → Activity → Activity Output → Descendant Entity"],[432,"Follows: Entity → Activity Output → Activity → Activity Input → Ancestor Entity"],[1785,"For a Make to Order part, Carbon already knows the recipe — what it's made of and how it's\nmade. So it rolls up a real cost instead of asking you to guess."],[1449,"For Acme, ERP took Radiant Aerospace's order for 500 Counterweight Hooks (sales order\nSO000069, $36,820) and bought the steel from Ryerson (purchase order PO000057)."],[1451,"For Acme's hook, the floor ran three steps in order — Flame Cut, Sandblasting, then\nInspection — all on job J000097."],[1542,"For materials, where the metal came from can matter as much as how much you have. A\nbatch (also lot, or heat for steel) is stock that arrived together in one shipment.\nAcme's A36 plate has batch tracking on, so:"],[45,"For now, please include the required environment variables found in env.ts, and setup the following infrastructure:"],[1336,"For our order, Carbon made job J000097 for 500 hooks. The shop floor reports progress\nthrough its operations: Draft → Ready → In Progress → Completed."],[1635,"For pure make-to-order parts, planning is simple: an order arrives, a job runs. The numbers\nbelow matter most for items you stock — bulk raw materials and make-to-stock parts."],[1108,"For the hero thread, Acme ordered 54,001 LB of A36 Steel Plate from Ryerson on PO000057."],[175,"Foreign key to company table with CASCADE delete: FOREIGN KEY (\"companyId\") REFERENCES \"company\"(\"id\") ON DELETE CASCADE"],[1545,"Forever after, each finished hook links back to that exact heat of steel — so if Ryerson\nreports a problem, Acme can answer \"which orders shipped that steel?\" in seconds."],[241,"form - Form components and validation"],[1529,"Form — the shape it arrives in. Carbon has 21 built-in: Plate, Billet, Flat Bar, Round\nBar, Hex Bar, Sheet, Tube, Angle, Channel and more."],[107,"Form Handling"],[236,"Formatting: Prettier"],[228,"Forms: Custom form library at /packages/form/"],[1699,"Forward (provenance): \"Radiant wants the material certs.\" Walk back from the shipment through the job to the exact heat of A36 steel and the Ryerson PO."],[225,"Framework: Remix (React-based)"],[1270,"Fred runs the Flame Cut on J000097: 500 hooks, on Burn Table - PA2."],[1842,"From sales order to shipment"],[691,"From the item → the item's Suppliers tab — good for \"who can sell me this?\""],[690,"From the supplier → the Supplier Parts tab — good for loading a vendor's catalog."],[210,"Frontend"],[9,"Full-stack type safety: Backend and frontend code are co-located for type-safe simplicity"],[133,"Functions are named in the snake_case format (e.g. get_customers, create_sales_order, update_item)"],[1656,"Gauges and calibration: trust your measurements"],[566,"Generate the linked PO. Carbon creates a PO to your supplier with the ship-to set to\nyour customer's address, not your warehouse. Confirm supplier, price, and quantity."],[582,"Generate the POs. Select the lines and let Carbon create the POs. It groups them by supplier,\nso one click can make several tidy orders — all the Ryerson items on one PO."],[167,"Generated Columns"],[615,"Get a price first. Not sure what something costs? Send a supplier quote (RFQ): you\nask one or more suppliers for a price, then turn the best reply into a PO without re-typing.\nCarbon also remembers a supplier's last price and pre-fills it — Acme's A36 plate runs\n$0.25/LB at Ryerson."],[431,"Get Ancestors (Backward Tracing):"],[427,"Get Descendants (Forward Tracing):"],[5,"Get Started"],[18,"Get started with Carbon in minutes"],[378,"Get Tracked Entities for an Item (All Revisions)"],[379,"Get Tracked Entities for Specific Revision"],[182,"get_companies_with_any_role() - Returns all companies user has access to"],[180,"get_companies_with_employee_permission(permission) - Returns companies where user has specific permission"],[181,"get_companies_with_employee_role() - Returns all companies where user is an employee"],[183,"get_company_id_from_foreign_key(id, table) - Gets companyId through foreign key relationship"],[276,"getCustomerPortal() - Get specific customer portal"],[275,"getCustomerPortals() - List customer portal links"],[463,"getTrackedEntities() - Get entities for an item"],[467,"getTrackedEntitiesByMakeMethodId() - Get available entities for production"],[464,"getTrackedEntitiesByMakeMethodId() - Get entities produced by a make method"],[465,"getTrackedEntitiesByOperationId() - Get entities produced by an operation"],[468,"getTrackedEntity() - Get specific entity details"],[469,"getTrackedInputs() - Get consumed inputs for an activity"],[16,"GitHub: Check out our source code and contribute at github.com/crbnos/carbon"],[900,"Give Carbon a URL. Your endpoint is a small web service that accepts an HTTP POST. Carbon\nsends a short JSON body saying what happened and which record it was."],[1740,"Give the customer a name, then set the optional type, status, and currency."],[832,"Give the least access that does the job. Don't make everyone an Administrator. Start\nnarrow, add a permission when someone hits a wall. Hand out Delete rarely — Carbon\nprefers to cancel or deactivate records, not erase the history other records depend on."],[1348,"Glossary"],[500,"Go deeper"],[1109,"Go to Inventory → Receipts → New and pick PO000057 (or open the PO and choose Receive). Carbon copies the open lines onto a fresh Draft receipt."],[1123,"Go to Inventory → Shipments → New and pick SO000069 (or open the order and choose Ship). Carbon brings the order lines across as a Draft."],[1005,"Go to Settings → API Keys. This page lists every key, who made it, and when it was last used."],[1284,"Good — pieces that passed and move to the next operation."],[965,"Good prompts are specific. \"Release the stuck orders\" works; \"Release sales orders in\nNeeds Approval with an order date 3+ days ago, and show me the list first\" gives the\nassistant a clean target and you a checkpoint."],[996,"Good to know"],[1100,"Goods cross your dock two ways:"],[1530,"Grade — the temper or spec, like T6 on aluminum or 304 vs 316 on stainless."],[365,"Graph Construction"],[366,"Graph Structure"],[367,"Graph Traversal"],[369,"Graph Visualization"],[342,"Greater flexibility"],[420,"Have a status ('Available', 'Reserved', 'On Hold', 'Consumed')"],[612,"Header (Details tab) — the supplier, dates, deliver-to location, currency, and payment\nterms. One supplier per PO."],[775,"Headquarters is Acme's home base. It runs the Counterweight Hook thread you'll follow\nin this manual (SO000069,\nJ000097, PO000057)."],[146,"Helper Functions for RLS"],[545,"Here an aluminum bracket is milled in-house, anodized at Allen's Anodizing, then inspected.\nOperation 20 has no work center and no labor minutes — it points at a supplier and carries a price."],[307,"Here is an example of how to use it in a loader:"],[305,"Here is an example of how to use RLS policies to limit a user's rights to modify a table using the get_my_claim function. This is SQL that's run against the database to create a security policy for the customer table. If you're not familiar with the ::bolean and ::jsonb syntax, that's just casting the value to a boolean or jsonb type. The get_my_claim function is a custom function that returns the value of a claim from the user's permissions record. The auth.uid() function returns the user's ID."],[358,"Here is the basic pattern for listening to updates to a table in the <RealtimeDataProvider> component and updating the store:"],[1217,"Here's a real example. Sales order SO000069 needs 500 Counterweight Hooks. Each hook uses 40 LB of A36 steel plate, so that's 20,000 LB of steel. Acme doesn't have that on the shelf, so Carbon suggests buying it — which became PO000057 to Ryerson. The hook itself is a Make part, so the order became job J000097."],[1534,"Here's a slice of Acme's 19-material catalog. The same substance shows up in several sizes —\neach is its own item, because each is a different piece of stock to buy, store and cut."],[313,"Here's an example of how we might use client-side permission checks to hide the NewSalesForm component if the user does not have the sales_create permission:"],[1549,"Here's how Acme added the 1-inch A36 plate. Same steps for steel, stainless, aluminum or brass."],[830,"Here's how Acme's common types map across the modules — full access, read-only (View), or none."],[693,"Here's Ryerson once it's fully set up — the record the rest of buying leans on."],[1816,"Here's SO000069 open. The line CWH-A36-15 is 500 EA at $73.14. The tabs along the\ntop — Shipments and Invoices — show what went out and what was billed."],[979,"Here's the full round-trip behind the on-hand-steel question. You'd only type the first line."],[1367,"Here's the hero order one more time — as a glossary in motion. Every row is one of the terms\nabove, filled with real Acme data."],[504,"Here's the whole journey. Each step happens in a different Module, and Carbon links them all\ntogether automatically:"],[484,"Here's what each Module is for:"],[1061,"Here's what each number means:"],[250,"hooks/ - Custom React hooks"],[1143,"How a job gets created"],[1613,"How a line gets filled"],[571,"How do suppliers actually reply to an RFQ or confirm a PO? Carbon gives each supplier a\nportal — a secure web link where they respond online, with no Carbon login of their own."],[575,"How do you know what to buy in the first place? Purchasing planning watches your demand\nand your stock, works out where you'll run short, and hands you a list of buy suggestions\nyou can turn into POs."],[707,"How every importer works"],[1159,"How is it made? The method — its materials and steps."],[1664,"How it runs on the shop floor:"],[1157,"How many? The production quantity — 500 EA."],[1246,"How operators run jobs: clock in, record quantities and complete operations."],[931,"How the assistant reaches Carbon"],[1353,"How the big terms connect"],[890,"How the pieces fit"],[409,"id - Unique identifier"],[389,"id - Unique identifier (xid)"],[139,"id() Function"],[204,"IDs: DEFAULT id()"],[1364,"If a few terms still feel abstract, here's the chain they form in real life. Each box is a record\nin Carbon, and each one links to the next automatically — the same thread the\nwalkthrough follows."],[1003,"If it's in the app, it's in the API. Carbon's UI is built on top of the public API, so\nevery feature is callable from your code the day it ships. That's the one thing to remember."],[1343,"If Ryerson later reports a bad heat of steel, Acme can name the affected parts and customer in\nseconds — no blanket recall."],[1130,"If the carrier gives you a tracking number, add it here with package counts and weights. It travels with the record so anyone can answer \"where is it?\" later."],[1634,"If the shelf is short when Carbon goes to pull, that shortage becomes new demand. Because\nsteel is a Buy item, that turns into a suggested purchase order — exactly how\nPO000057 to Ryerson came to exist."],[863,"If they agree, approve with confidence. If not — they billed for 100 but you got 90 — Carbon\nshows the gap before you pay."],[51,"If you need help self-hosting Carbon in a GovCloud environment, please contact us."],[905,"If you're running a script every five minutes to ask \"anything new?\", use a webhook instead.\nPolling wastes calls and adds delay; webhooks fire the instant the thing happens."],[102,"Import Conventions"],[700,"Import in this order"],[729,"Import opening inventory once, ideally on go-live day. If you import balances and keep\ntransacting in the old system, the two drift apart fast. Freeze, count, import, run forward."],[745,"Import. When the preview is clean, confirm. Carbon creates the records and shows a\nsummary. Spot-check a few, then move to the next file."],[270,"In /apps/erp/app/utils/path.ts:"],[1663,"In Carbon an inspection isn't a separate thing to set up — it's just an operation in a routing, run at an inspection work center. The hero Counterweight Hook shows it: its method ends with an Inspection operation, so no part ships before it's checked."],[564,"In Carbon it's a flag that links a sales order and a purchase order. Acme's hero order\nSO000069 is normal — its dropShipment flag is false (Acme makes those hooks itself). A\ndrop-ship order sets that flag to true."],[541,"In Carbon, it's just an operation in a part's routing — like\nFlame Cut or Inspection. The only difference: its type is Outside, not Inside."],[1101,"In from a supplier — that's a receipt. It closes a purchase order line."],[678,"In Purchasing → Suppliers, click New. Carbon opens a short form. The only required\nfield is the Name."],[1583,"In the Items module, open the Counterweight Hook (CWH-A36-15) and click the Manufacturing tab."],[1493,"In the left rail, open the Items module and choose Parts. Click the green\nAdd Part button, top-right."],[616,"In the Purchasing module, open Purchase Orders and click New Purchase Order.\nCarbon assigns the next number (Acme's was PO000057) and opens it in Draft — nothing is\ncommitted yet, so you can edit or delete freely."],[308,"In this example, the user must have the sales_view permission and the employee role in order to access the loader. If the user does not have the required permissions, an Access denied error will be thrown, and the user will be redirected to the root page."],[1000,"In three steps, you'll create a key, install a client, and read 