screen, and the dashboard shows\nyour live shop at a glance — Active Jobs, work center use, and more. Click View Active\nJobs to see the full list."],[577,"Jobs. When you release a job, its\nmethod lists the materials it needs. Not enough on hand = a shortage."],[1374,"Jump anywhere with search"],[1310,"Just read along. You don't need to do anything in the app yet. This is the mental-model\npage. Want to see it all move at once? Try the 15-minute walkthrough."],[880,"Keep it. Carbon can sync the invoices and payments it generates out to QuickBooks so\nyour accountant stays in the tool they know. Carbon owns operations (what shipped, what was\nreceived); QuickBooks owns the financials."],[722,"Keep readableId values consistent. Acme uses [abbrev]-[material]-[rev] for parts\n(CWH-A36-15) and a longer pattern for materials (A36-STEEL-PLT-1\".96x240). A predictable\nscheme makes parts findable and the BOM import in Step 5 far easier."],[562,"Keep the prices for next time. A supplier quote can feed a supplier's price list for\nthat item, so next time Carbon already knows the price — no RFQ needed unless you want to re-shop it."],[388,"Key Fields:"],[408,"Key Fields:"],[373,"Key Service Functions"],[242,"kv - Key-value store (Redis)"],[1187,"Labor time is per piece. As operators report finished pieces in the\nshop-floor app, the Complete and Status columns\nfill in — that's how all three reached Done."],[738,"Last, bring in work still in flight: open quotes, sales orders awaiting fulfillment,\nand purchase orders awaiting receipt. By now everything they point at already exists."],[1730,"Lead — a prospect you're quoting, no order yet."],[346,"Learn about syncing data in realtime in Carbon"],[34,"Learn about the Carbon project structure and technology stack"],[35,"Learn about the code conventions used in the Carbon project"],[279,"Learn about the permissions system in Carbon"],[360,"Learn about the traceability system in Carbon"],[36,"Learn how to self-host Carbon"],[33,"Learn how to use the TypeScript client to call the Carbon API"],[925,"Let AI assistants work in Carbon through the Model Context Protocol."],[537,"Let Carbon tell you what to buy (planning)."],[677,"Let's add Ryerson, Acme's steel mill."],[1492,"Let's create the Counterweight Hook the way Acme did. The flow is the same for any type — you\njust pick a different Type in step 2."],[68,"Lightweight C# client for implementing Carbon in your app"],[88,"Lightweight TypeScript client for implementing Carbon in your app"],[1866,"Line 1 on SO000069 is Make to Order. Confirming the order created job J000097 for 500\npieces, due 2026-06-26. The job links back to its order, customer, and quote — so the shop\nfloor knows why it's building these hooks."],[613,"Lines (Lines tab) — one row per thing you're buying: an\nitem, a quantity, a unit price, and a required date."],[1840,"Lines copied from a quote carry the quoted price. A line you add by hand uses the item's default\nsell price, which may differ. When in doubt, convert from the quote rather than re-keying."],[424,"Link consumed entities (inputs) to produced entities (outputs)"],[665,"Link supplier part numbers"],[446,"Links input materials via trackedActivityInput"],[442,"Links to receipt document"],[235,"Linting: ESLint with custom config"],[1032,"List endpoints return one page at a time. Pass limit (how many) and offset (how many to\nskip): limit: 50, offset: 50 gets the second page of fifty. A count tells you the total."],[1376,"List view"],[994,"List your items"],[347,"Listening for async events to complete"],[350,"Listening for async events to complete"],[109,"Loader Pattern"],[1179,"Location matters. A job runs at one\nlocation. J000097 runs at Headquarters, so it\nuses Headquarters work centers (like Burn Table — PA2) and pulls material from Headquarters\nstock."],[1041,"Locations"],[1037,"Locations & stock"],[1690,"Log each calibration. Carbon rolls the due date forward and flips the status back to In Calibration."],[243,"logger - Logging utilities"],[489,"Looking for developer docs (the API, self-hosting)? Use the Developer Docs toggle at\nthe top of the sidebar."],[1378,"Lost? Two quick resets"],[341,"Lower costs"],[454,"Maintains traceability across locations"],[1623,"Make — Carbon builds it on a job. It needs a\nmethod (a BOM + routing). The Counterweight Hook CWH-A36-15\nis Make."],[1318,"Make — you build it. It needs a method (below) and demand creates a Job."],[1625,"Make & Buy — both are allowed. You pick make-or-buy on each order line."],[23,"Make a request to the API"],[972,"Make credentials in Carbon. Open Settings → API keys and create a key (or set up\nOAuth). Copy it somewhere safe — you won't see it again."],[1612,"Make or buy"],[1629,"Make to Order — start a fresh job just for this order. Best for custom parts you don't stock."],[1864,"Make to Order — the part gets built. Confirming the order creates a job."],[1630,"Make to Stock — build a batch into inventory ahead of demand, then ship from the shelf."],[1219,"Make vs Buy is one setting on each item. The hook is Make; its steel is Buy. That flag decides whether a shortage becomes a job or a PO. See Replenishment."],[1201,"Managing production"],[1639,"Manual Reorder — no auto-suggestions; you create jobs and POs yourself."],[444,"Manufacturing (post-production/index.ts, MES operations)"],[1507,"Manufacturing and Purchasing are mirror images. A Make item fills in\nManufacturing and leaves Purchasing empty; a Buy item is the reverse. The A36 steel\nplate fills in Purchasing (Ryerson, $0.25/LB) and has no method."],[398,"Manufacturing dates"],[11,"Manufacturing-focused: Built for the complexity of complex assembly and make-to-order parts workflows across multiple locations"],[743,"Map columns. Point each of your columns at a Carbon field — your \"Part No.\" to\nreadableId, \"UoM\" to unitOfMeasureCode, \"Make/Buy\" to replenishmentSystem. If your\nheaders match the template, mapping auto-fills."],[682,"Mark one as the purchasing contact. That's who Carbon emails when you send a purchase\norder, so pick the person who takes orders. You can add as many contacts as you like."],[565,"Mark the sales order line as drop-ship. On the sales order,\nturn on drop-shipment for the line. Carbon now knows the part won't come from your inventory."],[865,"Match against the receipt. Confirm the billed quantities match what you received. Carbon\nflags any mismatch."],[917,"Match existing records. Both systems have customers and items, so the sync maps them: Carbon's\nRadiant Aerospace links to the matching QuickBooks customer. Getting this right stops the same\ncustomer appearing twice."],[1515,"Material vs. part"],[1512,"Materials"],[1523,"Materials live in the Items module, on the Materials tab next to Parts. Open Items\nfrom the home screen, then switch to Materials to see your raw stock."],[1147,"Materials: what the job consumes"],[1641,"Maximum Quantity — keep the shelf topped up toward a target level."],[450,"May create activities for shipped items"],[939,"MCP (Model Context Protocol) is a USB port for AI: any\nassistant that \"speaks MCP\" can plug into any system that exposes an MCP server — no custom\ncode in between."],[1435,"Meet Acme — our running example"],[1431,"MES — the shop floor"],[223,"MES (Manufacturing Execution System) - Located at /apps/mes/"],[1450,"MES means Manufacturing Execution System. It's what operators use on the floor. When\nthe office releases a job (an order to make a quantity of a part), it shows up for an\noperator. They open it, clock on to an operation, and record finished pieces."],[375,"MES Operations Service"],[1164,"Method = BOM + Routing. The bill of materials (BOM) is what the part is made of;\nthe routing is the ordered steps to make it. A job copies both. See\nMethods: BOM & routing."],[1577,"Methods live in the Items module, on each part's Manufacturing tab. Open the part, click Manufacturing, and you'll see the whole recipe as a tree: the part on top, its materials and operations nested underneath."],[1558,"Methods: BOM & routing"],[697,"Migrating your data"],[170,"Migrations are stored in /packages/database/supabase/migrations/, and are named with timestamps and descriptive names. Migrations are applied by the Supabase CLI, but it's useful to test them locally through the Studio."],[329,"Minimal dependencies"],[328,"Minimal languages and setup (npm, TypeScript and SQL)"],[348,"Minimizing the number of requests for popular data"],[351,"Minimizing the number of requests for popular data"],[1594,"Minutes/Piece scales with quantity; Total Minutes stays fixed."],[1387,"Module"],[216,"Module Organization"],[285,"Module permissions - These are permissions that are specific to a module. For example, a user may have permission to view the sales module, but not to create, update or delete sales."],[1383,"Module tiles on the home screen."],[1001,"Module: Settings. Create and manage keys under Settings → API Keys. A key is a secret\nthat lets your code log in as you."],[233,"Monorepo: NPM workspaces with Turbo"],[892,"Most ERP systems are a closed box. Carbon is the opposite: everything in the app runs on the\nsame public API you can use too. So you can connect Carbon to your\nother tools, or build the feature you wish existed."],[895,"Most integrations use the first two together: a webhook tells you something happened, then an\nAPI call gets the details."],[1536,"Most metal is bought in LB (pounds) — even when the part it feeds is counted in EA.\nCarbon mixes units happily: the Counterweight Hook consumes 40 LB of plate per 1 EA hook."],[1275,"Most operations have a procedure attached — Carbon's name for a standard work instruction. The operator ticks off each step as they go."],[1440,"Most shops glue this together from spreadsheets, an accounting program, paper travelers,\nand inspection forms. None of them talk to each other. Carbon replaces that pile with one\nsystem of record — one trusted place where the real state of the business lives."],[808,"Most shops have more than one person: sales, buying, floor operators, a bookkeeper. This\npage shows you how to invite them and control what each one can do."],[171,"Most tables follow this pattern:"],[685,"Most vendors have a single location, so Carbon fills it in automatically on every purchase\norder. You only choose when there's more than one."],[1083,"Move goods in and out with shipments and receipts."],[709,"Moving from spreadsheets or another system? You don't retype everything by hand. You import\nit with Carbon's built-in CSV importers. The one rule: import the things other records\ndepend on first."],[1055,"Moving stock between sites is a transfer, not an adjustment. Use a stock transfer so the\namount that leaves one site is exactly the amount that arrives at the other."],[737,"Multi-level assemblies import the same way — just make sure every sub-assembly exists as\nan item first, and import the deepest level's BOM before its parents."],[1571,"Multi-level methods (sub-assemblies)"],[149,"Multi-Permission Policies"],[31,"Navigate to API Docs to get your environment variables"],[29,"Navigate to Settings > API Keys"],[1369,"Navigating Carbon"],[13,"Need help or have questions? Connect with us:"],[793,"Net 30 is Acme's default and the term on the hero thread — on Radiant Aerospace's order\nSO000069, the Ryerson purchase order PO000057, and the invoice AR000025."],[1419,"New button (top-right) creates a record."],[897,"New here? Read Using the API first to make a key and your\nfirst call. Then come back to wire things together."],[145,"New Pattern (2025+)"],[1360,"New to Carbon? Start with What is Carbon? for the big\npicture, then follow one real order end to end in\nCarbon in 15 minutes. The example used below — the Counterweight Hook\nCWH-A36-15 that Acme makes for Radiant Aerospace — is that same order."],[478,"New to Carbon? Take the 15-minute tour first"],[788,"Next number — the counter, which ticks up by one each time a document is created."],[532,"Next steps"],[605,"Next steps"],[667,"Next steps"],[708,"Next steps"],[760,"Next steps"],[807,"Next steps"],[844,"Next steps"],[891,"Next steps"],[934,"Next steps"],[998,"Next steps"],[1047,"Next steps"],[1099,"Next steps"],[1151,"Next steps"],[1209,"Next steps"],[1257,"Next steps"],[1307,"Next steps"],[1355,"Next steps"],[1379,"Next steps"],[1438,"Next steps"],[1481,"Next steps"],[1521,"Next steps"],[1573,"Next steps"],[1616,"Next steps"],[1658,"Next steps"],[1724,"Next steps"],[1774,"Next steps"],[1808,"Next steps"],[1853,"Next steps"],[25,"Next Steps"],[574,"No account, no friction. The portal makes it easy for small shops — like an anodizer or\npainter — to reply fast. The faster they respond, the faster your RFQ comparison fills in."],[619,"No supplier record yet? Create it first — see Suppliers. A PO\nmust point at a real supplier."],[418,"Nodes: TrackedEntity records"],[1454,"Non-conformances (NCRs) — a record you raise when something is wrong, so it gets fixed."],[1654,"Non-conformances (NCRs): record what went wrong"],[1651,"Non-conformances, inspections, corrective actions and full traceability."],[563,"Normally goods you buy come to you — you receive them, then ship from your own dock.\nSometimes the supplier should ship straight to your customer instead. That's a\ndrop-shipment: you still buy it and still bill your customer, but the goods never touch your\nbuilding."],[1822,"Not every order comes from a quote — a repeat customer might just email a PO."],[244,"notifications - Notification services"],[50,"Novu (In-app notifications)"],[59,"Novu is used for in-app notifications and notification workflows throughout the application."],[62,"NOVU_APPLICATION_ID - Client-side public identifier (format: ********************)"],[63,"NOVU_SECRET_KEY - Server-side secret key, backend only (format: ********************)"],[1028,"Now grab a single record: SO000069, Radiant Aerospace's order for 500 Counterweight Hooks."],[694,"Now raising a purchase order is mostly point-and-click: pick Ryerson, pick the material, and\nCarbon already knows the contact, address, terms, and price."],[726,"Now record what's on your shelves today. Each row says: this item, this quantity, at this\nlocation (and which shelf, if you track bins)."],[961,"Now the assistant reads to find the stuck orders, then issues a WRITE call to release\neach one. Approve WRITE access first, and ask to see the list before it acts. More actions:"],[194,"NUMERIC or DECIMAL for monetary values"],[1017,"OAuth is for apps that act on behalf of other Carbon users — a product where its users\nconnect their Carbon account. Your app sends each user through a consent screen and gets a\nshort-lived token scoped to that user."],[144,"Old Pattern (Pre-2025)"],[1632,"On Acme's hook order, the line is Make to Order, so Carbon created job J000097. Inside\nthat job, the A36 steel is set to Pull from Inventory — Carbon draws it from the shelf\ninstead of buying fresh for the job."],[197,"ON DELETE CASCADE - For child records that should be deleted with parent"],[199,"ON DELETE RESTRICT - To prevent deletion if references exist"],[198,"ON DELETE SET NULL - For optional relationships"],[405,"On deletion: SET NULL, On update: CASCADE"],[966,"On every request the assistant signs in as a real Carbon user, and Carbon enforces that\nuser's permissions on every call."],[1732,"On Hold — paused, often for a payment issue."],[1286,"On J000097 every hook was good — 500 made, 0 scrapped. When scrap does happen, reasons roll up into reports, and repeated failures can feed the quality side of Carbon as a non-conformance (NCR)."],[1743,"On the customer record, click the Contacts tab, then New Contact."],[1751,"On the customer record, click the Locations tab, then New Location."],[1755,"On the customer record, click the Payment tab."],[1739,"On the Customers list, click New Customer (top right)."],[620,"On the Details tab, confirm the order date (2026-06-12) and pick the 