 This page shows how Carbon turns customer demand into a plan, tells you what to make and what to buy, and shows you whether the shop is on track."],[1888,"One line, one self-linking chain — nothing re-typed between steps:"],[1097,"One number, entered once"],[1815,"One or more lines — each line is one thing the customer is buying: an item, a quantity,\na unit price, a promised date, and a fulfillment method."],[517,"One part, one connected chain — each record a click away from the next:"],[1015,"One-off migration or reporting jobs."],[1738,"Only a name is required. Filling in the rest now saves re-keying later."],[1138,"Only when the item asks for one. The field shows up for batch- or serial-tracked items, like A36 Steel Plate. Plain Inventory items, like the finished Counterweight Hook, just track a quantity and skip the step."],[1373,"Open a Module"],[1621,"Open an item from the Items module and look at its Manufacturing view. The\nReplenishment field is the make-or-buy switch."],[1174,"Open J000097 and you land on its Details tab. A few fields do most of the work."],[641,"Open PO000057 and click Receive (or start from Inventory → Receipts and pick the PO).\nCarbon pre-loads the open lines with the outstanding quantity — here the full 54,001 LB."],[1220,"Open Production → Planning. You get one row per item that needs attention — what's required, what's available, the shortage, and the suggested action."],[987,"Open Settings → API Keys"],[767,"Open Settings → Company."],[1860,"Open SO000069 and you get a row of action buttons across the top — including Shipments and\nInvoices. You do not leave the order to ship or bill. You click these buttons, and Carbon\nfills in the rest from the order."],[1819,"Open the accepted quote. Go to Sales → Quotes and open it — for Acme that's\nQ000061. Confirm the line, quantity, and price."],[1711,"Open the Contacts tab"],[681,"Open the Contacts tab and click New. Add a name, email, and phone for the person you\ndeal with — usually a sales rep."],[660,"Open the form"],[1707,"Open the form"],[741,"Open the importer. Go to the module that owns the data — Items, Sales, Purchasing,\nInventory — and click Import. Download Carbon's template CSV and pour your data into\nits columns."],[1636,"Open the Inventory module to see the reorder policy and stock levels Carbon plans against,\nitem by item."],[870,"Open the invoice you're settling — say AR000025, or a supplier bill like AP000023."],[1069,"Open the item at the right location. Adjustments are per location — adjusting at\nHeadquarters never touches Texas."],[1170,"Open the Jobs list. In the Production module, click View Active Jobs (or open\nJobs). Click New Job."],[1715,"Open the Locations tab"],[683,"Open the Locations tab and click New to enter the ship-from or remit-to address. If\na vendor ships from several plants, add one location per site."],[1563,"Open the Manufacturing tab"],[1250,"Open the operation"],[508,"Open the order and you see the line: CWH-A36-15, 500 each at $73.14. Notice it's set to\nMake to Order — so Carbon knows it has to be built, and it already created a job for it."],[1475,"Open the Parts list"],[1719,"Open the Payment tab"],[686,"Open the Payment tab and pick a default term. Net 30 means the invoice is due 30 days\nafter it's issued. Setting a default here means every new order starts with the right terms."],[580,"Open the planning view. In the Purchasing module, open Planning. Carbon lists every\nitem about to run short, the quantity it suggests, and what's driving the need."],[1660,"Open the Quality module from the home screen. The dashboard shows your open work and a sub-nav for Issues, Gauges, Records, and Inspections."],[854,"Open the source. Go to Sales Invoices and click New, then pick the shipment (or\nsales order) to bill — here, the shipment behind SO000069. Carbon pulls in the lines\nautomatically."],[827,"Open the type. From Settings → Employee Types, click a type (say Sales) and open\nits Permissions tab. You'll see one row per module."],[2,"Open-source manufacturing platform for vertically integrated manufacturing"],[318,"Openness"],[323,"Openness"],[1146,"Operations: the steps, in order"],[1264,"Operators open the MES at its own address (think mes.carbon.ms) and sign in with their own account. A worker who only runs machines never has to learn the full ERP."],[1805,"Order statuses"],[1870,"Ordered — how many the customer asked for."],[1320,"Our hook CWH-A36-15 is a Make part. Its steel is a Buy material."],[1859,"Our line is Make to Order, so it gets built before it ships. Here is the whole chain:"],[1102,"Out to a customer — that's a shipment. It closes a sales order line."],[543,"Outside — runs at a supplier and costs you what the supplier charges."],[552,"Outside parts are still your inventory. While parts are at the anodizer, they're\nwork-in-progress that's temporarily off-site. Don't close the job until you've received them\nback, or your job costs and on-hand counts will be wrong."],[523,"Outside processing"],[521,"Outside processing, RFQs, drop-ship and the supplier portal."],[1115,"Over — Carbon flags the overage so you can accept it or send it back."],[206,"Overview"],[213,"Package Structure"],[787,"Padding — how many digits, zero-filled. Acme pads to six, so SO000069, not SO69."],[1496,"Part number — CWH-A36-15"],[1604,"Parts change, so methods aren't frozen. Carbon keeps history so today's edit doesn't rewrite what you already shipped."],[1471,"Parts, materials, tools and services — how to create and describe the things you make and buy."],[219,"Path Configuration"],[271,"path.to.externalQuote(id) generates /share/quote/${id}"],[874,"Payment terms drive the due date. Each invoice carries a payment term that Carbon uses to\nset when payment is due. Net 30 is Acme's default. Terms flow down from the customer or\nsupplier record onto every order and invoice, so you set them once."],[1754,"Payment terms say when a customer should pay — for example Net 30 means \"due 30 days\nafter the invoice date.\" Set them on the customer and every invoice inherits the right due date."],[792,"Payment terms say when an invoice is due — and sometimes offer a discount for paying\nearly. Attach a default to each customer and supplier. Carbon copies it onto their orders and\ninvoices and works out the due date. Acme keeps seven."],[811,"People and access live in the Users module, inside Settings. Go to Settings → Users\nin the left navigation. You'll see everyone in your company and the type assigned to each."],[1443,"People describe business software with three acronyms — ERP, MES, and QMS. Many shops buy\nthree separate programs. Carbon does all three — not bolted together, but as three views of\nthe same data."],[278,"Permissions"],[815,"Permissions are granted per module (Sales, Purchasing, Items, and so on), with four\nactions each: View, Create, Update, Delete."],[298,"Permissions are managed within the user module. An employee's permissions are set according to the default permissions for their employee type when the user is created. Each employee may then be fine-tuned for individual permissions in the users module. There is also an option to bulk update permissions for employees."],[968,"Permissions come from whoever owns the credentials. If that user can't delete sales\norders in the app, the assistant can't either. MCP is a new doorway into Carbon, not a way\naround its permission model."],[280,"Permissions in the Code"],[1804,"Pick a fulfillment method"],[1638,"Pick a reordering policy — when Carbon suggests a top-up:"],[1622,"Pick one of these on every item:"],[1551,"Pick substance, form and grade. Choose Steel and Plate (PLT), enter grade A36,\nand dimensions 1″ thick, 96 × 240 sheet. Carbon builds a readable ID like\nA36-STEEL-PLT-1\".96x240."],[899,"Pick the events you care about. For a shop like Acme: a quote sent, a sales order confirmed,\na job completed, a shipment shipped, an invoice paid. Subscribe only to what you'll act on."],[1093,"Pick the finished goods"],[1876,"Pick the finished goods. Enter how many of each line you're sending. All 500 hooks came in\nfrom job J000097, so enter 500 EA. Because A36 steel is batch-tracked, Carbon records which\nbatch ships — that's the traceability link."],[1171,"Pick the part. Choose a Make item like CWH-A36-15.\nCarbon pulls in its description and unit of measure (EA)."],[592,"Pick the supplier"],[1720,"Pick the terms"],[539,"Pick the tool you need today:"],[1679,"Pick the type and workflow. Choose the cause (e.g. Manufacturing Defect) and the right playbook (CAPA for a recurring defect, 8D if parts reached the customer)."],[1076,"Pick what to count. A rack, an item class, or your highest-value stock. Counting the\ncostliest items most often (an \"ABC\" approach) catches the errors that matter most."],[882,"Pick your books-of-record up front. Choose one financial source of truth — Carbon or\nQuickBooks — and set up the integration before posting real invoices. See Integrating with\nCarbon."],[718,"Pick your UoM and location codes now and never rename them. Every imported row points at\nthese codes by exact text — change EA to ea later and you orphan thousands of references."],[1124,"Picking is choosing which stock fills the shipment. Carbon pulls the hooks from the job's finished-goods bin (8-1-H). Confirm the quantity per line — here, all 500 EA. For batch/serial items, you pick the exact lots here, which closes the traceability loop."],[1349,"Plain-English definitions of every Carbon and manufacturing term in this manual."],[1396,"Plan and run jobs on the shop floor"],[1614,"Plan when to reorder"],[585,"Planning closes the loop. A job creates demand, planning surfaces the shortage, a PO fills\nit, the receipt restocks the shelf, and the job pulls what it needs. Run planning regularly and\nshortages stop sneaking up on you."],[547,"Point it at a supplier and a price. Pick the supplier — Allen's Anodizing — and enter\nwhat they charge. That price rolls up into the part's cost, just like in-house labor."],[1885,"Post and send it. Posting books the revenue and marks the line fully invoiced. Send it to\nRadiant; when they pay, mark it Paid — exactly how AR000025 ended, paid the same day."],[856,"Post it. Posting assigns the number (AR000025) and turns it into a live receivable — money\nthe customer now owes."],[867,"Post it. The invoice moves to Open, records the payable, and sets the due date from the\nsupplier's terms."],[603,"Post the receipt"],[1090,"Post the receipt"],[1096,"Post the shipment"],[1878,"Post the shipment. Posting removes the hooks from inventory and adds 500 to the line's\nshipped count. The shipment is saved and linked to the order."],[1079,"Post the variances. For each bin that differs, Carbon posts an adjustment so the ledger,\non-hand, and books all move together."],[1137,"Posting is a committed inventory transaction, so you don't just edit it after the fact. You reverse it with a correcting movement — a negative inventory adjustment, a return, or a credit — which keeps a clean audit trail. Fix it before you post whenever you can."],[650,"Posts the inventory value to your books at the purchase cost."],[786,"Prefix — the letters in front. AR is accounts receivable (money owed to you), AP\nis accounts payable (money you owe)."],[1423,"Press ⌘K to search from anywhere."],[1771,"Price the line"],[172,"Primary keys use TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT id('prefix') for globally unique IDs"],[314,"Principles"],[1177,"Priority — ranks this job against others for the same machines. J000097 is 1, the\nhighest, so it jumps the queue."],[1278,"Procedures are versioned. Operators always run the Active version; managers can revise a draft without disrupting the floor. Build them in the ERP's Production module."],[1395,"Production"],[1314,"Production — the jobs that actually build parts."],[1175,"Production quantity — how many good pieces to finish. Here, 500."],[319,"Productivity"],[324,"Productivity"],[472,"ProductLabelPDF uses generateQRCode(item.trackedEntityId, size)"],[208,"Project Structure"],[120,"Props are defined with TypeScript interfaces"],[265,"Protected routes under x+/ prefix"],[438,"Provides interactive visualization of material lineage"],[266,"Public routes under _public+/ prefix"],[1631,"Pull from Inventory — take what's already on the shelf. No new job or PO."],[1865,"Pull from Inventory — the part is already on a shelf, so you skip straight to shipping."],[1588,"Pull from Inventory vs. Make. Use Pull from Inventory for stocked materials like the steel plate. Use Make when the line is itself something you build — that makes it a sub-assembly (see below)."],[1077,"Pull the count sheet and walk the floor. A counter writes down what's actually in each\nbin — ideally without seeing the expected number, so the count stays honest."],[850,"Purchase invoice (AP) — records a bill a supplier sent you. AP means Accounts\nPayable: money you owe."],[840,"Purchase invoices — recording what you owe"],[868,"Purchase invoices add a couple of statuses the sales side doesn't have:"],[626,"Purchase Order · PO000057 — Lines. One line: 54,001 LB of A36 steel plate at $0.25/LB."],[587,"Purchase orders, receiving and supplier quotes."],[1391,"Purchasing"],[586,"Purchasing basics"],[533,"Purchasing basics covered the everyday loop: raise a PO,\nsend it, receive the goods. This page covers the trickier buying jobs:"],[608,"Purchasing is its own module. Open it from the left rail to see open POs, the amount on\norder, and the sub-nav for Purchase Orders, Suppliers, and supplier quotes."],[530,"Purchasing planning"],[993,"Put your key in the environment"],[78,"Python Client"],[84,"Python client for calling the Carbon API."],[1432,"QMS — quality"],[1452,"QMS means Quality Management System. It's how you make sure each part is right and\ncan prove it later:"],[376,"QR Code Integration"],[1399,"Quality"],[390,"quantity - Current quantity of this entity"],[622,"Quantity — 54,001 LB"],[81,"Quick start"],[77,"quickbooks-desktop-sync/Services/CarbonService.cs"],[17,"Quickstart"],[1331,"Quote — a priced offer, before the customer commits. Ours was Q000061."],[1445,"Quote a customer, then turn the quote into a sales order when they say yes."],[272,"Quote sharing implemented in QuoteHeader.tsx using window.location.origin + path.to.externalQuote(externalLinkId)"],[911,"quote-configurator asks the customer a few questions (size, material, finish) and turns the\nanswers into a priced quote automatically. Acme already has one in its item list: the Flame Cut\nPart Configurator (FLAME CONFIG). The app computes a price and creates a quote through the API,\njust like the Q000061 quote you'd build by hand in Quoting."],[1390,"Quote, sell and ship to customers"],[1777,"Quotes live in the Sales module. Open Sales → Quotes to see every quote. Click a row\nto open one, or click the green Add Quote button (top-right) to start a new one."],[1784,"Quotes start in Draft — yours to edit freely before the customer sees them. Carbon also\nassigns the number (Q000061) and a revision automatically."],[1767,"Quoting & estimating"],[1838,"Radiant Aerospace keeps coming back: the same hook runs on SO000070 (1,500 EA, in\nprogress) and SO000071 (3,000 EA, queued). Each is its own order with its own job, but all\npoint back to the same item and method."],[505,"Radiant asks \"what do 500 hooks cost?\" You answer with a quote. Open the Sales module,\ngo to Quotes, and you'll see every quote — here's Q000061 for Radiant, already marked\nOrdered (they said yes)."],[549,"Raise a PO for the service. When production reaches the outside step, create a\npurchase order to the supplier. Carbon links it back to\nthe job, so it knows which parts left the building and why."],[1655,"Raise an NCR"],[1668,"Raise an NCR for failures. Bad parts trigger a non-conformance (next section), and the job can be held so they can't ship by mistake."],[1446,"Raise purchase orders to suppliers for the materials you need."],[1513,"Raw materials, forms, grades and dimensions for cut-to-size stock."],[245,"react - Shared React components"],[125,"React Query for server state"],[1031,"Read before you write. Read endpoints can't change anything, so they're safe to learn on.\nWhen you're ready to write (creating a quote line, releasing a job), use a test or demo\ncompany first — never your live data."],[1222,"Read each row. When Short is above zero, Carbon proposes an action. 20,000 LB of steel with nothing on hand produces a Buy → PO."],[1235,"Read it as a plan: J000097 finished first, J000098 is running now, J000099 is staged and Ready. Sequencing by due date keeps the single Sand Blasting Room from causing a missed deadline."],[1368,"Read that table top to bottom and you've just used a dozen glossary terms in one breath — which\nis exactly how Carbon strings them together."],[32,"Read the API Docs or view the source code on GitHub to get started."],[24,"Read the Docs"],[1251,"Read the standard procedure"],[1723,"Reading a customer record"],[946,"Reading a quantity is harmless; deleting a sales order is not. So Carbon tags every tool\nwith one of three safety classes. You can filter by them — for example,\nsearch_tools({ classification: \"READ\" }) returns only the look-but-don't-touch tools."],[1533,"Reading an Acme ID. A36-STEEL-PLT-1\".96x240 = A36 (grade) · STEEL (substance) ·\nPLT (form) · 1″ (thickness) · 96×240 (sheet, inches)."],[1479,"Reading the item detail page"],[12,"Ready to build your vertically integrated manufacturing system? Sign up and make your first API call in minutes with our quickstart guide."],[196,"REAL for percentages"],[345,"Realtime"],[644,"Receipt · A36 Steel Plate against PO000057. Receiving 54,001 LB into bin R02-B01-01, with the supplier's batch recorded."],[440,"Receipt (post-receipt/index.ts)"],[400,"Receipt/supplier info"],[1085,"Receive against a purchase order"],[599,"Receive the goods"],[1253,"Record good and scrap"],[1667,"Record good and scrap counts. Good pieces become quantity complete; failures become scrap with a reason."],[1088,"Record the batch (if asked)"],[871,"Record the payment. Enter the amount, the date, and the method — check, ACH, wire, card.\nRadiant paid the full $36,820.00 on 2026-06-11."],[841,"Recording payments"],[1422,"Records are linked. From a sales order you can hop to the job that makes it, the shipment\nthat sent it, and the invoice that billed it — usually by clicking the linked number. Watch the\nwhole chain in the 15-minute walkthrough."],[1033,"Records have two IDs: a friendly readable ID (SO000069, CWH-A36-15) and an internal\nrecord ID used in URLs (so_Fx6FCeSpx9sxut9Qns6y91). Fetch by either. Readable IDs are for\npeople; internal IDs are stable references for linking records."],[638,"Records how much arrived per line, so Carbon knows what's still outstanding."],[639,"Records the lot for batch-tracked items, for full\ntraceability."],[474,"Reference: llm/cache/pdf-generation-patterns.md:43"],[1688,"Register the gauge in Gauges → New — a number, description, type, and home location."],[402,"Relationship to Item Ledger:"],[1195,"Release the job. Click Release. Carbon stamps the released date, moves the job into the\nactive queue, and makes its operations available in the\nshop-floor app."],[548,"Release the job. The outside operation appears in the job's operation list with status\nTodo, in sequence between the inside steps."],[1148,"Releasing a job to the floor"],[246,"remix - Remix-specific utilities"],[126,"Remix's built-in data loading for route-specific data"],[1646,"Reorder points are per location, not per company. If you stock the same material in two\nplaces, give each location its own numbers — or one site runs dry while the other overflows."],[578,"Reorder points. For stocked items (see Replenishment),\nCarbon flags anything that dips below its minimum."],[1610,"Reorder policies, lead times and planning parameters that keep stock flowing."],[1501,"Replenishment — Make or Buy. The hook is Make: Carbon builds it on a job. The\nsteel plate is Buy: Carbon orders it on a purchase order."],[1618,"Replenishment lives in two Modules:"],[1609,"Replenishment: make vs. buy"],[419,"Represent physical items, batches, or lots"],[423,"Represent transformations or processes"],[386,"Represents a physical item, batch, or lot that needs to be tracked through the system."],[406,"Represents a transformation or process that converts input entities into output entities."],[624,"Required date — 2026-06-21"],[49,"Resend (Email service)"],[52,"Resend is used for transactional emails including user invitations, email verification, and onboarding."],[55,"RESEND_API_KEY - Your API key (format: re_**********)"],[57,"RESEND_AUDIENCE_ID - Optional, required for contact management in background jobs"],[56,"RESEND_DOMAIN - Your domain for sending emails (no trailing slashes or protocols)"],[1231,"Respect the sequence. Operations run After Previous, so Carbon keeps them in order. You decide where the whole chain fits against other jobs."],[128,"Responsive design with Tailwind utilities"],[433,"Returns all entities consumed to produce the given entity"],[429,"Returns all entities produced from the given entity"],[1557,"Reuse, don't duplicate. Search first — Acme already stocks A36 plate in 1″, 2″, 3″ and 4″.\nOnly create a new material when the physical stock is genuinely different."],[581,"Review and adjust. Bump a quantity to hit a price break, change the supplier, or skip a line.\nCarbon's number is a starting point, not a command."],[1821,"Review the header. Confirm the customer PO reference (55557777) and the\nship-from location (Headquarters). Set the order date if it isn't today."],[1193,"Review the job. Confirm quantity, due date and priority on Details, then skim\nMethod, Operations and Materials."],[855,"Review the lines. Check the quantities and prices match what shipped. Last chance to catch\na wrong price before the customer sees it."],[286,"Role permissions - These are permissions that are specific to a role. For example, customers may be able to view the sales module, but a customer role limits the data to only their own sales, where an employee with the same permission can view all sales."],[806,"Roles side by side"],[1448,"Roll up cost automatically, so you know if a price leaves a profit."],[108,"Route Patterns"],[251,"routes/ - Remix routes"],[218,"Routing"],[1325,"Routing — how it's made. The hook's routing is three steps: Flame Cut → Sandblasting\n→ Inspection."],[1581,"Routing — how the part is made. An ordered list of operations, each run at a work center with a time. The hook: flame cut, then sandblast, then inspect."],[734,"Routing operations — one row per operation, with its sequence, process (Flame Cut,\nSandblasting, Inspection) and the work center it runs at, plus a time per piece."],[1020,"Rule of thumb: automating your data → API key. Building an app other customers log\ninto → OAuth."],[1627,"Rule of thumb: if an item has a method, it's Make. If it has a supplier and a\npurchase price, it's Buy."],[1249,"Run an operation, start to finish"],[1593,"Run time — per-piece time. Here, 45 Minutes/Piece."],[1389,"Sales"],[1313,"Sales — quotes and orders from customers."],[836,"Sales and purchase invoices, payments and finance integrations."],[849,"Sales invoice (AR) — bills a customer for what you shipped. AR means Accounts\nReceivable: money owed to you."],[839,"Sales invoices — billing the customer"],[858,"Sales invoices use three statuses:"],[1332,"Sales Order (SO) — the customer's commitment: who, what, how many, when, and price.\nAccept a quote and it becomes an SO in one click. Ours is SO000069."],[1798,"Sales orders"],[1811,"Sales orders live in the Sales module. Open Sales, then click Orders in the\nleft sub-nav to see every order and its status."],[1647,"Same shop, four different strategies — all driven by make-or-buy plus a couple of numbers."],[1478,"Save"],[1709,"Save"],[1717,"Save"],[1721,"Save"],[1713,"Save and repeat"],[1753,"Save each address. Carbon proposes the defaults on every new order, and you can switch in one click."],[1745,"Save, then add anyone else you deal with — for example a separate AP contact for invoices."],[1173,"Save. Carbon assigns the next job number and snapshots the method. The job opens as\nPlanned, ready for review."],[1757,"Save. From now on, invoices for this customer default to Net 30 — exactly what shows on\nRadiant's real invoice AR000025."],[829,"Save. The change applies to everyone with that type right away. No need to edit each person."],[1202,"Schedule, track and plan work across the shop."],[387,"Schema:"],[407,"Schema:"],[3,"Scope"],[1285,"Scrap — pieces that failed. Each scrap needs a reason (Acme uses Damaged, Defective, Quality) so the shop can see why parts are lost."],[1417,"Search and filter at the top to narrow the rows."],[163,"Security Invoker Views"],[76,"See the Carbon API Reference for more information."],[86,"See the Carbon API Reference for more information."],[96,"See the Carbon API Reference for more information."],[75,"See the community supabase C# client documentation for more information."],[95,"See the official supabase javascript client documentation for more information."],[85,"See the official supabase python client documentation for more information."],[920,"See your connected systems in Settings → Integrations. Here's Acme's:"],[38,"Self-host Carbon on your own infrastructure"],[37,"Self-Hosting"],[1330,"Selling happens in the Sales module. Two records carry demand:"],[1791,"Selling the same kind of part in many shapes (cut plate, machined bar)? Use a\nconfigurator — one item that asks a few questions, then builds the method and cost for\nyou. Acme has the Flame Cut Part Configurator (FLAME CONFIG). See\nMethods: BOM & routing."],[534,"Send a part out for a coating (outside processing)."],[526,"Send an RFQ and compare the replies"],[598,"Send it"],[1772,"Send it"],[1016,"Send it as a header. Carbon reads your company from the key automatically:"],[857,"Send it. Email or download the PDF. Carbon stamps the date and starts the payment-terms\nclock — here, Net 30."],[567,"Send the PO; the supplier ships your customer. Nothing arrives at your shop, so there's no\nreceipt and no inventory movement on your side."],[635,"Sending is not receiving. Sending tells the supplier what you want — it does not add\nanything to inventory. Material lands on your shelf only when you receive it."],[1341,"Serial — a unique number per individual unit (high-value or regulated parts)."],[396,"Serial numbers"],[1696,"Serial tracking gives each finished unit its own number — for parts a customer needs to trace one by one."],[282,"Server-Side Permission Checks"],[302,"Server-side permission checks - a helper function that checks the user's permissions before making a call to the database."],[263,"Service functions handle database operations"],[106,"Service Layer Pattern"],[220,"Services"],[122,"Services handle business logic and database operations. The first argument of the service is always the client object, which is a user-permissioned Supabase client:"],[252,"services/ - Business logic and API calls"],[1601,"Set a BOM line's method type to Make instead of Pull from Inventory, and it becomes a sub-assembly — Carbon nests that child part's whole method underneath. When a job runs, it can build the sub-assemblies first."],[670,"Set a supplier up once and the rest of buying gets easier. Every purchase\norder already knows who to email, where to ship from, how\nyou pay, and the price to expect."],[783,"Set an item's unit before you transact with it — it feeds pricing, inventory and\npurchasing. Buying in one unit and stocking in another (buy steel by the pound, receive it as\nplates) uses separate purchase and inventory units, not a change to the base unit."],[593,"Set dates and delivery"],[1575,"Set it once. Every quote, job, and cost estimate is built from it automatically."],[805,"Set module permissions"],[795,"Set one term as the company default, optionally override it on a specific customer or\nsupplier, and Carbon fills it in automatically on every new order and invoice. You can still\nchange it on one document when a deal calls for it."],[664,"Set payment terms"],[1718,"Set payment terms"],[791,"Set prefixes and padding before you create your first document. The counter only goes up\n— don't reset it backwards, or you risk duplicate IDs."],[1172,"Set quantity, due date and priority. Enter how many to make, when they're due, and how\nurgent the job is."],[1553,"Set replenishment to Buy. Acme buys plate, so set\nreplenishment to Buy. This unlocks supplier and reorder settings."],[1643,"Set safety stock. A buffer kept on the shelf beyond known demand. Acme keeps 3,000 LB\nof A36 steel at Headquarters. The hook keeps none — it's made to order."],[1689,"Set the calibration interval (Acme uses six months). Carbon uses it to compute the next-due date."],[1221,"Set the horizon. At the top, choose how far ahead to look. Carbon only raises suggestions for demand inside the horizon."],[1644,"Set the lead time. How long replenishment takes. Both hero items use 7 days. Carbon\nworks back from the due date to tell you the latest day to order or release."],[1586,"Set the line to Pull from Inventory. That tells Carbon to pull the steel off the shelf when a job runs."],[1565,"Set the quantity per piece"],[1642,"Set the reorder point and quantity. Drop below the reorder point and Carbon raises a\nsuggestion. The reorder quantity is how much to order each time."],[1552,"Set the unit of measure. Choose LB (Pound) — the unit you buy and consume the plate in."],[1637,"Set these on the item's Planning tab, per location (Headquarters and Texas can differ):"],[1477,"Set tracking and Make-or-Buy"],[528,"Set up a drop-ship"],[524,"Set up and run an outside operation"],[655,"Set up the vendors you buy materials and services from."],[1404,"Set up your company and account"],[770,"Set your base currency. Acme uses USD. This is the currency your books are kept in."],[750,"Setting up your company"],[1403,"Settings"],[763,"Settings is split into sections: Company, Locations, Units of Measure,\nSequences, Payment Terms, and more. You'll set up five of them below."],[1592,"Setup time — one-time per job. The flame cut has 0 setup."],[1599,"Setup vs. run time. Run time scales with quantity; setup doesn't. That's why bigger batches usually cost less per piece — and Carbon does the math the moment you set a job quantity."],[755,"Shelves and bins live inside a location"],[1091,"Ship against a sales order"],[550,"Ship out, then receive back. Send the parts to the supplier. When they return finished,\nrecord a receipt against the PO. That marks the outside\noperation complete and the job moves to the next step."],[536,"Ship straight to your customer (drop-ship)."],[1749,"Ship-to — where goods are delivered. Drives shipments."],[449,"Shipment (post-shipment/index.ts)"],[1835,"Shipments — every time goods leave, a shipment record appears with the quantity and date.\nSO000069 has one shipment for all 500 hooks, sent 2026-06-11."],[1871,"Shipped — how many have left the dock."],[1082,"Shipping & receiving"],[535,"Shop several suppliers for the best price (RFQs)."],[1114,"Short — receive what arrived; the PO line stays open for the rest."],[628,"Shortcut: buy from a job. Acme didn't type this line by hand. When job J000097 was\nplanned, Carbon saw it needed 20,000 lb of A36 plate it didn't have and surfaced a\nshortage — from there you generate the PO with item, quantity, and supplier already\nfilled in. See Jobs and\nAdvanced purchasing."],[28,"Sign up at app.carbon.ms"],[967,"Sign-in is either an OAuth login (you log in to Carbon once; the assistant gets a\nscoped token) or an API key from Carbon's settings — the same key you'd use for the\nAPI."],[316,"Simplicity"],[321,"Simplicity"],[44,"Single-click self-hosting is coming soon!"],[330,"Single-purpose examples and templates"],[1830,"SO000069's line is Make to Order — Acme doesn't stock 500 finished hooks, so each order is\nbuilt fresh. That one setting spawns Job J000097 when the order is confirmed."],[166,"Soft Delete"],[356,"Some data like the list of parts, customers, and suppliers are used on many pages. And regularly refetching thousands of rows is not ideal. To avoid making a request for this data on every page, we load it once in the <RealtimeDataProvider> on page load. We then put the data from each table into a nanostore hook that has a getter and setter that can be accessed from any page. For example:"],[540,"Some steps aren't done in-house. A part comes off your mill in great shape, but still needs\nanodizing or painting. You send it to a specialist, they do the work, and they ship it\nback. That round trip is outside processing."],[201,"Some tables use \"blocked\" BOOLEAN DEFAULT FALSE"],[1418,"Sort by clicking a column header."],[411,"sourceDocument - Document type that triggered this activity"],[392,"sourceDocument - Type of document that created this entity (e.g., \"Receipt\", \"Manufacturing\")"],[412,"sourceDocumentId - Specific document instance"],[393,"sourceDocumentId - UUID of the specific revision that created this entity"],[394,"sourceDocumentReadableId - Human-readable ID of the source document"],[147,"Special Cases"],[368,"SQL Functions"],[649,"Stamps the PO line as received and moves the order toward To Invoice."],[151,"Standard Columns"],[1034,"Standard HTTP codes: 401 key missing or wrong, 403 key lacks permission, 404 record not\nfound, 429 too many requests. The clients surface these as typed errors. On a 429, wait and\nretry."],[159,"Standard Indexes"],[156,"Standard Pattern"],[1550,"Start a new material. In the Items module, on the Materials tab, click the green\nAdd button (top-right). Picking Material gives you the substance/form/grade fields."],[591,"Start a new order"],[600,"Start a receipt from the PO"],[864,"Start from the PO. Go to Purchase Invoices → New and select the purchase order —\nfor example, Ryerson's A36 steel from PO000057. Carbon pre-fills supplier, lines and prices."],[1678,"Start from the problem. Open the failing operation, or go to Issues → New. Starting from the operation pre-fills the job, part, and work center."],[1780,"Start it. Click the green Add Quote button, then pick Radiant Aerospace as the\ncustomer. Carbon pulls in their address, contact, currency (USD) and payment terms\n(Net 30) — so you don't re-key any of it."],[1649,"Start simple. Set Make or Buy on every item, add a lead time so dates are\nrealistic, and add safety stock only where running out actually hurts. Tighten the rest later."],[1070,"Start the adjustment. Choose Adjust quantity and pick the storage unit, e.g.\nR02-B01-01."],[1086,"Start the receipt"],[1092,"Start the shipment"],[975,"Start with a READ. Ask something safe, like \"List Radiant Aerospace's open jobs.\" If you\nget a sensible answer, you're connected. Only then move to WRITE asks, deliberately."],[470,"startProductionEvent() - Creates activities and links during production"],[111,"State Management"],[391,"status - Enum: 'Available', 'Reserved', 'On Hold', 'Consumed'"],[1729,"Status — shows where a customer is in your relationship:"],[676,"Status controls whether you can buy now. Active shows everywhere; Inactive is\nhidden from new orders but kept for history — that's how you retire a vendor without\ndeleting records."],[1241,"Status says where to look. In Progress jobs are on the floor now — J000095 and J000098 get today's attention."],[1847,"Step 1 — A Make-to-Order line creates a job"],[986,"Step 1 — Create an API key"],[492,"Step 1 — Quote the customer · Sales module"],[1204,"Step 1: Demand in, plan out"],[991,"Step 2 — Install a client library"],[493,"Step 2 — Take the order · Sales module"],[1848,"Step 2 — Watch fulfillment on the order"],[1205,"Step 2: Review suggestions in Planning"],[1849,"Step 3 — Create the shipment"],[494,"Step 3 — How it's made · Items module"],[992,"Step 3 — Make your first call"],[1206,"Step 3: Schedule jobs across work centers"],[495,"Step 4 — Make it · Production module"],[1850,"Step 4 — The line reads Shipped"],[1207,"Step 4: Prioritize what runs first"],[496,"Step 5 — Buy the steel · Purchasing module"],[1851,"Step 5 — Invoice the order"],[1208,"Step 5: Track progress"],[497,"Step 6 — Check it and ship it · Quality + Inventory"],[498,"Step 7 — Get paid · Accounting module"],[455,"Step-by-step process for converting tracked entities (e.g., material → part):"],[1276,"Steps aren't only checkboxes. A step can also ask the operator to type a measurement (with a min and max, so bad values are caught on the spot), pick from a list, or attach a photo. A laminated sheet becomes recorded, checkable data."],[452,"Stock Transfer (post-stock-transfer/index.ts)"],[1042,"Storage units (shelves & bins)"],[443,"Stores supplier info, batch numbers, etc. in attributes"],[253,"stores/ - State management (appears to use nanostores)"],[254,"styles/ - CSS files"],[227,"Styling: Tailwind CSS"],[596,"Submit for approval"],[1528,"Substance — the alloy. Carbon ships 17 built-in (Steel, Stainless Steel, Aluminum,\nBrass, Inconel, Titanium and more). Acme uses six, plus a custom one (Foam) for packaging."],[1887,"Subtotal vs. total. The subtotal ($36,570) is the goods alone. The total ($36,820)\nadds the $250 freight. The order total and invoice total match — the gap is always shipping."],[46,"Supabase"],[292,"supplier"],[525,"Supplier quotes (RFQs)"],[654,"Suppliers"],[669,"Suppliers live in the Purchasing module. Open Purchasing, then click Suppliers\nin the sub-nav across the top."],[1215,"Supply — what covers it: stock on hand, open purchase orders, jobs in progress."],[6,"Support"],[437,"Supports ancestor/descendant traversal"],[131,"Tables are named in the singular camelCase format (e.g. customer, salesOrder, item)"],[1280,"Tap Pause to step away — the timer stops, so breaks aren't billed to the job."],[1279,"Tap Start. This clocks the operator ON and starts a timer. From here, every minute counts against the job — at Burn Table - PA2's rate of $50/hour labor, that time is becoming real cost on J000097."],[1271,"Tap the Flame Cut row. The MES shows an operation card — what to make, how many, from what, and how."],[209,"Tech Stack"],[761,"Tell Carbon a few facts about your business — who you are, where you keep stock, how you\nmeasure things, how documents are numbered, and when you get paid. Set these up once, up\nfront. We'll use the real settings behind Acme Inc., the example company in this manual."],[1559,"Tell Carbon how a part is made with a bill of materials and a routing."],[1089,"Tell Carbon where it goes"],[1759,"Terms are defaults, not handcuffs. You can override them on a single order or invoice anytime."],[776,"Texas is a second site with its own burn table and laser table."],[980,"That last sentence is the real value: the assistant didn't just fetch a number — it tied it\nto something you care about. You can't build a hook until you raise another\npurchase order to Ryerson, like PO000057."],[851,"That's it. Acme has 25 sales invoices (AR000001–AR000025) and 27 purchase invoices\n(AP000001–AP000027)."],[1294,"That's the hand-off back to the office: a Completed job means the parts exist, ready to ship against sales order SO000069. The shop floor did its part, and every minute it spent is now visible to the rest of Carbon."],[519,"That's the whole idea of Carbon: enter something once, and it follows the work across every\nModule. Now dive into any step below."],[499,"That's the whole loop"],[1346,"That's the whole vocabulary, mapped to one hook:"],[1458,"That's what \"system of record\" buys you: enter it once, and it follows the work\neverywhere. Here is Acme's single hook order seen through all three sides at once."],[1162,"That's what keeps a finished job's cost and\ntraceability trustworthy months later."],[1132,"The 500 hooks leave inventory from the picking bin."],[938,"The API is the raw machinery — every Carbon action as a callable endpoint. MCP wraps\nthat machinery so an AI assistant can drive it. Want to wire Carbon to another system\ninstead of talking to it? See Integrating with other systems."],[956,"The assistant reads the order list, filters by status and date, and hands you the offenders.\nThis is MCP's sweet spot — a question that would take several filtered screens, answered in\none sentence. More triage:"],[1852,"The back half, in one table"],[1161,"The big idea: a job carries its own copy of the method. When you create it, Carbon\nsnapshots the part's bill of materials and routing onto the job. Edit the part's master\nmethod later — this job keeps the recipe it was born with."],[1582,"The BOM answers one question: to make one, what do I use? Enter the quantity for a single piece. Carbon scales it later — a job for 500 hooks needs 40 × 500 = 20,000 LB of plate, automatically."],[1182,"The BOM has one material line: 40 LB of A36 steel plate per piece. Times 500, the job\nneeds 20,000 LB — Carbon does the math."],[475,"The Carbon Manual"],[1315,"The chain that ties them together looks like this:"],[101,"The conventions that guide the development of Carbon"],[135,"The conventions that guide the development of database migrations in Carbon"],[1789,"The cost rollup is only as good as the part's method. No bill of\nmaterials or routing yet? Carbon can't estimate the cost — build the method first, or quote\na known price and refine it later."],[1538,"The Counterweight Hook (CWH-A36-15) pulls 40 LB of A36 plate per hook."],[1786,"The Counterweight Hook is short: 40 lb of 1-inch A36 steel plate, then three operations."],[731,"The Counterweight Hook's method is short: one material, three operations."],[1827,"The customer PO reference (55557777) is the number your customer uses for the order.\nCapturing it prints it on the packing slip and invoice, so their accounts-payable team can\nmatch your bill without a phone call."],[1727,"The Customers list shows one row per company. We'll build out Radiant Aerospace — Acme's\nmost active customer, behind the Counterweight Hook order SO000069."],[1212,"The dashboard is your shop at a glance: Active Jobs, Work Center Utilization, and which machines are busy. Acme runs work through machines like the DMU 50, the Inspection Station, and its Burn Tables."],[1505,"The detail page groups everything into tabs. The hook is a Make part, so its\nManufacturing tab holds the method (the recipe) and a 3D model."],[482,"The easiest way to picture Carbon: it's split into Modules — one for each part of your\nbusiness. Selling lives in Sales. Buying lives in Purchasing. Making things lives in\nProduction. And so on."],[257,"The ERP app organizes business logic into modules:"],[1260,"The ERP is the full office app — Sales, Purchasing, Items, Production. Jobs are planned and costed there."],[339,"The ERP system is the heart of a business' digital operation. We want to make sure that they can easily integrate with other systems and customize it in any way that they need. The only real way to do this that to make the source code available."],[501,"The fastest way to \"get\" Carbon is to follow one order through it. We'll track a single real\npart — a Counterweight Hook that Acme makes for Radiant Aerospace — from the first\nprice request to a paid invoice. You'll touch most of the Modules along the way."],[1407,"The fastest way to get around is search. Press ⌘K (Ctrl+K on\nWindows), or click the search bar up top, and a box opens over whatever you're doing."],[909,"The field names you see here (salesOrderId, unitPrice) are the same ones used inside the app.\nThere's no separate \"integration data model\" to learn."],[1144,"The fields that drive a job"],[666,"The finished supplier"],[1486,"The first thing you choose is the type. It tells Carbon what role the item plays. Acme\nuses all six."],[1196,"The floor takes over. Operators clock onto each operation and report pieces. When the last\noperation hits the production quantity, the job is Completed."],[816,"The flow: invite the user, give them an employee type, and that type's\npermissions decide what they can touch."],[1040,"The four building blocks"],[1516,"The four parts of a material"],[1829,"The fulfillment method is the most important choice on a line. You set it per line, so\none order can ship some items from stock and make others to order."],[1352,"The full A–Z"],[997,"The full reference: Developer Docs"],[1358,"The glossary isn't a Module — it's a reference for all of them. Carbon is built from a set of\nModules: Sales, Purchasing, Items, Production, Inventory, Quality, Accounting, and Shop Floor.\nEach definition below tells you which Module a term belongs to so you know where to click."],[1298,"The handful of ideas that make everything else click: items, methods, jobs, orders and traceability."],[1600,"The hook goes straight from raw material to finished part — a single-level method. But many products are built from sub-parts you also make."],[1590,"The hook's routing is three operations:"],[173,"The id() function returns a random character string with an optional prefix for better readability"],[1044,"The item ledger"],[652,"The job consumes the plate, carrying the lot number into the finished hooks."],[515,"The job's last step is Inspection — a quality gate. Once the parts pass, you create a\nshipment and send the 500 hooks. Carbon marks the order line Shipped."],[1238,"The jobs list is your live status board. Completion updates itself as operators record finished pieces in the shop floor app — you never type a percentage by hand."],[288,"The JSON permissions data in that column something like this:"],[860,"The key idea is matching. Carbon checks the supplier's bill against two things that already\nexist:"],[1256,"The last operation finishes the job"],[1189,"The last operation, Inspection, is a quality gate: the parts aren't finished until they\npass. See Tracking quality."],[1333,"The line says Make to Order. Because the hook is a Make item, the next step is a Job —\nnot a pick from the shelf."],[1812,"The list shows each order's number, customer, total, and status at a glance. Click a\nrow to open the order."],[1244,"The loop. Demand creates suggestions → you turn them into jobs and POs → you schedule jobs across work centers → operators run them → the dashboard updates in real time → new demand restarts it."],[646,"The lot shown (HEAT-A36-0612) is illustrative — enter whatever batch ID the mill\ncertificate gives. Items that aren't batch- or serial-tracked skip this step."],[1121,"The material is now real stock the job can pull from."],[1183,"The material is Pull from Inventory, so the job draws steel from stock. The\npurchase order to Ryerson makes sure that stock is there."],[1190,"The Materials tab is the job's shopping list. For J000097 it's one line."],[1272,"The Materials tab shows what to pull: 40 LB of A36 Steel Plate 1″ per piece, from bin R02-B01-01."],[971,"The menu differs by assistant, but the shape is the same: point it at Carbon's MCP URL and\ngive it credentials."],[1261,"The MES is a stripped-down, touch-friendly app for a shop-floor tablet. It shows an operator only what they need: the operations waiting at their work center, the instructions, and big Start, Pause and Finish buttons."],[1266,"The MES shows only the operations queued at the operator's work center — not the whole factory. Each row is one operation on one job. Fred Flame works the burn tables, so his queue leads with the Flame Cut on J000097."],[1327,"The method earns its keep two ways:"],[1129,"The method is where a shipping cost rides along. SO000069 carries $250 of freight, which shows on the invoice but not in the goods subtotal."],[1145,"The method the job carries"],[1384,"The module rail — the column of icons down the left edge, on every page."],[237,"The monorepo uses NPM workspaces with packages located in /packages/:"],[915,"The most common integration is keeping your accounting system in step. Acme runs its books in\nQuickBooks. Carbon owns what was made, shipped and billed;\nQuickBooks owns the general ledger. The sync keeps them agreeing without double data entry, and\nit's a textbook example of the webhook-plus-API pattern."],[1437,"The one idea to remember"],[1186,"The Operations tab lists the routing. Each operation runs at one work center and has a\ntime per piece. They run in sequence — Sandblasting can't start until Flame Cut is done."],[759,"The order to do them in"],[1796,"The order total ($36,820.00) is higher than the quote line total ($36,570.00) because $250\nof shipping was added on the order. Quotes price the work; the order is where freight and\ntaxes get finalized."],[1288,"The other operators do the same in turn: Carlos Axis runs Sandblasting, then Terry Tolerance runs the Quality Inspection at the Inspection Station and clocks off the last operation."],[1406,"The outer frame stays put. Only the content area in the middle swaps to show the Module\nyou picked."],[1579,"The part itself — name, unit, Make or Buy — is set on the item. See Defining an item. The method is where the making lives."],[1499,"The part number must be unique. Pick a readable scheme and stick to it."],[503,"The part: the Counterweight Hook (part number CWH-A36-15) is a steel hook cut from\n1-inch plate. Radiant orders 500 at a time. You don't need to do anything here — just read."],[1845,"The path, in four moves"],[942,"The pattern is always: search → describe (if needed) → call. You never see these steps —\nyou just see the answer. Ask \"what's the on-hand quantity of A36 steel?\" and the assistant:"],[901,"The payload is small on purpose: it tells you what and which record, not every field. Use the\nrecordId to fetch the full, current details with an API call."],[476,"The plain-English guide to running your manufacturing business on Carbon — with real screenshots showing exactly where to click."],[1120,"The PO line moves toward Received / To Invoice."],[1111,"The PO must be issued to the supplier first. You can't receive against a PO that's still a draft."],[315,"The principles that guide the development of Carbon"],[123,"The project uses a custom form library with validators:"],[115,"The project uses absolute imports with these patterns:"],[861,"The purchase order — the price and quantity you agreed to."],[1659,"The Quality module keeps bad parts from leaving the building — and lets you prove later that what you shipped was good. It has four jobs: inspections, non-conformances (NCRs), gauges, and traceability."],[1268,"The queue filters by work center, not by job. Fred sees Flame Cut work from several jobs at once. An operator at the Sand Blasting Room sees a different list."],[889,"The QuickBooks sync, end to end"],[862,"The receipt — what actually showed up on the dock."],[1589,"The routing is the ordered list of shop-floor steps. Each operation says what you do, where (a work center), and how long it takes. Steps are numbered in tens (10, 20, 30…) so you can slot one in between later."],[507,"The sales order is the customer's commitment. In Sales → Orders you can see SO000069\nfor Radiant Aerospace — Completed, $36,820."],[1869,"The sales order is your dashboard for \"how close are we?\" Every line keeps three running tallies,\nupdated automatically:"],[1168,"The same link happens for Radiant's other orders: SO000070 made job J000098 (1,500 EA)\nand SO000071 made job J000099 (3,000 EA). One part, three orders, three jobs."],[1834,"The Shipments and Invoices buttons on the order are where fulfillment shows up. You\ndon't fill them in by hand — they populate as goods leave and bills post."],[1127,"The shipping method is the carrier the goods leave on. Acme has ten configured. A pallet of 500 steel hooks is freight, not a parcel — so pick LTL (Less Than Truckload) or FTL (Full Truckload), not UPS Ground."],[845,"The shop earns the money; the Accounting module counts it. This page covers the two kinds\nof invoice and how they get paid — no accounting background needed."],[1245,"The shop floor (MES)"],[1259,"The shop floor is the Shop Floor module, delivered as its own app: the MES (Manufacturing Execution System)."],[1473,"The six item types"],[1133,"The SO line shows 500 of 500 sent and moves toward Completed."],[1833,"The status column on the Orders list tells you where each order is."],[1191,"The steel is batch-tracked, so Carbon records exactly which heat went into this batch of\nhooks — the foundation of Radiant's traceability. It pulls\nfrom bin R02-B01-01 at Headquarters."],[651,"The steel is now real, on the shelf, and ready for job J000097."],[529,"The supplier portal"],[653,"The supplier sends a bill, which you match to the PO and receipt as an\naccounts-payable invoice. Matching PO ↔ receipt ↔ bill is how\nyou catch an overcharge before you pay."],[919,"The sync writes it across. It pulls the full invoice ($36,570 subtotal, $250 shipping,\n$36,820 total) and creates the matching invoice in QuickBooks. When Radiant pays, that status can\nflow over too."],[1351,"The three letters: ERP, MES, QMS"],[928,"The three meta-tools"],[1457,"The three sides feel like one tool because they sit on one database. A sales order, the\njob that fulfills it, the purchase order for its material, the inspection that passed it,\nand the invoice that bills it are all linked records."],[1273,"The Tools tab lists any tooling the step needs."],[435,"The traceability graph is visualized in apps/erp/app/routes/x+/traceability+/graph.tsx:"],[417,"The traceability system forms a directed acyclic graph (DAG) where:"],[1561,"The two halves of a method"],[838,"The two kinds of invoice"],[1661,"The two numbers up top tell you the workload at a glance:"],[1375,"The two screens you'll always see"],[848,"There are only two, and they mirror each other:"],[300,"There are three places where permissions can be used in the code. In order of precedence, they are:"],[894,"There are three ways to connect:"],[349,"There are two basic use cases for realtime data in Carbon ERP:"],[284,"There are two types of permissions in the system:"],[1817,"There are two ways an order is born. Converting a quote is by far the most common — it's\nhow SO000069 was created."],[1165,"There are two ways."],[1311,"These ideas span three modules. You'll spend most of your time in:"],[739,"These mirror Acme's real follow-on Counterweight Hook orders (SO000070 and SO000071, right\nafter the hero order SO000069). Once in, Carbon plans jobs and purchasing against them."],[825,"These names are examples — you create and name your own. The one type that always exists is\nAdministrator: it reaches every module and Settings. Always keep at least one."],[414,"These tables link activities to entities and define the graph structure."],[58,"These variables are used in the authentication configuration (packages/auth/src/config/env.ts)."],[820,"They accept. Carbon emails the invite. When they click it and set a password, they're in.\nUntil then their status shows Invited instead of Active."],[1291,"They advance the work. Reported good quantity flows to the next operation."],[1292,"They build the record. Who ran each step and when is stored for good — for traceability, payroll, and answering \"what happened on this job?\" later."],[1290,"They cost the job. Recorded minutes times the work center's labor and machine rates post to the job as actual cost — so Carbon can compare estimated vs. real cost."],[1413,"Think of ⌘K like a browser address bar: don't navigate to a thing — just name it."],[1049,"This all lives in the Inventory module. Open it, then go to Quantities to see\non-hand stock for every item, with its reorder policy."],[353,"This can be done easily with the useRealtime hook:"],[1546,"This chain — shipment → batch → job → part → customer — is traceability. It's why Radiant\nAerospace cares that Acme runs batch-tracked steel. More in\ntracking quality."],[65,"This command syncs your Novu workflows using the bridge URL."],[1856,"This flow lives mostly in the Sales module, with one stop in Inventory (the shipment).\nOpen Sales → Orders, then click your order to see the buttons that drive everything below."],[579,"This is how Acme's hero PO was born. Job J000097 needed 40 LB of A36 plate per piece —\n20,000 LB for the batch of 500 — and Acme was short. Carbon flagged it, and that suggestion\nbecame PO000057 to Ryerson."],[936,"This is part of the Developer module — the same place as the API.\nCarbon hosts the server for you at app.carbon.ms/mcp. Nothing to install. You connect an\nassistant to that URL, and it can run Carbon on your behalf."],[893,"This is part of the Developer module. You set up keys and connections in\nSettings → Integrations and Settings → API."],[1460,"This is the biggest difference from spreadsheets. There, each row lives in a different\nfile, gets copied by hand, and drifts out of sync. In Carbon they are the same data —\nchange one, and everyone sees it."],[1211,"This is the Production module. Open it from the home screen, then use Planning, Jobs, and the dashboard inside it."],[1029,"This is the same record the Sales Order page shows — same\nnumbers, no copy:"],[636,"This is the step that actually changes your stock. When the truck arrives, create a\nreceipt against the PO. Receiving:"],[481,"This is the written guide to Carbon — the read-it-yourself companion to\nCarbon Academy. It's made for people who'd rather read than\nwatch a video. Every page is short, uses real screenshots, and shows you exactly where\nto click."],[1258,"This is where planned work gets done. An operator picks an operation, clocks on, records good and scrap counts, and clocks off. Every tap feeds real labor time and cost back to the job — no clipboards."],[1576,"This page builds the method for Acme's hero part, the Counterweight Hook (CWH-A36-15)."],[1810,"This page follows Acme's real order SO000069 — 500 Counterweight Hooks for Radiant\nAerospace, $36,820, Make to Order."],[1036,"This page is the on-ramp. For every endpoint, field, auth flow, and webhook, go to the\nDeveloper Docs:"],[1356,"This page is your dictionary. Carbon uses a lot of words that sound technical but are simple\nonce someone explains them plainly. That's what this page does: one short definition per term,\nplus a real example from Acme Inc. — the demo company used throughout this manual."],[1483,"This page lives in the Items module. It covers the six kinds of item and how to create one."],[929,"Three safety classes"],[1462,"Throughout the manual we follow one part Acme makes — a Counterweight Hook\n(part number CWH-A36-15) for the customer Radiant Aerospace. One order for it touches\nevery Module, so it's the thread that ties the whole manual together."],[828,"Tick what the role needs. For a salesperson: full Sales, View on Items (to pick\nparts onto a quote), and nothing else."],[202,"Timestamps: DEFAULT NOW()"],[781,"To add your own, open Settings → Units of Measure and give it a short code (the\nabbreviation that shows on documents) and a name."],[169,"To create a database migration use npm run db:migrate:new <name>."],[1687,"To keep gauges current:"],[1024,"To prove your key works, read something — don't write. You'll list items, then fetch one\nsales order: the Counterweight Hook (CWH-A36-15) and its order, SO000069."],[334,"To provide extensibility we have the following goals:"],[326,"To provide simplicity we use these approaches:"],[1541,"To see live stock, open the Inventory module. It lists on-hand quantity, reorder policy\nand replenishment for every item — including Acme's steel and aluminum."],[27,"To use the API, you need to sign up on Carbon and get an API key. You can also run Carbon locally by following the README."],[385,"Together, these form a directed acyclic graph (DAG) that represents material flow from raw materials through transformations to finished products."],[1491,"Tool vs Consumable is just value and durability. A Tool (a caliper, a torque wrench)\nlasts years and is worth tracking. A Consumable (sandpaper, welding wire) is cheap and\nused up. Ask: \"would I notice if one walked off?\" If yes, it's probably a Tool."],[332,"Total transparency"],[359,"Traceability"],[1455,"Traceability — the linked chain from finished part back to the exact batch of raw\nmaterial. Carbon can answer \"which heat of steel went into Radiant's hooks?\" in seconds."],[1339,"Traceability (or genealogy) answers, after the fact: what went into this, and where did\nit end up? It works through two kinds of tracking you can switch on per item:"],[1694,"Traceability (or genealogy) follows a part backward and forward: which raw material went in, which job made it, which customer it shipped to. The enabler is tracking set on the item:"],[1657,"Traceability: prove what went where"],[1447,"Track inventory — what's on the shelf, where, and how much."],[1806,"Track shipments and invoices"],[1398,"Track stock across locations"],[382,"Tracked Activities - Transformations or processes that consume inputs and produce outputs (nodes in the graph)"],[383,"Tracked Activity Inputs - Links activities to their input entities (edges in the graph)"],[384,"Tracked Activity Outputs - Links activities to their output entities (edges in the graph)"],[381,"Tracked Entities - Physical items, batches, or lots that need to be tracked (nodes in the graph)"],[439,"Tracked entities are created during various operations:"],[471,"Tracked entities can have QR codes generated for labeling:"],[363,"trackedActivity"],[415,"trackedActivityInput:"],[416,"trackedActivityOutput:"],[362,"trackedEntity"],[1500,"Tracking — Inventory (Carbon keeps a running on-hand count). Use Batch when the lot\nmatters, Serial for high-value parts, Non-Inventory for services."],[1503,"Tracking is hard to change once an item has history, so set it now. When unsure: Inventory\nfor physical goods, Non-Inventory for services."],[1650,"Tracking quality"],[451,"Tracks what entities left the facility"],[453,"Transfers entities between locations"],[1081,"Treat a bin that's always short as a signal, not just a number to fix — the cause is usually\nupstream (material used but never recorded on a job, or scrap that skipped the system)."],[1010,"Treat a key like a password. Anyone with it can act as you. Never put it in client-side\ncode, a public repo, or a screenshot. Keep it in an environment variable, and delete any key\nthe moment you think it leaked."],[914,"Treat these as templates, not products. Clone one, point it at your own company with your API key,\nand reshape it. Same field names as the app, so the gap is usually small."],[948,"Treat WRITE and DESTRUCTIVE tools like a teammate with edit access. The assistant is\nchanging your live data, just like a colleague clicking the buttons. When exploring, keep\nit to READ tools. Turn on WRITE access deliberately, for one task, with a human checking\nthe result."],[48,"Trigger.dev"],[1554,"Turn on batch tracking (if needed). For traceable stock, switch on Requires batch\ntracking now — before any inventory exists."],[1548,"Turn on batch tracking before you receive any stock. Switching it on later leaves existing\nquantity with no batch number. For regulated work, enable it when you first create the material."],[1701,"Turn on tracking before you receive material. Set batch (or serial) tracking on the item up front, so every receipt, job, and shipment records the lot automatically."],[531,"Turn suggestions into purchase orders"],[720,"Two decisions matter on every row: its itemType (part, material, tool?) and its\nreplenishmentSystem — do you Make it or Buy it?"],[426,"Two key functions enable bidirectional graph traversal:"],[1801,"Two parts of an order"],[1672,"Two settings shape every NCR:"],[802,"Two simple ideas"],[674,"Two small fields shape how a supplier behaves:"],[1705,"Two things to know first"],[1267,"Two things to know:"],[1181,"Two things to notice:"],[1382,"Two ways to move around:"],[1011,"Two ways to prove who's calling. Pick by whose data you're touching."],[410,"type - Describes the transformation (e.g., \"Manufacturing\", \"Assembly\", \"Conversion\")"],[1735,"Type — a label for grouping customers, handy for filtering and reports. Acme groups by\nindustry. Radiant Aerospace is Aerospace & Defense."],[1495,"Type — Part"],[1673,"Type — the cause, so you can spot patterns later (e.g. three Material Issue NCRs all from one supplier). Acme ships with ten types like Manufacturing Defect, Material Issue, and Customer Complaint."],[675,"Type groups and filters the list. It doesn't affect pricing. Define your own types in\nSettings — Acme uses five."],[1752,"Type the address, then tag it Ship-to, Bill-to, or both. Mark one as the default so\nCarbon pre-fills it on new orders. Radiant uses one HQ address for both roles — the most common\nsetup."],[643,"Type the supplier's lot number from the mill certificate. This lot is now linked to the\nmaterial, so Carbon records which lot the job consumes."],[262,"Type-safe queries with generated types from @carbon/database"],[485,"type: info"],[488,"type: info"],[502,"type: info"],[518,"type: info"],[584,"type: info"],[609,"type: info"],[645,"type: info"],[724,"type: info"],[794,"type: info"],[809,"type: info"],[824,"type: info"],[878,"type: info"],[908,"type: info"],[937,"type: info"],[977,"type: info"],[1002,"type: info"],[1019,"type: info"],[1058,"type: info"],[1066,"type: info"],[1167,"type: info"],[1184,"type: info"],[1243,"type: info"],[1309,"type: info"],[1359,"type: info"],[1506,"type: info"],[1535,"type: info"],[1602,"type: info"],[1633,"type: info"],[1676,"type: info"],[1761,"type: info"],[1778,"type: info"],[1795,"type: info"],[1831,"type: info"],[1837,"type: info"],[1857,"type: info"],[1886,"type: info"],[561,"type: tip"],[573,"type: tip"],[614,"type: tip"],[