 Bill of Material, click Add Material. Pick A36 Steel Plate 1″ (A36-STEEL-PLT-1\".96x240). Carbon fills in the description and unit."],[1591,"Under Routing, click Add Operation. Pick the process Flame Cut and the work center Burn Table — PA2. Carbon assigns it sequence 10."],[160,"Unique Constraints"],[1498,"Unit of measure — EA (Each)"],[623,"Unit price — $0.25 (Carbon pre-fills the last known price)"],[460,"Update entity statuses (consumed entities → 'Consumed')"],[459,"Update item ledgers with deductions (inputs) and additions (outputs)"],[448,"Updates entity statuses (inputs → 'Consumed', outputs → 'Available')"],[742,"Upload the file. Drop in your .csv. Carbon previews the first rows so you can confirm\nit parsed correctly."],[769,"Upload your logo (PNG or SVG). It shows on PDFs and in the top-left of the app."],[912,"upload-3d-model attaches a 3D model to an item so anyone can\nsee the part. The Counterweight Hook already carries one: counterweight hook 3d.stl. The repo\nshows how to upload a model file and link it to the right item."],[277,"upsertCustomerPortal() - Create/update customer portal"],[47,"Upstash"],[70,"Usage"],[90,"Usage"],[200,"Use \"active\" BOOLEAN DEFAULT TRUE instead of actual deletion"],[1526,"Use a material for anything you cut, machine, weld or form from raw stock. Not sure which\nitem type to pick? See defining an item."],[178,"Used descriptive policy names with has_role and has_company_permission functions:"],[434,"Used for backward tracing (where did this come from?)"],[430,"Used for forward tracing (where did this material go?)"],[148,"User-Specific Tables"],[799,"Users & permissions"],[124,"Uses nanostores for global state"],[264,"Uses Remix flat routes"],[179,"Uses standardized policy names (SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE) with helper functions:"],[261,"Uses Supabase client from @carbon/auth"],[983,"Using the API"],[247,"utils - Common utilities"],[256,"utils/ - Utility functions"],[744,"Validate. Carbon checks every row before changing anything — flagging blanks, a missing\nUoM code, or a duplicate readableId. Fix flagged rows and re-upload."],[41,"Vercel Configuration"],[1046,"Verify counts: cycle count"],[1572,"Versions and revisions"],[132,"Views are named in the plural camelCase format (e.g. customers, salesOrders, items)"],[1670,"Want first-article or incoming inspection instead of a final check? Put the inspection operation first in the routing. Same mechanism — only the position changes."],[1890,"Want the wider context? The 15-minute walkthrough runs this exact\nexample end to end, from quote to cash."],[1038,"Warehouses, shelves, on-hand quantities and the item ledger."],[309,"We can also required multiple permissions. In the next example, the user must have the sales_update permission and the users_update permission in order to invoke the action:"],[479,"We learn with a real company"],[306,"We provide a helper function called requirePermissions that can be used to check the user's permissions before making a call to the database. This method is almost always called in an action (data write) or a loader (data fetch)."],[325,"We understand that manufacturers don't often have the luxury of large teams of developers. Often a single software developer will be responsible for many custom applications. Our goal is to provide a simple platform with a single database that manufacturers can use as the heart of their digital operations."],[1855,"We use one real example all the way through — the 500 Counterweight Hooks (part\nCWH-A36-15) Acme made for Radiant Aerospace on sales order SO000069."],[607,"We'll follow a real Acme example: PO000057 to Ryerson for the A36 Steel Plate that\nfeeds job J000097."],[1776,"We'll follow Acme's real quote Q000061: 500 Counterweight Hooks for Radiant Aerospace\nat $73.14 each."],[1051,"We'll follow one item to make it real: Acme's stock of A36 Steel Plate 1″\n(A36-STEEL-PLT-1\".96x240), the raw material for the\nCounterweight Hook."],[1265,"We'll follow one real job: J000097 — 500 Counterweight Hooks (CWH-A36-15) for Radiant Aerospace. It runs three operations in order: Flame Cut → Sandblasting → Inspection."],[1153,"We'll follow one real job: J000097 — 500 Counterweight Hooks for Radiant Aerospace."],[710,"We'll use Acme Inc.'s real data as the example throughout."],[884,"Webhooks, integrations and extending the platform."],[886,"Webhooks: Carbon tells you when things happen"],[19,"Welcome to Carbon"],[1142,"What a job carries"],[657,"What a supplier record holds"],[1248,"What an operator sees"],[1156,"What are we making? The part — here, CWH-A36-15, the Counterweight Hook."],[1255,"What clocking off feeds back"],[1372,"What each Module is for"],[604,"What happens next"],[1,"What is Carbon?"],[1426,"What is Carbon?"],[1436,"What makes Carbon different"],[927,"What MCP is, in one line"],[1239,"What to read off this screen:"],[930,"What you can actually ask"],[1388,"What you do here"],[1803,"What's on a line"],[589,"What's on a purchase order"],[572,"Whatever the supplier types lands straight on the matching record in your Carbon — no copy-paste,\nno typos. Each link is private, so a supplier only sees the documents you sent them."],[1818,"When a customer accepts a quote, you don't re-type anything.\nCarbon copies the lines, quantities, prices, and the linked method,\nand keeps the two records linked."],[606,"When a job needs material you don't have, you buy it with a\npurchase order (PO) — a document that tells a\nsupplier what you want, how much, the price, and when. This page\nshows how to raise a PO, send it, and receive the goods onto your shelf."],[1107,"When a truck arrives with material you ordered, you create a receipt against the matching PO. Carbon already knows the part, quantity, and price — you're mostly confirming reality."],[352,"When a user performs an action that triggers an async event (a job is inserted into a queue), the UI should listen for updates to the table to be updated."],[876,"When Acme posts AR000025, two things move at once so the books always balance:"],[853,"When Acme shipped 500 Counterweight Hooks to Radiant Aerospace, that became sales invoice\nAR000025 for $36,820.00."],[1628,"When an item is ordered (a sales order, or a part needed by a job), Carbon picks how to fill\nthat one line:"],[344,"When making decisions, we aim to optimize for long-term developer productivity. We take it as a given that everyone wants more features. But in order to quickly provide new features over time, we need to make sure that the platform is easy to use and maintain. This may mean that we have a steeper learning curve in the short term, but it should pay off in the long term."],[1234,"When more work wants a machine than it can handle, priority and due date decide the order. Here's Acme's live Counterweight Hook backlog — three jobs for the same customer, stacked up:"],[877,"When Radiant pays, the $36,820 moves out of Accounts Receivable and into Bank - Cash\n(1010). On the buying side it's the reverse."],[1794,"When Radiant says yes, don't rebuild anything. On the quote, click Convert to Order.\nCarbon copies the customer, lines, quantities and prices onto a new\nsales order — here, SO000069 — and the two stay linked."],[1873,"When shipped catches up to ordered, the line is delivered. When invoiced catches up\ntoo, the line is done."],[822,"When someone leaves, deactivate them instead of deleting. That frees the seat but keeps\ntheir name on records they created — like Chase Foster staying attached to\nSO000069 forever."],[1287,"When the count is in, the operator taps Finish. This clocks them off, stops the timer, and marks the operation Done. The good quantity is now available to the next operation — so when Fred finishes Flame Cut, Sandblasting flips to Ready in the blast-room queue."],[1293,"When the inspector clocks off the final Inspection operation, all three steps are Done and all 500 pieces are made. Carbon rolls the job up: the finished hooks are received into inventory, actual cost is locked in, and the job moves to Completed."],[630,"When the order is ready, submit it for approval. Carbon moves it from Draft to\nNeeds Approval — large buys can need a manager's sign-off so nobody accidentally commits\nthe company. Who approves what is set in Users & permissions."],[1068,"When the shelf and Carbon disagree, an inventory adjustment makes Carbon match reality.\nIt writes one ledger entry and posts the value change to the books."],[483,"When you log in, you land on the home screen. Every tile here is a Module — click one to\nstart working in it."],[906,"When you need to do something to Carbon, you use the API. The same API powers the whole app, so\nanything you can do by clicking, you can do with code."],[1335,"When you release a job, Carbon copies the item's method onto it. The job keeps its own copy\nof the BOM and routing — so editing the master method later won't rewrite jobs already running."],[355,"Whenever a row is updated, the data for the page will be re-fetched."],[1160,"Where are we? The status, and how many good pieces are done."],[1216,"Where demand beats supply, Carbon raises a suggestion. For a Buy item, that's a purchase order. For a Make item, it's a job."],[1150,"Where the numbers go next"],[610,"Where this fits. A job (or low stock) creates a need →\nyou raise a PO here → you receive the goods,\nwhich adds them to inventory → the job uses them → the supplier bills you. It's the buy-side\nmirror of the sell-side flow in Carbon in 15 minutes."],[1858,"Where this fits. This is the last leg of selling: Quote → Sales Order → make it → ship\nit → invoice it. It picks up after Sales orders and hands\noff to Accounting."],[522,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[588,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[656,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[699,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[752,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[801,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[837,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[885,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[926,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[985,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[1039,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[1084,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[1141,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[1203,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[1247,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[1299,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[1350,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[1371,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[1428,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[1472,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[1514,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[1560,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[1611,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[1652,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[1704,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[1769,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[1800,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[1844,"Where this lives in Carbon"],[1433,"Who uses which Module"],[4,"Why Carbon"],[1296,"Why clock time at all? Guessed labor is the most common reason a shop loses money without knowing it. When operators clock real time on the MES, your next quote rests on what work actually takes — not a hopeful estimate."],[723,"With items in place, add who you sell to and buy from. Customers come before any quote or\norder; suppliers before any purchase order. Same workflow, two files."],[1882,"With the goods shipped, you can bill. A sales invoice is your request for payment. Carbon\nbuilds it from what actually shipped, so it can't drift from reality. Start it from the order's\nInvoices button."],[692,"With this in place, picking Ryerson on a purchase order line for A36 plate auto-fills the\n$0.25/LB price Acme negotiated."],[357,"Without realtime, this data would quickly become stale. To keep data fresh, the <RealtimeDataProvider> listens for updates to the table and update the nanostore hook accordingly. This means that the data will be updated on every page that uses the hook."],[1691,"Work the overdue list. Filter by Out of Calibration to see what needs attention this week."],[1233,"Work-center rates also cost your jobs. Time booked on Burn Table PA2 absorbs labor at $50/hr and machine at $25/hr — so J000097's cost came from recorded shop time, not a guess."],[1674,"Workflow — the playbook, matched to severity. It lists the required actions you must finish before closing."],[14,"X (Twitter): Follow @carbon_ms for updates and announcements"],[1841,"Yes. A line can ship partially — send what's ready now, the rest later. The line stays To Ship\nuntil the full quantity has gone out. The order reaches Completed only when every line is fully\nshipped and invoiced."],[1136,"Yes. Receipts and shipments are per-line and per-quantity. Receive 30,000 of 54,001 LB today and the PO line stays open for the rest; ship 200 of 500 hooks and the SO line keeps the other 300 open. A line only goes \"complete\" once the full quantity has moved."],[506,"You add a line for the part and quantity; Carbon adds up the material and shop time so you\ncan set a price. When the customer says yes, one click turns the quote into a sales order."],[817,"You add people by email. They click the link, set a password, and they're in."],[847,"You can also see an invoice's status right on the document it came from. Sales order\nSO000069 below is Invoiced and Paid — the same money that became sales invoice\nAR000025."],[1021,"You can call Carbon with raw HTTP, but the official client libraries handle auth, paging,\nand errors for you. Reach for these first."],[1511,"You can create an item — now teach Carbon how to make it and how to keep it in stock."],[1126,"You can only ship what you have. Carbon won't let you ship more than is on hand. Short shipments are fine — the SO line stays open for the balance."],[1408,"You can search three ways:"],[1880,"You can ship a line in more than one go. Finish only 300 of 500? Ship 300 now — Carbon\nrecords a partial shipment and keeps the line open for the rest."],[1425,"You can't get truly stuck — every record is reachable by its number."],[1485,"You describe an item once. After that, Carbon reuses the same record everywhere — so a\nprice fix happens in one place."],[671,"You don't have to fill it all in at once — a name is enough to start. Add the rest as\nyou go."],[1442,"You don't have to learn all of Carbon. Most people live in one or two Modules. Pick the\ntile for the work you do."],[714,"You don't have to migrate history. Most shops bring in master data (items, customers,\nsuppliers) plus a snapshot of opening inventory and any open orders — and leave closed\njobs and paid invoices in the old system. A clean start beats a perfect copy."],[1345,"You don't have to track everything. Turn on batch or serial only where it pays off —\nregulated, high-value, or warranty-sensitive parts."],[1662,"You don't have to use all four tools to start. Many shops begin with one inspection on their most important part and grow from there."],[949,"You don't memorize tool names. You describe what you want; the assistant finds the tools.\nHere are real asks against Acme's data."],[1386,"You don't need every Module on day one. Most people live in one or two. What you can see also\ndepends on your permissions, so your rail may be\nshorter than the screenshots here."],[1468,"You don't need the API or AI features to get full value from Carbon. Day one, you can\nquote, order, make, buy, inspect and invoice entirely by clicking. New to a bolded term?\nEvery one is defined in the glossary."],[879,"You don't need to memorize any of this. Every shipment, receipt and payment lands in the\nfinancials automatically and correctly — no spreadsheet reconciliation, no double data entry."],[1357,"You don't need to read it top to bottom. Skim it once, then look things up as you go. Most pages\nlink their jargon straight here."],[1027,"You get back the same item records you see under the Items module:"],[732,"You import methods with two files, loaded in order:"],[765,"You need an administrator account to change these settings.\nYou can edit most of them later — except your base currency. Pick that one carefully."],[810,"You need to be an admin to invite people. If you set 